Xref: newshost.anu.edu.au aus.org.efa:5914 aus.net.policy:1138

In article &lt;31FC05A5.167E@maths.usyd.edu.au&gt;, Robbie Gates
&lt;robbie@maths.usyd.edu.au&gt; wrote:

# &gt; Dave Nagle wrote:
# &gt; # The difference between a moderator and a censor is that the
# &gt; # moderator seeks out the best, whereas the censor seeks out the
# &gt; # worst.
#
# Jason Stokes wrote:
# &gt; Is this original?  In any case, it's a great, pithy response.
# &gt; Definitely a quote file addition.
#
# i really don't want to get into this debate, but i have to point
# out that best and worst are very relative subjective words. I
# think it was Chomsky who said "Freedom of speech means precisely
# giving free speech to those you despise". i am sure the family
# values bandwagon that the internet legislation was designed to
# please could consider themselves moderators, only allowing the
# best, pure and wholesome contributions to be posted.
#  - robbie

Perhaps I should add - a great, pithy response that, like all pithy
statements, needs a great number of auxiliary premises and background in
order to work.  The vast majority of newsgroups are not moderated - they
are a form of expression open to all.  The question is: are citizens
subject to prior restraint or chilling effect censorship when they try to
post to these newsgroups?  If so, they're not being "moderated" - they're
being censored!

But I acknowledge - the difference between content selection and
censorship *can* get a little hazy.  Fortunately, current government
censorship efforts do not even approach the grey area.

Jason Stokes: j.stokes@student.anu.edu.au

From: danny@cs.su.oz.au (Daniel Yee)
Newsgroups: aus.org.efa,aus.education
Subject: Re: moderation is not censorship
Date: 30 Jul 1996 16:15:27 +1000
Organization: Basser Dept of Computer Science, Uni of Sydney, Australia
Lines: 22
Distribution: aus
Message-ID: &lt;4tk99v$35b@staff.cs.su.oz.au&gt;
References: &lt;4t9v1o$91n@staff.cs.su.oz.au&gt;
&lt;j.stokes-2807961850430001@150.203.109.22&gt;
&lt;31FC05A5.167E@maths.usyd.edu.au&gt;
&lt;j.stokes-3007961225390001@150.203.109.12&gt;
NNTP-Posting-Host: staff.cs.su.oz.au
Xref: newshost.anu.edu.au aus.org.efa:5922 aus.education:4854

Jason Stokes &lt;j.stokes@student.anu.edu.au&gt; wrote:
&gt;But I acknowledge - the difference between content selection and
&gt;censorship *can* get a little hazy.

Yes, things can get hazy even with selection of articles for academic
journals get a bit hazy.  Complaints that journals are favouring
certain kinds of approaches over others, or some people (or countries)
over others are not uncommon.  Of course whoever owns a journal is
entitled to print what they like (?), but the problem is that some
journals have a status due to external forces (ie they are included in
citation listings, or libraries subscribe to them).  Censorship is
definitely a possibility when this is the case.  (It's all very well
being able to publish on the Internet, but if your job prospects depend
on publication in certain journals it doesn't help much.)

&gt;Fortunately, current government
&gt;censorship efforts do not even approach the grey area.

Indeed.

Danny.


</pre>

