<b>References</b>: &lt;Pine.SGI.3.93.960801122927.14374A-100000@world.std.com&gt; &lt;gm0HGem00iVC8_BVkk@andrew.cmu.edu&gt;

Michael Loomis wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; Excerpts from internet.listserv.fight-censorship: 1-Aug-96 Re: Your
&gt; attention please.... by Bob B Chatelle@world.std
&gt; &gt; Jon makes the valid point, which I'm sure Seth agrees with, that different
&gt; &gt; responses are appropriate for state and private censorship.  Most
&gt; &gt; importantly, when dealing with private censorship, one must not run to the
&gt; &gt; government for help.
&gt; 
&gt; You mean like taking Princeton to New Jersey State court for its efforts
&gt; to censor?  I see this demand for state intervention as a perfectly
&gt; appropriate way to deal with private censorship, but I do urge Bob to
&gt; attempt to dissuade those who may wish to take this action.
&gt; 
&gt; Michael Loomis

Thank you for calling attention to the need for clarification.  By running to
the government to help I meant asking the government to intervene in a way
contrary to the First Amendment--e.g. by forcing a newspaper to print something
it does not want to print.  Using the courts is a  perfectly valid way of asking the 
government for help in cases where private institutions are trampling on the First 
Amendment rights of others.  If I didn't believe in the appropriateness of using
the courts, I never would have involved the National Writers Union as a plaintiff
in the suit to invalidate the CDA.  (Granted, this is a case of state censorship.)

Anyway, my original message certainly left me open to misinterpretation.  Forgive
my sloppiness and thank you for calling this to my attention.

Cheers,
Bob

