    <h1>[3388] <a href="dl?thread=GeoCities+kills+web+site+with+drawings+of+male+nudes&after=3388">GeoCities kills web site with drawings of male nudes</a></h1>
    <h2><i>declan@well.com (Declan McCullagh)</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: GeoCities kills web site with drawings of male nudes
<b>To</b>: RBryanRuss@aol.com
<b>From</b>: declan@well.com (Declan McCullagh)
<b>Cc</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>Date</b>: Tue, 6 Aug 1996 23:42:01 -0500
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v01510106ae2dcc02134a@[204.62.128.229]&gt;

Bryan,

I've taken the liberty of forwarding your note, along with my prepended
comments, to the fight-censorship mailing list.

I confess I'm not sure what recourse you have now that GeoCities has killed
your web site's graphics. Their current policy says that "nudity or
pornographic material of any kind" is verboten. Do you have the URLs to
other nude sites that remain on GeoCities?

At http://www.geocities.com/homestead/homeguide.html, I found:

-----------------------------------------------------------------------
The following is a summary of things that are not permitted as part of
the GeoCities free Personal Home Page Program:

1.Material that is grossly offensive to the Web community including
blatant expressions of bigotry, racism, hatred, or profanity

2.Pages that promote or provide instructional information about illegal
activities

3.Pages that promote physical harm or injury against any group or
individual

4.The use of free Personal Home Pages for commercial purposes,
including but not limited to the following:

Soliciting for advertisers or sponsors

Displaying a sponsorship banner of any kind, including those that are
generated by "banner exchange" services

Displaying banners for services that provide cash or cash-equivalent
prizes to users in exchange for hyperlinks to their web site.

Conducting raffles or contests that require any type of entry fee

5.Pages that contain nudity or pornographic material of any kind

6.Pages that exploit images of children under 18 years of age

7.Restricted or Password-only access pages

8.Hidden pages or images (those not linked to from another accessible
page)

9.Use of the page (or directory) as storage for remote loading

10.Use of the page as a door or signpost to another server

11.Use of copyrighted material without the prior permission from the
author
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

What you might want to do is publicize this well, and then move your site
to a less sensitive ISP such as Netcom.

Does anyone else have any insights?

-Declan

------------------

From: RBryanRuss@aol.com
Date: Tue, 6 Aug 1996 20:51:35 -0400
To: declan@eff.org
Subject: censorship at www.geocities.com

Over a month ago I responded to a soliciation for a free personal home page
from www.geocities.com (which is advertised on their home page). They are
promoting theme-based neighborhoods for the home pages. The only content
guidelines were that nothing injurious to any person or group is permitted.
Based on those guidlelines, I felt the server a safe place to display my art
work and I placed my drawings of male nudes on an available address in
GeoCities' WestHollywood neighborhood. I have noticed other sites on
GeoCities with an equal amount of nudity. The only difference was my site
displayed the blue ribbon online freedom icon with a link to the EFF site.

Well, 30 days  and 10,000 hits to my site later (I heavily promoted my site
with listings in many art related directories), I awakened one morning to a
barage of e-mail from people informing me my site had been stripped of all
its graphics--everything from the blue ribbon icon to my nude art work, only
part of which contained male frontal nudity, to the photo of myself
fully-clothed. Later I was to receive an impersonal e-mail notification from
 GeoCities informing me that I was violating their content guidelines which
they now claim prohibit nudity (which I did not find in their posted
guidelines all the while other nude sites remain on GeoCities).

I am very distressed that after all my work and sincere efforts to produce a
tasteful site (which I received many e-mail compliments on wordwide),  I
would have it stripped bare in Nazi style of all the graphics, the essence of
my artistic energy.

Perhaps I have little legal recourse since GeoCities was sponsoring the disk
space (which I credited with their logo and a link back to them). But I do
sense great deception on their part with a theme-based neighborhood like
"West Hollywood", which in the real world is a locale known for its freedom
of expression in art and lifestyles.

R. Bryan Russell


</pre>

