&gt; &gt; sort of convention)
Excuse me?  Last I heard, Feinstein (who wouldn't be caught dead in SD this
week&gt;, was sponsoring the worst censorship bill currently in Congress.  
And, lest we forget, Sen. Exon was (and is) a Democrat.  Sure, there are 
censors in the Republican Party (can you say Christian Coalition?), but 
that's a rather wide brush you're painting the Republicans with.  On the 
net, party lines don't quite fit.  As I think we've discussed here and 
elsewhere, it's net.experience that is the divider.

&gt; &gt; just one more example of how the Internet rots your mind, corrupts the
&gt; &gt; morals of young souls and causes madness and mayhem.
No truer words were ever spoken &lt;g&gt;, speaking as one of the corrupted 
myself... :)

&gt;         But, I'm wondering: how is it possible that, in a country where
&gt; you can buy an AK47 as easily as a PC and modem (more easily?)
Uhhhh... no.  The last time I went to Computer City, I didn't have to 
have a criminal background check or wait five days.  Actually, in VA, we 
don't have to wait 5 days, but that doesn't matter.  Back-of-the-truck 
sales, like you must be referring to, are illegal anyway, and if the 
police would enforce current laws, we might not have to worry about that.

&gt; therefore where there must be a few dozen thousand accidental death by
&gt; weapon every year...
More like &lt;maximum&gt; a few thousand over several years.  Remember, there 
are a hell of a lot more accidental car deaths than accidental gun 
deaths, though.  There's your few dozen thousand.

&gt;         ... so many people think it'd be REALLY kewl to censor the
&gt; Internet, but so few ever realize that guns are ACTUALLY (without any
&gt; extrapolation) dangerous?
Good point.  Guns, though, in a way like computers, require a 
mis-intentioned person to become dangerous.  Computers aren't designed to 
put holes in people or things (as Kurt Vonnegut would say).  In both 
cases, though, an unreasonable person has to make an irrational decision 
in order to cause harm.

