    <h1>[3431] <a href="dl?thread=Clinton+Links+Wiretap+Opposition+to+Gun+Lobby&after=3431">Clinton Links Wiretap Opposition to Gun Lobby</a></h1>
    <h2><i>telstar@wired.com (--Todd Lappin--&gt;)</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Clinton Links Wiretap Opposition to Gun Lobby
<b>To</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>From</b>: telstar@wired.com (--Todd Lappin--&gt;)
<b>Date</b>: Sun, 11 Aug 1996 15:04:54 -0700
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v02140b00ae3407b20dcc@[204.62.133.199]&gt;


Congress may be in recess, but Bill Clinton is still dreaming of expanded
FBI wiretap authority.  In this week's radio address, Clinton sought to
paint the GOP into a corner by depicting the opponents of his
"anti-terrorism" plan as "gun nuts."

Expect the White House to continue beating this drum throughout September.

More detail below.

--Todd--&gt;
-------------------------------------------------------


From: http://allpolitics.com/news/9608/10/clinton.radio/

Full transcript of Clinton's radio address at:
http://allpolitics.com/news/9608/10/clinton.radio/clinton.transcript.shtml


      Clinton: GOP Listening To 'Gun
      Lobby Over Law Enforcement'

      JACKSON, Wyo. (AllPolitics, Aug. 10) --
      President Clinton on Saturday accused the
      Republican-led Congress of hampering efforts
      to fight terrorism by kowtowing to the gun
      lobby.

      In his weekly radio address from Jackson,
      where the president and his family are
      vacationing, Clinton said that Congress had
      stripped his anti-terrorism bill of valuable tools "that law
      enforcement needs to help them find out, track down and shut down
      terrorists."

      The president said that those who oppose two key provisions in his
      anti-terrorism legislation -- broader wiretapping authority and
      marking explosive powder with a "taggant" that can be traced back to
      the dealer who sold it -- were the same who opposed the Brady bill
      and the assault weapons ban.

      [ ... ]

      Negotiations between the White House and Congress for anti-
      terrorism legislation stalled last week over the wiretapping and
      explosive taggant issues. The House later passed an anti- terrorism
      bill of its own that excluded those provisions, but the Senate did not
      vote on the measure before adjourning for its August recess.

      [ ... ]

      "We cannot cast aside any tools in this fight for the security of our
      country and the safety of our people," he said.

      The United States, he said, is not immune to terrorism, citing the
      Oklahoma City bombing and last month's bombing in Centennial
      Olympic Park in Atlanta as "brutal evidence."

      [ ... ]

###








</pre>

