    <h1>[3326] <a href="dl?thread=G7+to+stop+Internet+terrorism&after=3326">G7 to stop Internet terrorism</a></h1>
    <h2><i>Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@eff.org&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: G7 to stop Internet terrorism
<b>To</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>From</b>: Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@eff.org&gt;
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 31 Jul 1996 14:43:00 -0700 (PDT)
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;Pine.SUN.3.91.960731144221.4628B-100000@eff.org&gt;




---------- Forwarded message ----------
Date: Tue, 30 Jul 1996 11:08:00 -0700 (PDT)
From: Bruce Taylor &lt;brucet@well.com&gt;
To: fight-censorship+@andrew.cmu.edu
Cc: brucet@well.com
Subject: G7 to stop Internet terrorism


"G7, Russia Forge Anti-Terror Front"

Reuters reports foreign and security ministers of the G7 countries 
and Russia met in Paris Tuesday 30-July-96 to agree on building an
international front to fight terrorism.  The last two paragraphs 
of the summary:

"Among the measures the ministers planned to adopt was a drive to
prevent terrorists from communicating or sharing bomb-making
instructions over the Internet computer network.

Kinkel [German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel] said Canadian 
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy had told the meeting his 
11-year-old son had shown him how to find such content on the 
Internet."


http://www.yahoo.com/text/headlines/960730/international/
stories/terrorism_4.html

Bruce Taylor
brucet@well.com

</pre>

