Seth's arguments are typical for anti-Libertarians -- that business is
inherantly suspect (and, likely, evil), and that anyone who defends business
is, of course One Of Them (and therefore suspect and likely evil).

Problem with these arguments is that they're more rhetoric than substance,
and when the principles of their side are questioned it's discovered that
there aren't any.

I said "principle." That means the word "Randian" is likely to appear soon.

Let's keep this list about government censorship, please.

AK

