    <h1>[3331] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+Your+attention+please....+(fwd)&after=3331">Re: Your attention please.... (fwd)</a></h1>
    <h2><i>David H Dennis &lt;david@amazing.com&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: Your attention please.... (fwd)
<b>To</b>: ml3e+@andrew.cmu.edu (Michael Loomis)
<b>From</b>: David H Dennis &lt;david@amazing.com&gt;
<b>Cc</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 31 Jul 1996 09:05:30 -0700 (PDT)
<b>In-reply-to</b>: &lt;<a href="/fight-censorship/dl?message-id=4lzq3_a00iWkI1TsVO@andrew.cmu.edu">4lzq3_a00iWkI1TsVO@andrew.cmu.edu</a>&gt; from "Michael Loomis" at Jul 31, 96 09:34:02 am
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;199607311605.JAA14533@remarkable.amazing.com&gt;

&gt;     On the other hand, the owners of this small firm may have
&gt; preferences and in our respect for diversity, we may indeed decide that
&gt; they have the right to their quirks in refusing business.  Further, I
&gt; think it is incumbent on us to be suspicious of the accusations of one
&gt; individual.  We need more evidence before taking such a post
&gt; seriously--some source of information that we know and trust.  Though we
&gt; should welcome Kate's post on this list as piece of information that we
&gt; may wish to keep in mind.
&gt;     This points to a need to distinguish big business from small
&gt; business for our political purposes and to demand liberal policies from
&gt; big business.   We do not have a liberal society, if we do not liberal

Why?

Right now, the situation is that if you want to show your opposition
to censorship, you don't get your film developed at Wal-Mart.  Is that
not the perfect solution?  Wal-Mart pleases its pro-censorship
customers, and you still get your film developed, since there are about
a million places to have it done.

The reason Libertarians focus on government is CHOICE.  You can deal
with Wal Mart or you can deal with Kmart or you can deal with the one
hour outfit around the corner.  Because of that, freedom can survive
any policy of theirs.

But we have only one government; if I want to opt out of the Social
InSecurity system because it's such a horrifyingly bad deal, the
government will say "You can't do that, we're forcing you
to give us this money or we'll lock you up in jail."

There /is/ a fuzzy boundary where there are private monopolies like
the phone company.  We have to deal with them if we want any kind of
phone service, so there has historically been a valid public interest
in regulating them.  But with competition popping up in the most
unlikely places nowadays - including local phone service - that's
becoming less and less true everywhere.

And, just in case you haven't noticed it, you surely can't depend
on government to fight censorship!

D

</pre>

<hr>
    <h1>[3332] <a href="dl?thread=Centennial+Park+bomber+/+security+state&after=3332">Centennial Park bomber / security state</a></h1>
    <h2><i>Josh Crockett &lt;jcrocket@musashi.gsgis.K12.VA.US&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Centennial Park bomber / security state
<b>To</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>From</b>: Josh Crockett &lt;jcrocket@musashi.gsgis.K12.VA.US&gt;
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 31 Jul 1996 13:14:22 -0400 (EDT)
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;Pine.LNX.3.91.960731124130.25584B-100000@musashi&gt;

Since we're way off topic here anyway, I guess I'll add my say.

If in fact Jewel is the bomber, I would tend to see him as a rent-a-cop 
with a hero complex rather than a symbol of the Evil White Male Security 
State.  (BTW, I'm a white male, so that was sarcasm.)  The scenario looks 
to me like:
     12:30 or so  Sets the bomb in place
     12:45 "  "   Lets the other (rent-a-)cops know there's a package
     12:58        Someone (maybe not him) makes the 911 call
     1:25         detonation
We had a situation of a cop with a hero complex at the Hampton (VA) 
Coliseum a couple of years back, at some controversial concert.  He just 
wanted to find the bomb and get famous for supposedly saving lives.

That said, what could happen from this is that he could unwittingly get 
us to lower our expectations of freedom of movement, freedom of 
information, etc.  That's where the security state, J.-Edgar-Hoover-style 
pervasive wiretapping on the net, and censorship come in.  That's 
dangerous, as (I hope) everyone on this list believes.  If we give up our 
freedom, we've let one rent-a-cop gone bad achieve the aims of terrorists 
that are too tactically smart, and too technically sophisticated (with 
respect to explosives), to go after the Olympics with a pipe bomb.

Like people had been saying, you can't completely secure an open area.  It's 
just a fact of life.  I was down in Atlanta three weeks ago, and went to 
a Braves game Thursday night at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium, the 
baseball venue for the Games.  They were searching backpacks of every one 
of the 72 youth and adults we had in our church choir tour group, all 
wearing our tour T-shirts.  If Olympic venue security is anything like that 
tight, and I'm sure it is, I seriously doubt anything will happen to the 
actual event sites.

The danger to the net comes, once again, from technophobic politicians -- 
and even the ones that do appreciate the Net, like Newt, but are facing 
challenges in their races this fall.  Such is life, and like it says in 
the Netizen article from the August Wired (4.08), the Net is a fledgling 
political entity.  We can hope, for now, that the bombing furor dies down 
and DC goes back to gridlock as usual, because if that happens, we may be 
safe for the moment.

And that's all I have to say about that...
Josh Crockett

--
"Relax, Luther.  It's much worse than you think."
	-- Ethan Hunt, "Mission: Impossible"
 
Josh Crockett / jcrocket@gsgis.k12.va.us
http://www.gsgis.k12.va.us/~jcrocket/


</pre>

