    <h1>[3333] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+Your+attention+please....+(fwd)+&after=3333">Re: Your attention please.... (fwd) </a></h1>
    <h2><i>Thomas Grant Edwards &lt;tedwards@src.umd.edu&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: Your attention please.... (fwd) 
<b>To</b>: Michael Loomis &lt;ml3e+@andrew.cmu.edu&gt;
<b>From</b>: Thomas Grant Edwards &lt;tedwards@src.umd.edu&gt;
<b>Cc</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu, tedwards@src.umd.edu
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 31 Jul 1996 15:53:22 -0400
<b>In-reply-to</b>: Your message of "Wed, 31 Jul 1996 09:34:02 EDT."
             &lt;<a href="/fight-censorship/dl?message-id=4lzq3_a00iWkI1TsVO@andrew.cmu.edu">4lzq3_a00iWkI1TsVO@andrew.cmu.edu</a>&gt; 
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;199607311953.PAA07421@kolo.isr.umd.edu&gt;


Michael Loomis writes:
&gt;The Libertarian effort to impugn all government action s evil coercion
&gt;and to regale all private action as beautiful choice is as strained
&gt;as it is tautological.

As a Libertarian, I have to concur in some sense.  Censorship is often
wrong, even if done by private entities.  I refuse to put someone in
jail for refusing to let their computers or printing presses be used by
someone else, however I reserve the right to complain about it and
encourage boycotts.

I think that private electronic censorship is an appropriate topic for
fight-censorship...if we are to get along in a society based on
voluntary action, we need to communicate the deeds we feel are wrong,
even if they are legal.

-Thomas

</pre>

