    <h1>[3336] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+Trueman+responds&after=3336">Re: Trueman responds</a></h1>
    <h2><i>declan@well.com (Declan McCullagh)</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: Trueman responds
<b>To</b>: bill.humphries@msn.fullfeed.com (Bill Humphries)
<b>From</b>: declan@well.com (Declan McCullagh)
<b>Cc</b>: joeshea@netcom.com, fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 31 Jul 1996 20:16:43 -0500
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v0151010cae25b513973b@[204.62.128.229]&gt;

I talked to Trueman today.

He told me Shea's victory was "not unexpected."

"The ACLU did some forum shopping. If I were going to file a suit like they
did, I'd go to Manhattan," he said, adding that NYC is much more permissive
than most parts of the country.

When I told him that Shea rather strongly dislikes the ACLU and refused to
join the ACLU lawsuit, Trueman was incredulous. Said that Shea must have
received some help from the ACLU in preparing briefs or whatnot.

Not quite.

-Declan



Bill writes:

&gt;&gt;David Cassel wrote in response to remarks by the head of the AFA
&gt;&gt;&gt; [AFA Head] Trueman adds:
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; "This is clearly a case of forum shopping. Shea didn't go to Alabama or
&gt;&gt;&gt; Minnesota, he went to Manhattan and found three judges that ruled the CDA
&gt;&gt;&gt; as unconstitutional. When in fact, Manhattan is a cesspool of
&gt;&gt;&gt; pornography,"
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;Like the bluenoses didn't forum-shop when they went after Larry Flynt and
&gt;&gt;the Mapplethorpe collection in Cincinnati, and in the Amateur Action BBS case.
&gt;&gt;
