-----BEGIN PGP SIGNED MESSAGE-----

[Cc'd to Jamie, Hilary, Marc, Rich, and Ingrid in case Declan has decided
that this thread has already gone too far.]

On Wed, 31 Jul 1996, Rich Burroughs wrote:

&gt; (http://www.webcom.com/ezundel/english/sirc/affidavit_of_marc_lemire.html)
[...]
&gt; Does a free speech advocate break into other people's voicemail and delete
&gt; their messages?

In fairness to Marc, I should explain that the Grant Bristow he was talking
about was a government informant. The point of his affidavit was to say he
was set up. You really need to read the whole SIRC report, and all of the
rebuttals on Zundel's web page, the counter-rebuttals on Nizkor, and all of
the press reports if you want to have the foggiest idea what is going on. It
wouldn't bother me one bit if you didn't care to do that, but it would bug
me if you presumed to pass judgement without doing that.

Since we're obviously not going to do that on this list, forget the larger
issues. They do not concern fight-censorship.

&gt; Rich's point is well put, to me.  It's wrong to censor Lemire, and the
&gt; attempts tro censor him should be exposed.  But people should also be aware
&gt; of who he is and what he represents.  I'm guessing that the SWC Canada is
&gt; well aware of Lemire's extracurricular activities, and that those activities
&gt; are at least part of the reason they have tried to silence him.  Whether
&gt; that's right or not (I think not), it's important to understand, IMHO.

Actually, I disagree. Unless you happen to live in Toronto, or to be Jewish,
I see no particular reason to be interested in the larger issues. You can't
expect us as free-speech activists to investigate the background of every
censorship victim.

My point was that absent a THOROUGH investigation, which one usually cannot
do, it is improper to comment on the merits of a particular site, or even to
characterize it in any but the most general terms. 

Wiesenthal Center-Canada (not sure of the position of the US org) wants to
shut down the web site of a political opponent. Wearing our free-speech
activist hat, we can say that that is wrong. But that's all we should say
without donning another hat. 

I apologize to Marc and Declan for bringing in other issues. Backlashes
breed more backlashes. If you're interested in my opinion of and experiences
with Marc, I'd be more than happy to talk to you off the list, but my point
is precisely that such extraneous discussions, for or against any viewpoint,
do not concern fight-censorship.

Some conflicts that hit the internet censorship scene verge on actual
warfare. The Zambia newspaper case, the Basque separatist web site, and this
case are viewed by their participants as real battles. The Wiesenthal Center
probably sees its battle with neo-Nazis as a covert war, and vice versa --
and rightfully so. I know people on both sides who have "gone underground," 
at considerable risk to life and limb. The role of a free-speech/peace
activist in such a situation is to enforce the "rules of war," and try to
foster real discussion. I don't think the Nazis should be excluded from the
political system; I see no reason to wage war on them. Obviously, the
Wiesenthal Center (and a few other groups, but not the ADL or Nizkor)
disagrees. 

[An extreme case to ponder: When the UN coalition bombed and jammed the
Iraqi communications infrastructure, was that censorship? That's how Lemire 
and certain people in the Wiesenthal Center view this "battle."]

- -rich
 [blue-ribbon disclaimer: it's called sarcasm, son, SARCASM]
 censor the internet! http://www.stanford.edu/~llurch/potw2/
 boycott fadetoblack! http://www.fadetoblack.com/prquest.htm

