At 01:28 PM 7/31/96 -0400, sethf@mit.edu wrote:
&gt;&gt; Seth, I'm no libertarian, but I do have a problem with any system that says
&gt;&gt; a private individual or business can't select, edit, censor, or whatever you
&gt;&gt; want to call it. I mean, what exactly are you suggesting?  Would we
&gt;&gt; *require* the operators of web servers to post any materials submitted ...
&gt;
&gt;	There's a whole range of actions that could take place that don't
&gt;*require* anything. The fact that this is an immediate, knee-jerk
&gt;reaction along the same lines, now yet another person, says something
&gt;very significant. As I said, it's a real mental tick. Anytime something
&gt;negative is said about private action, bang, are-you-proposing-to-compel...

But Seth, I think the line must be drawn clearly between public and private.
I don't know that it's 'kneejerk' to make that distinction.

&gt;	We could begin by not having this immediate flaming at the
&gt;critic whenever a business is criticized. Bad publicity can have a very
&gt;potent effect on private conduct, but actions are less likely to be
&gt;changed if any complainant seeking assistance has to pass through a gauntlet
&gt;of "business is holy, how dare you question it".

You certainly won't get that from me. However, when you're discussing an
issue of possible non-government censorship, I think the strategies for
handling differ (as you imply below). Again, the line between public and
private is important, because when you're in the public context of
government & court enforcement, you have force rather than volition, as you
would have in a private context. I'm not behind a libertarian critique of
government enforcement as an inherent evil, but I would certainly agree that
force should be used judiciously, minimally, and would not apply to a
process of selection in a private context that one might construe as censorship.

&gt;	The typical tactics of influencing business are publicity
&gt;campaigns and boycotts. Boycotts are sometimes criticized themselves,
&gt;but for the scope of this discussion, I'll just point out that they are
&gt;a type of private action that doesn't require any government
&gt;intervention, We've got to get past the idea that business conduct can't
&gt;be opposed, and the immediate leap into absurdity at the very thought is
&gt;a symptom of how deeply this blindness is rooted.

Agreed. If, for instance, you think that AOL is committing egregious acts of
censorship and exclusion, drop your AOL account, fuss at/about AOL, but
don't seek government involvement or court resolution.

thx
Jon

--
Jon Lebkowsky           http://www.well.com/~jonl              jonl@hotwired.com

</pre>

