In today's Mercury News
NETCOM SETTLES SUIT WITH CHURCH

Out-of-court deal with Scientologists

BY MARK LEIBOVICH
Mercury News Staff Writer

A lawsuit that many in the online community feared would set a
precedent restricting freedom of expression on the internet was
resolved quitely Saturday in an out-of-court settlement in San
Jose.

Netcom On-Line Communications Services Inc. announced it has
settled the intellectual property dispute initiated by
Religious Technology Center, the publishing wing of the Church
of Scientology.

RTC had brought a claim against Netcom, seeking to prohibited
what is viewed as illegal postings of sacred church writings,
some of which it claimed were protected under US copyright
laws.  Both parties agreed not to disclose specific details
of the settlement.

According to a statement, Netcom as set up a protocol on its
company home page for handling future intellectual property
disputes.

[...]

The full text of the protocol can be found on Netcom's home
page, at
http://www.netcom.com/about/protectcopy.html

[...]

"I would hate to see Netcom be put in the position of having
to police the material posted on its service," says Howard
Rheingold, a well-known digital community guru, and author of
the 1993 book Virtual Community, who is not familiar with the
details of the case.

[...]

