    <h1>[3423] <a href="dl?thread=Washington+Post+letter+by+Sen.+Burns+(8/9/96)&after=3423">Washington Post letter by Sen. Burns (8/9/96)</a></h1>
    <h2><i>Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@well.com&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Washington Post letter by Sen. Burns (8/9/96)
<b>To</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>From</b>: Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@well.com&gt;
<b>Date</b>: Fri, 9 Aug 1996 07:14:01 -0700 (PDT)
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;Pine.3.89.9608090731.A14644-0100000@well.com&gt;

[Burns' letter follows a rather silly editorial in the Post recently on
the dangers of unfettered crypto. --Declan]


---------- Forwarded message ----------
Date: Fri, 09 Aug 96 09:16:56 EST
From:Matt_Raymond@burns.senate.gov
To: declan@well.com
Subject: Washington Post letter by Sen. Burns

     Sen. Burns' letter to The Washington Post today contained something of 
     an error, in case you couldn't tell.
     
     A line from the original letter was deleted.
     
     The line that read, "Second, the administration's proposal to seek a 
     copy of decoder 'keys' for our electronic information is not simply an 
     extension of the groundwork for drastic breaches of privacy rights" 
     should instead read, "Second, the administration's proposal to seek a 
     copy of decoder 'keys' for our electronic information is not simply an 
     extension of current wiretapping authority, it is a drastic expansion. 
     it lays the groundwork for drastic breaches of privacy rights."
     
     Fortunately, the overall meaning of the letter is left largely intact.


[Attached is Burns' letter. --Declan]
   


                      `SPEAKING IN CODE ON THE INTERNET'
   
   Friday, August 9 1996; Page A16
   The Washington Post
   
   
   The Post's editorial July 27 on my Pro-CODE bill to ease restrictions
   on encoded, or "encrypted," computer messages ["Speaking in Code on
   the Internet"] was generally balanced but deleted a couple of key
   points.
   
   First, my bill would not "lift" restrictions on the export of strong
   encryption technology, which is designed to allow people to protect
   their computer files and messages. Instead, it would allow the
   Commerce Department merely to ease export restrictions to a level of
   computer security that it deems is "generally available" in the
   nations we trade with.
   
   This bill does not open the floodgates. Instead, it is an
   acknowledgment of the real world and that high-tech U.S. companies
   must be allowed to compete in an increasingly vital sector of the
   world economy. One trade group stated the United States stands to lose
   $60 billion in market share and 216,000 jobs under the current
   restrictions.
   
   Second, the administration's proposal to seek a copy of decoder "keys"
   for our electronic information is not simply an extension of the
   groundwork for drastic breaches of privacy rights. Imagine a Craig
   Livingstone or an Aldrich Ames being designated the "trusted third
   party" who holds the keys.
   
   Supporters of my bill have never maintained that some criminals will
   not attempt to use encryption to evade law enforcement. But the bill
   is an attempt to address the encryption status quo, not some long-ago
   world to which the FBI would like to return. (FBI Director Louis Freeh
   stated in the hearing July 25 that he would even like to restrict
   encryption imports.)
   
   While the White House indicates it might be willing to give people
   stronger encryption, it insists that the trade-off must be a copy of
   our decoder keys. It's a deal Americans will never accept and a plan
   that has yet to be proven feasible.
   
   Denying millions of law-abiding people the use of a legitimate and
   increasingly necessary security product for "law enforcement" reasons
   is like banning deadbolt locks because they make it a little harder to
   kick down the doors of a few drug dealers.
   
   CONRAD BURNS
   
   U.S. Senator (R-Mont.)
   
   Washington
   
###

</pre>

<hr>
