On Sat, 10 Aug 1996, Declan McCullagh wrote:

&gt; http://interactive4.wsj.com/edition/current/articles/Online.htm
&gt; 
&gt; August 9, 1996
&gt;   
&gt; After Dhahran, TWA, and Atlanta: Who's Afraid of the Big Bad 'Net?
&gt; 
&gt;    By VIVIENNE WALT 
&gt;    THE WALL STREET JOURNAL INTERACTIVE EDITION
&gt;    
&gt;    At 15, Frank Sayre isn't old enough to vote in Canada. Yet, his knack for
&gt;    Internet coding has already earned him some powerful enemies.

I believe this is false. As far as I know, no one has objected, other than
by calling him naive. Frank is on vacation and off the net until early
September, so I imagine the WSJ was unable to reach him for this story. 
People reacted to his action the same way they did to our Zundelsite mirrors
- -- despite the fact that Zundel is just a harmless neo-Nazi propagandist,
while Lemire is a bit more... activist. For *his* side of the story, see
http://www.webcom.com/ezundel/english/sirc/affidavit_of_marc_lemire.html

&gt;    Last month, Mr. Sayre launched a private protest against Web censorship
&gt;    from his home in Smithers, British Columbia. After hearing that a
&gt;    white supremacist site had been ejected from an Internet service
&gt;    provider,

This is false. He heard that they were being protested. Lemire has not been
kicked off. His site remains at http://www.ftcnet.com/~freedom, and the site
that the SWC-Canada was far more concerned about, www.ftcnet.com/~skinhds,
is still online, too. Oddly, none of the stores in the US press even mention
the skinheads site. The initial reports in the Canadian press didn't even
mention Lemire, because it really wasn't about him.

Funny... the Skinheads site admits that they won and will not be censored. 
Take a look at http://alpha.ftcnet.com/~skinhds/ -- "Well my site has
weathered the storm of controversy and is still afloat.  Despite the best
efforts of some of the enemies of free speech my service provider did not
capitulate."

I wonder how long Lemire plans to milk the publicity. Maybe trolling the
Wall Street Journal was enough.

&gt;    the teenager posted the site's entire contents in a
&gt;    compressed "mirror" file... 

This is false. Lemire created and posted the archive, soliciting mirror
sites. The first one online was www.alpha.org, but they've been having
technical problems, so Frank's was announced first. Frank's web page simply
links to Lemire's archive on ftcnet.com. Frank did not compile and is not
distributing the site's entire contents. 

&gt;    Incensed, the province's Attorney General, Ujjal Dosanjh, dispatched a
&gt;    task force to investigate the Web's proliferation of hate speech --
&gt;    something the Canadian government, like its allies in Western Europe,
&gt;    has laws against. 

This is highly misleading; I assume it was taken from either Declan's
article or Lemire's press release, as it shows a lack of understanding of
the political and legal situation in Canada.

I don't suppose the WSJ will admit that they were trolled? Frank has, but I
know that Declan won't. In fact, if it weren't for this sentence and the
fact that I'm Bcc'ing it to Vivian, I doubt Declan would allow this message
to hit fight-censorship at all.

&gt;    One day after a bomb in Saudi Arabia killed several U.S. servicemen and
&gt;    virtually flattened a military base, Sen. Joseph Biden (D., Del.)
&gt;    pushed his proposal to make posting bomb-making information on the
&gt;    Internet a felony, punishable by up to 20 years in jail.
&gt;    
&gt;    "I think most Americans would be absolutely shocked if they knew what kind
&gt;    of bone-chilling information is making its way over the Internet," he told
&gt;    the Senate on June 26. "You can access detailed, explicit instructions on
&gt;    how to make and detonate pipe bombs, light-bulb bombs, and even -- if you
&gt;    can believe it -- baby-food bombs."

...and thanks to Biden, that recipe is now available through thomas.loc.gov.
What a moron.

&gt;    "They might be the lunatic fringe, but they've embraced this technology. A
&gt;    subculture is emerging," says Rabbi Abraham Cooper of the Simon Weisenthal
&gt;    Center in Los Angeles, who recently presented President Clinton with a disk
&gt;    of extremist Web sites, and whose Cyberwatch project monitors extremism on
&gt;    the Web.

No, Cyberwatch does no such thing. It just moans about it, giving no
specific examples. They don't even acknowledge the existence of other
organizations with policies that are both more effective and more respective
of freedom of speech, such as the Anti-Defamation League (which is larger
and older than the Wiesenthal Center, but strangely absent from press
reports of "jewish reaction to hate on the net") and Nizkor (which has far
more experience than either, but isn't jewish).

- -rich

