<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Christopher's Wine and Cigar Club: Arizona Cigar Lovers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H2>Arizona Cigar Lovers Magazine</H2></CENTER>

<P><BR>
</P>

<UL><MULTICOL COLS=2 GUTTER=40>

<P>Close to 30 years ago, a desire to race motorcycles in the vast deserts
of Arizona just outside of Phoenix sparked a brilliant career for a young man. His
profession, though, had nothing in common with dirt, speed and the sun.</P>

<P>At the age of 12, Christopher Gross and his family moved from his
birthplace of Trenton, Missouri, to the Valley of the Sun. His first discovery was,
it seemed, that everyone was out in the desert racing motorcycles. His next door
neighbors had six dirt bikes and Christopher was determined to have one of his own.
Chris went to work at a local restaurant with the single goal of buying a bike of his
own so that he, too, could race in the desert. He soon achieved his objective and
continued to work in local Phoenix restaurants and ride bikes until he
turned 18.</P>

<P>In 1973, at the Adams Hotel in Phoenix, Christophers life would
be forever changed. For it was here that he discovered the restaurant industry was
no longer a means to an end - it had captured his heart and soul and soon became a
passion that would lead him to great things.</P>

<P>Leaving Phoenix to pursue his newfound career, Christopher returned
13 years ago. At that time, the Valley was hardly culinary paradise.  One was hard
pressed to find a restaurant other than the classic American "steak and potatoes"
chain or the American version of a French restaurant, of which Christopher says,
"You never needed a menu one would have Chateaubriand, which was not really French,
and maybe some snails. Basically, every French menu looked the same." However, since
then, the bustling Phoenix economy has brought to life a more discerning palate in its
citizens. The passion that began all those years ago has turned into a remarkable,
award-winning career. Over the last 20 years, his accomplishments have created a
worldwide reputation and earned him the respect of his peers, both nationally and
internationally.  Today, Christopher and his wife, Paola, can be found at the
restaurants, making sure that a unique dining experience continues to await each
guest and taking care of the myriad of problems that occur daily. We caught up
with them one morning.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> What led you to leave Phoenix for Los Angeles?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> The hotel went into Chapter 11, and the whole team went to
Los Angeles. One of the chefs said to me, "If you want to continue in this field, you
should go to Los Angeles." So I went to LA and worked for a few big hotels and small
restaurant, and I ended up at the Century Plaza Hotel. After a year and half, the chef
advised that to further my knowledge I should go to London. He had a connection over
there, and I worked in a small French restaurant for about a year. I then basically
took the Michelin Guide to restaurants in France, and sent out 100 letters to all of
the one-, two-, and three- star restaurants in Paris and waited for responses.
I received a few responses and accepted an opportunity to work at Chez Albert,
a two-star restaurant. I made friends with one of the cooks who went to Lucas Carton.
I was basically an observer there. His father owned a pastry shop in Normandy, and
I went to work there for six months. Then I returned to Los Angeles to work at
LOrangerie, and stayed there about a year and a half. I then worked for three
months for a friend who is a very talented pastry chef, learning things I felt
I needed to know, returning to Phoenix shortly thereafter.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> When and where did you meet your wife?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> I met Paola almost four years ago here at the restaurant.
She was working for a consulting company that was based out of Belgium. Paola would
spend half of her time in the U.S. and half in Europe traveling.  Whenever she was
in town for a month at a time, she would go out to eat every night and continued to
frequent this restaurant more and more.  Over a period of time, we got to know each
other well and were married three years ago.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> When did you smoke your first cigar?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> This is a tough one. My first serious cigar was probably
12 years ago at Le Relais in north Scottsdale. We used to have a few customers who
were cigar smokers come in and they would always have a Monte Cristo or Cohiba and
would leave one for me. I discovered that I enjoyed them more and more, especially
at the end of the night with nice glass of port!</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> What are your favorite cigars?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> A Churchill or that size cigar.  I like Avos or Ashtons,
but is anyone leaves a Cohiba or a Monte Cristo for me, I will very happily smoke
it.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> You now have your cigar bar upstairs from the restaurant.
How did that come about?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> My partner Guy Coscas and I were always looking for extra
space in the building to do private parties. We wanted to have room to hold special
or private parties that would not cause disruption to our regular restaurant guests.
The building was very generous in offering to build this private space, with the
ideal of including a lounge where people could conduct business in private. Of course,
we were all interested in cigars and didnt have a specific place for cigar smokers,
so it basically all came together.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> Do you see the trend in cigars growing?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> I think it will continue to get more and more popular.
People seem to equate cigars to wine. It takes almost as much time to create a great
cigar as it does to create a fine bottle of wine.,  The curing of the tobacco and
craftsmanship all have their own characteristics and different flavors. The wine
trend shows people getting introduced to the many different varieties of wines,
not just the typical Chardonnay or Cabernet. They are enjoying other wonderful
types like Sauvignon Blanc, Viognier, Merlot, Cabernet Franc and many others.
The same is true with cigars.  You dont want to smoke just one kind of cigar.
Different occasions call for different varieties.  I would smoke one type of cigar
in the afternoon, then I would enjoy another at the end of the night with a nice
glass of Port.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> What does a membership in Christophers cigar club
entitle you to?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> It entitles you to come up anytime for lunch and to enjoy the
lounge.  There is also a small media center with a television and VCR if you need to
conduct business.  Members are permitted to purchase wine at reasonable prices
(probably less expensive then anywhere else in town) and store it in their lockers.
If you reserve the room for a dinner for perhaps 20 to 30 people, the savings alone
in the cost of wine come close to paying for the membership.  Each member leases a
humidor that holds 25 cigars and they can come up at anytime and enjoy a good smoke.
Membership also provides the waiving of room charges for parties held in the private
dining room.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> You stated that you tried your first cigar 12 years ago - how
did that come about?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> We were doing a promotion with Davidoff and Baron de Rothschild.
Davidoff was introducing their cigar line, and Zinos and Rothschild were introducing their
wine Mouton Cadet.  One of the general managers for Davidoff was giving a presentation
on how to light a smoke a cigar.  One of the things I most remember was him saying,
"You know Christopher," with a very intense look, "a cigar is like a woman, if you dont
give her attention, shell go out!"</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> I see you smoke Cubans. How do you compare them to other
brands of cigars?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> I think they are little heartier and more robust in flavor.
If you get a really good one, the aroma and flavor are wonderful.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> I understand that your wife, Paola, smokes cigars?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> My wife is obsessed with everything she gets involved in.
She will not get involved unless she knows a lot about it,  Paola has a natural
talent, a  great palate and nose, which has tremendous impact on her ability to
analyze and taste wines.  She felt that she could not buy or sell cigars unless
she knew everything about them.  She studied the subject thoroughly, but did not
leave it at that.  She talked to her friends that smoked cigars, and then ultimately
bought a variety of cigars and literally sat down and smoked them.  Paola analyzed
the aromas and flavors, and then documented all the information so that our staff could
sell them properly.  She has created a document that we put in every cigar box that we
sell that not only gives prices, but describes each cigar as well, allowing our servers
to provide our guests with the information to choose the cigar most suited to them.
</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> Paola, we understand that you smoke cigars. Do you recall having
your first cigar?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> I think it was when we first decided to open the cigar room
upstairs.  It was a bit intimidating.  Never having smoked a cigar, I thought it was
the same as smoking a cigarette.  People often smoke cigarettes when theyre stressed.
And then I discovered that smoking a cigar is pensive, something you think about and
take your time.  You devote 20 minutes to it and it is very relaxing.  I began smoking
cigars a lot and it was fun.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> Is this how you started with wines?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> No, wines I had a passion for right away.  What I could not
understand was the wide variation in pricing.  What helped me the most was
experimenting and tasting the wine.  I just loved it.  And it wasnt simply
drinking the wine, but understanding how it could compliment food, how they
ultimately go hand in hand.  Now I see that the meal is not over when you finish eating.
A great Cigar and a fabulous after dinner drink are the perfect end to a perfect meal.
</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> Do you like Cognacs?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> More Ports and Madeiras.  I enjoy my cigar best with a Madeira.
Madeiras have a little higher acidity and are a little more refreshing. I believe that
cigars tend to dry your palate and that you need to have drinks made from grapes that
refresh you palate.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> How about you Chris?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> I love the smell of Cognac, but I cant drink it.
I get a tremendous headache from it.  Port is far more refreshing; it has more character.
It also has a better finish.  I does not have the intense alcohol in the palette that
Cognac does.  Madeira has many characteristics similar to a cigars in flavor.
</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> You opened A.C.G. (Arizona Caf and Grill) with your partner
Guy Coscas about a year ago wasnt it?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> Yes and on any given night you might see Guy Coscas smoking
a cigar on the patio there, but not inside.</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> How does A.C.G. differ from Christophers?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> It is more American-style, almost a cowboy western steak house.
The restaurant is more family-oriented and offers great steaks, pizzas and a great view
of the city lights.</P>

<P><B>A. (Paola)</B>  We focus on beer there.  Of course we have wine, but
we are trying to concentrate on offering as many different beers as possible.
</P>

<P><B>Q.</B> What is on the horizon for you two in the next couple of
years? How do you see your business and your lives evolving?</P>

<P><B>A.</B> I would think we will continue to grow and expand the business
and persevere in providing our guests with the classic, innovative artistry and cuisine
that has always epitomized Christophers.  Weve been thinking about expanding the cigar
smoking and doing something on the patio when the weather is nicer. We have more of an
outside meeting-type atmosphere on our patio now that it is covered.</P>

</MULTICOL></UL>

<P><BR>
</P>

<P>
