<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Paola Gross: Chile... still hot</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H2>
&quot;CHILE... STILL HOT&quot;<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=+0>by</FONT></I><BR>
PAOLA GROSS<BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=+0>as written for:</FONT></I><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>&quot;ANDRE GAYOT'S TASTES&quot;<BR>
THE WORLD DINING &amp; TRAVEL CONNECTION (FEBRUARY/MARCH 1996)</FONT>
</H2></CENTER>

<P><BR></P>

<UL>

<P>It's hard to believe, but the Chilean wine craze that has hit North America
and England in the recent years hasn't hit Chile.</P>

<P>Traditionally, Chilean wines have been at their best when young and
hearty and the fruit is fresh and delicious. That applies, it seems, for
just about everyone but Chilean restaurateurs. On each and every visit,
I am surprised to look at various restaurant's wine lists that inevitably
feature the same old vintages of tired, fruitless reds and oxidized whites.
I always inquire of the server which are the most recent vintages; it is
those wines I enjoy most because of their vigorous fruit.</P>

<P>On my most recent visit to Chile, I had occasion to conduce a series
of wine service classes for one of the most modern and luxurious hotels
in the country. I was amazed to find improper storage and handling of the
wines. So, even in the best of circumstances, these wines are not given
the full and proper attention in their native land. The good news is that
things are changing fast, with quality players such as Concha y Toro, Santa
Rita and Cousino-Macul, producing small lots of premium wine. These new
wines are emerging from the so-called &quot;$10 good value&quot; range
and entering competition with contemporaries form California and France.
One of the most exciting developments with regard to Chilean winemaking
in recent years has been the influx of capital investment from such French
winemaking superstars as Lafite, Bruno Prats from Cos d'Estournel and Chateau
Margaux.</P>

<P>Here are some contenders stepping into the ring that should have the
longevity and age-ability to maintain their place and not easily fall out
the market for some time to come. (Tasting notes derived from my recent
visit to Chile.)</P>

<P><B>1992 Cousino-Macul, Finis Terrae, Maipo Valley</B><BR>
This is a blend of 50% Cabernet and 50% Merlot. Deep intense purple
hue, medium to full body. On the nose complex: layers of black fruit, aggressive
tannins but round, good acidity and length. Delicious ! $24.</P>

<P><B>1992 Concha y Toro, Cabernet Sauvignon, Maipo, Don Melchor Private Reserve</B><BR>
This wine offers great depth, complexity and elegance. Round firm
tannins with great concentration of ripe fruit. This wine is mouth watering.
$15. </P>

<P><B>1992 Santa Rita Cabernet Sauvignon, Medalla Real, Maipo Valley</B><BR>
Brilliant intense currant fruit on the palate. Medium body with some
herbal nuances, this is a luscious wine. $14.</P>

<P><B>1994 Domaine Paul Bruno Cabernet Sauvignon</B><BR>
The owner of Cos d'Estournel, Bruno Prats and Paul Pontalier, winemaker
of Chateau Margaux, have produced a wine that is supple and elegant with
great vibrant fruit of cassis and plums with a long, smooth finish. $15.</P>

<P>Chile's winemaking is improving every vintage and investments in the
vineyards are paying off. Only time will tell, but the phenomenal growth
of the country in every aspect show nothing but great promise.</P>

</UL>

<HR WIDTH="60%">

<P><B>Back to <A HREF="paola.html">Paola Gross<BR>
</A>Back to <A HREF="http://www.christophers.com">Christopher's Web Site</A></B></P>

