<html>
<TITLE> Mars Rover Fact Sheet</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#8f8fff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00ff00" VLINK="#0000ff">

<h1>
<img align=right src="images/mfexlogo_tiny.gif">
<img align=right src="../images/r7logo_tiny.gif"><br>
<i>Mars Rover Fact Sheet</i>
<hr></h1><pre>
</pre>

<table border=0 cellspacing=20 >

<tr>
<td align=center>
<h1> ROCKY 7<br></h1>
<h2> <i>Prototype</i> </h2><br>
</td>
<td align=center>
<h1>SOJOURNER<br></h1><h2> <i>Flight Vehicle</i> </h2>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td align=center>
<a  href="images/rocky7.jpg">
<img src="images/rocky7_medium.jpg"></a><br>
</td>
<td align=center>
<a  href="images/mfex.jpg">
<img src="images/mfex_medium.jpg"></a><br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Mission Description:</b><br>
On Earth, demonstrate new technology concepts for use
in a long range (50km) traversal across Mars,
scheduled for early in the next decade.
</td>
<td>
<b> Mission Description:</b><br>
During July 1997, explore the terrain of Mars 
within sight of the Pathfinder lander, conducting technology
and science experiments.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=bottom>
<td>
<b> Heritage:</b>
</td>
<td>
<b> Heritage:</b>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i> Mechanical:</i>
Employs Sojourner flight spare wheels and steering struts,
and is approximately the same size.  All other mechanical
designs are new.  
</td>
<td>
<i> Mechanical:</i>
Mobility configuration and general size are drawn from
the <a href="images/rocky4.jpg">Rocky 4</a> prototype.
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i> Electrical:</i>
Employs duplicates of Sojourner flight accelerometers and
quartz rate sensor. All computer components are commercial off the
shelf (COTS).  Some other electronics are custom design, using COTS
parts.
</td>
<td>
<i> Electrical:</i>
Custom surface mount board set using radiation hardened components.
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i> Control:</i>
Currently uses a version of the Sojourner navigation
algorithm, modified to accommodate the different sensors
and steering performance of Rocky 7.
All other on and off-board software is newly developed.
</td>
<td>
<i> Control:</i>
Modified Behavior control navigation algorithm developed for Rocky 4.
All other rover and ground station software is new. 
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Navigation Sensors:</b><br>
Black and white CCD stereo camera pairs, three pairs total: 
front, back, and mast.  Sun position sensor. Quartz rate gyro.  
Accelerometers (3).
Wheel optical encoders.
</td>
<td>
<b> Navigation Sensors:</b><br>
Black and white CCD cameras, and five laser stripe projectors
on front side of vehicle.  Quartz rate gyro.  Accelerometers (3).
Wheel optical encoders. Bump detector switches. 
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Mobility System:</b><br>
Modified six wheel rocker/bogey, with two tandem wheel pairs on one end
and two steering wheels on other end.  Total of eight actuators.
Mechanical coupling of tandem wheels can reduce total actuators to six.
</td>
<td>
<b> Mobility System:</b><br>
Six wheel rocker bogey with four corner steering.  Total of ten
actuators.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Manipulation System:</b><br>
</td>
<td>
<b> Manipulation System:</b><br>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>Arm:</i>
The shorter four degrees-of-freedom (DOF) 
arm stows against the side the chassis and 
can dig, dump, grasp rocks, carry one sample, and point 
an integrated optical spectrometer and its calibration target.
</td>
<td>
<i>APXS deployment mechanism:</i>
A one DOF mechanism for deploying the one science instrument.
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>Mast:</i>
The longer three DOF mast stows in a slot in the solar panel,
can raise a stereo camera pair and filter wheels to 1.4 meters
above the ground, use these same cameras to visually inspect
the entire vehicle, and deploy another 0.5 kg instrument canister
to targets in a large area around the rover.
</td>
<td>
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>



<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Motor Control:</b><br>
Accurate variable rate motion is accomplished with 
Proportional/Integral/Derivative (PID) motor servoing,
Pulse Width Modulation (PWM) of motor currents, 
and optical encoder monitoring of output shaft position.
</td>
<td>
<b> Motor Control:</b><br>
Bang-Bang on/off control of motor actuation is used based
on actuator positions monitored by optical encoders.
No variable rate motion is possible.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Science Payload:</b>
</td>
<td>
<b> Science Payload:</b>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>COTS visible/near-IR reflectance spectrometer:</i>
pointed and calibrated by rover arm; sensitive from 350-850 nm.
</td>
<td>
<a href="http://mpfwww.jpl.nasa.gov/mpf/sci_desc.html#APXS">
<i>Alpha-proton X-ray spectrometer (APXS):</i></a>
Irradiates rocks and
soil and determines their chemical components from the
backscatter signature.  A
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>COTS color filter stereo imager:</i>
Mast mounted CCD cameras with RGB filters.
</td>
<td>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>COTS multispectral close-up imager:</i>
Close focus CCD camera with multi-spectral LED illumination.
</td>
<td>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>Mossbauer spectrometer:</i>
Flight qualified science instrument for measuring iron content
in soils and rocks.  Sometimes attached to rover in place of
close-up imager.
</td>
<td>
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Computer:</b><br>
Commercial 3U VME, 68060 CPU, 100 MIPS
</td>
<td>
<b> Computer:</b><br>
Custom boards with 80C85 CPU, 100 KIPS
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Software:</b><br>
<i>Wind River</i> VxWorks &reg real-time operating system.  
<i>Real Time Innovations</i> ControlShell &reg , 
Network Data Delivery System &reg .
Unix development environment. C++, C, Lisp software.
On-board stereo correlation.  HTML/Java &reg based operator interface.
</td>
<td>
<b> Software:</b><br>
C and assembly.  Unix development environment.  <i>Silicon Graphics</i>
Inventor &reg based operator interface.
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Mass:</b><br>
15.7 kilograms
</td>
<td>
<b> Mass:</b><br>
11.5 kilograms
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Size:</b><br>
60 x 40 x 33 centimeters
</td>
<td>
<b> Size:</b><br>
60 x 40 x 35 centimeters
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Power:</b>
</td>
<td>
<b> Power:</b>
</td>
</tr>

<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>Source:</i>
Rechargeable NiCad batteries, Si solar panel.
</td>
<td>
<i>Source:</i>
GaAs solar panel.  One primary, non-rechargeable battery.
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<i>Usage:</i>
About 35W average.
</td>
<td>
<i>Usage:</i>
About 16W peak. 
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<hr>
</td>
</tr>


<tr valign=top>
<td>
<b> Thermal Protection:</b><br>
Designed with fans to stay below 70 deg C during terrestrial desert testing.
</td>
<td>
<b> Thermal Protection:</b><br>
Employs aerogel insulator to stay above -40 deg C during Mars night.
</td>
</tr>

