<html>

<Title> JPL Rover Science Data Acquisition </Title>

<body BGCOLOR="#8f8fff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00ff00" VLINK="#0000ff">

<center>
<H1>Rover Science Data Acquisition</H1>
<H2> Long Range Science Rover Task</H2>
<IMG SRC="images/r7-spec_medium.gif">
<a href="images/spec-data.gif"><IMG SRC="images/spec-data_medium.gif"></a>

<h2><I>
Technology development to enhance and demonstrate rover-based science
acquisition and data analysis for Mars surface exploration<P>
</I></h2> 
</center>

<HR>

The Rover Science Data Acquistion effort is integrating three science
instrument on the Rocky 7 rover for experimentation with rover-based
in-situ analysis.  These instruments are:<br>

<ul> 

<li><B>
<a href="../technology/spectrometer/homepage.html">Point Spectrometer</a></B> 
- Commerically available visible/very
near-IR (450-850nm) point reflectance spectrometer.  This instrument
is incorported into the the manipulator arm on the Rocky 7 rover as
shown above enabling it to be pointed at rock/soil targets and
includes an integrated calibration target for reference data.  In this
wavelength region different weathering materials can be clearly
identify by their spectra as shown in the figure above.<P>

<li><B>Mast Stereo Imager</B> - A mast and mast mounted imaging system
are being developed to enable the rover to gather panoramic stereo
images from a vantage point of more than 1 meter above the ground.
The imaging system will include two monochrome microvideo cameras and
and filter wheel for broad band red/green/blue imaging enaling
generation of false color images.<P>

<li><B>Close-up Imager</B> - A monochrome microvideo camera will be
used in the development of a close-up imaging instrument for placement
agianst targets to gather close-up imagery with ~50um/pixel
resolution.  The instrument will include an active illumination source
as well as contact sensors to confirm successful emplacement against
target.  This instrument will be mounted on mast and reply on mast
degrees of freedom for placement against targets.  

</ul> 
<HR>

<h4>Related Links</h4>
<ul>
<li><A href="internal/homepage.html">Internal Pages</a>
<li><A href="sag/homepage.html">
  Science Advisory Group (SAG) for Mars Robotic Technology</A>
<li><A href="http://cass.jsc.nasa.gov/pub/publications/psiw/cover.html">
  LPI Planetary Surface Instrument Workshop, May 1995</A>
</ul>

