<html>
<TITLE> Lavic Lake Desert Test Site</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#8f8fff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00ff00" VLINK="#0000ff">

<a  href="images/siteCrater.jpg">
<img src="images/siteCrater_medium.jpg"></a><p>

<h1>Lavic Lake Desert Test Site</h1>
<h4>
Part of the Twentynine Palms Marine Corps base, Lavic Lake is a dry
lake bed bordered by a geologically recent lava flow, and pock marked
by craters created by military practice 
<a href="images/dangersign.jpg">bombing</a>.
</h4>

<hr>
<h2> TEST SITE 1: Tadpole Crater</h2>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr>
<td align=center>
<a  href="images/r7digTadpole.jpg">
<img src="images/r7digTadpole_medium.jpg"></a><br>
Digging evaporites.
</td>

<td align=center>
<a  href="images/r7mastLavic.jpg">
<img src="images/r7mastLavic_medium.jpg"></a><br>
Taking panoramic images.
</td>

</tr>
</table>
<p>

Two feild trips have been made to the northern portion of Lavic lake
in November and December of 1996.  While the first served largely
as a logistics exercise, the second contained several days of experiments
conducted 
<a href="http://wundow.wustl.edu/rocky7/">
in conjunction with a team of planetary scientists</a>.
Among the results were: 
<ul>
<li> Multiple 100-200 meter traverses using sun sensing for heading maintenance.
     (Record distances for Rocky 7.)
<li> The first demonstration of using
     <a href="../technology/panorama/homepage.html">rover mast imagery </a>
     for specification of desired navigation paths,
     <a href="../technology/selfinspection/homepage.html">self-inspection</a>,
     and <a href="../technology/sciimaging/homepage.html">science imaging</a>.
<li> Rover task specification over the internet by scientists at JPL,
  <a href="http://ranier.oact.hq.nasa.gov/staff/Lavery.html">NASA managers</a>
  in Washington, D.C., and school children in Colorado Springs.
</ul>
The December tests were the subject of a NASA/JPL
<a href="http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/releases/rocky7.html">press release</a>.  
All participants may be viewed <a href="participants/homepage.html">here</a>.
Field test notes may be obtained <a href="notes/dec96">here</a>.

<hr>
<h2> PROPOSED SITE 2: Southern Alluvial Fan </h2>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr>
<td align=center>
<a  href="images/site2closeL.jpg">
<img src="images/site2closeL_medium.jpg"></a><br>
</td>

<td align=center>
<a  href="images/site2closeR.jpg">
<img src="images/site2closeR_medium.jpg"></a><br>
</td>

</tr>
</table>
<p>

For tests in May 1997, we are considering a test site on the southern side
of Lavic lake, near the junction of the lakebed, a lava flow, and an alluvial fan.
These tests will extend the performance demonstrated in December in 
several ways:
<ul>
<li> Placement of a
  <a href="http://www.scimedia.com/chem-ed/spec/material/mossbaue.htm">
  Mossbauer Spectrometer</a>
  by the mast. (This science
  instrument will be provided by G. Kligelhofer, Institut fur Kernphysik, Germany.)
<li> One kilometer traversal by the rover.
<li> Use of integrated GPS for rover position measurement
     (not used for navigation purposes).
</ul>
These tests will be open to the press.

