<hr>
<h2>GEOLOGICAL DESCRIPTION</h2>

From <b>Geolology Underfoot in Southern California</b>, R. Sharp and A. Glazner,
Mountain Press Publishing Company, Missoula Montana, 1993:

<blockquote>
Relatively young volcanoes dot the triangular region of the Mojave 
Desert between Barstow, Baker, and Twentynine Palms. Amboy and Pisgah
craters are among the youngest of those youthful volcanoes.  Both
have small craters in their summits, but mainly they are excellent
examples of cinder cones.  Cinder cones are small basaltic volcanoes
that spit songy fragments of basalt lava up to an inch or two in diameter....
Geologists call such material tephra, a term Aristotle used that is
based on the Greek word for ashes.  Tephra refers to any fragmented material
(ash, cinder, or even automobile-sized blocks) that a volcano blows
into the air.<p>

Cinder cones typically appear, erupt tephra for a few weeks or years,
produce lava flows, then stop.   Few ever erupt again.  In most cases,
the next eruption will build a new cinder cone.  The larger tephra blown 
from a cinder cone piles up around the vent to build the volcano; the small
material drifts downwind as a cloud of ash.  Although a strong wind may
shape them, most cinder codes are symmetrical.  After the column of 
magma has blown off most of its gases the tephra eruption ceases, and 
the volcano ends its career by producing a lava flow, perhaps two or three.
Th flows typically burst out of the base of the cone because the pile of loose 
tephra is too weak to support an internal column of magma.  In many cases,
a segment of the cone floats away on a lava flow.<br>

...<p>

Amboy an Pisgah craters stand amid large fields of basalt lava.  Although
the tephra eruptions undoubtedly made good fireworks displays, they were
neither dangerous nor violent -- by volcanic standards.  Basalt flows 
tupically erupt very quietly and predictably.  Contrast that to rhyolite 
eruptions, such as the Bishop tuff from the Long Valley caldera...,
which may devastate a region the size of an average state, and possibly
change the climate worldwide for years.<p>

Most of the basalt flows erupted from Amboy and Pisgay craters have a 
``pahoehoe'' surface.  Pahoehoe, a Hawaiian term, refers to surfaces
that are relatively smooth and locally covered with distinctive ropy
coils.  The ropy texture forms when molten lava beneath rumples a
thin outer skin of hardening rock, much like the surface texture of 
fudge that cools as it is poured into a pan.  Some of the flows have 
``aa'' surfaces, another Hawaiian term.  Aa surfaces are rough, clinkery,
and jagged; they tear your boots.<br>

...<p>

How old are Amboy and Pisgah craters?  No one knows for sure, except
that they are among the youngest volcanoes in Southern California.
They are too young to date by the potassium-argon technique, which can
be used on basalt erupted as recently as about 100,000 years ago.
They may be young enough to date by the carbon-14 technique, which
can be used for samples as old as about 50,000 years.  But geologists
normally use volcanically charred wood for radiocarbon (carbon-14)
dating, and so far no one has found any around either cone.  
Neither volcano shows much evidence of erosion, but that is typical
of cinder cones; the loose tephra absorbs water so well that surface
runoff rarely gullies the surface. Lavas from Amboy Crater are interbedded
at a depth of about 30 feet with lake sediment in Bristol playa ...
that are about 100,000 years old.  So these volcanoes could be 
as much as 100,000 years old, perhaps much younger.<p>

</blockquote>



<hr><h2>FIELD EQUIPMENT</h2>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr>

<td align=center>
<a  href="images/siteCamp.jpg">
<img src="images/siteCamp_medium.jpg"></a><br>
Our home away from home.
</td>

</tr>
</table>
<p>

Our typical complement of equipment includes:
<ul>
<li> Two Sun workstations configured for stand-alone operation.
<li> A satellite modem and dish/transponder for our internet link.
<li> Cell phones and walkie-talkies for communication.
<li> <a href="images/insideTrailer.jpg">Trailer</a>
     for workstations and other equipment.
<li> Motorhome for people and food.
<li> At least 2 four-wheel-drive vehicles.
<li> Telescope/binoculars for viewing Marine bombardments, and stars at night.
</ul>

<hr>
<h2>ROAD TRIP SCHEDULE</h2>
<ul> 
<li> November 1996:  First desert trip.  Logistics and engineering test.
<li> December 1996:  First full scale field demonstration with 
     <a href="http://wundow.wustl.edu/rocky7/">
     participation of planetary scientists</a>.
     (<a href="press.html">press release.</a>)
<li> January 1997:  Demonstration at the
     <a href="http://planetary.org/tps/">Planetary Society</a>
     <a href="http://www.transatlantech.com/TPS/gsp-calandar-rovertour.html">
    Conference on Mobile Planetary Robots, Santa Monica CA</a>
<li> May 1997:  1km traversal test at Lavic Lake.
</ul>

