<HEAD>

<TITLE>Long-Range Science Rover
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>Long-Range Science Rover (LRSR) Task<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Introduction/Rationale:</B>
<P>
This task develops technologies that enable 15 Kg class microrovers
to autonomously traverse many kilometers on a planetary surface
and perform scientist directed experiments and return relevant
data back to Earth. Present microrover technology has several
limitations that preclude more ambitious science rich missions.
Current microrovers have very limited range (10s of meters), are
not capable of sample acquisition and manipulation (i.e., soil
and rock acquisition, subsurface access, pointing and burial of
instruments), have limited science packages onboard, are designed
for short term missions (10 days), require careful and repetitive
ground monitoring and control (limited autonomy). <BR>

<P>
There is great interest in the science community to explore Mars
by landing near interesting geographic areas and moving to pre-selected
targets helping to offset landing errors. It is desirable to place
instruments against outcrops or loose rocks, search an area for
a sample of interest, and possibly collect rocks and soil samples
for return to Earth. Long traverse will provide an opportunity
to make observations and measurements along the way providing
access to a wide variety of rocks from different areas.<BR>

<P>
This task will develop a small prototype rover that will carry
several science instruments. It is envisioned that the mass of
the flight rover will be 7-8 Kg and that of the science payload
5-6 Kg. The challenge will be to increase the science payload
to rover mass ratio and at the same time achieve long-range and
autonomous science experiment goals. This rover will have the
capability to perform macro and micro imaging, visual and near-infrared
spectroscopy, instrument pointing, sample acquisition, and manipulation.
The rover will also carry several yet to be defined science instruments.
This task will emphasize scientist involved field testing and
long traverses so that relevant onboard and ground based automation
tools for realistic surface exploration of Mars are developed.
Ames Research Center is collaborating in this task by providing
virtual reality displays and ground-based science data analysis
and visualization.<BR>

<P>
This task will increase the traverse range of microrovers by 100
times in FY 97, 500 times by FY 98, and 1000 times by FY 99. The
science instrumentation will be increased by a factor of 3 and
4 in FY 96 and 97, respectively. A major contribution of this
task is the development of autonomous science experiments with
and without a lander. Such autonomous operations will increase
the science return per uplink command by a factor of 2-3 in FY
97 and 4-5 in FY 98.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Focus and Direction:<BR>
</B>
<P>
This technology development program combines both research and
actual system demonstrations to advance the existing autonomous
vehicle technologies for future Mars missions. While the primary
focus is research, the planned system demonstrations and scientist
directed field tests provide a means of testing the robustness
of the technology components within a viable mission scenario/environment.
The task will have three distinct components: Rover System; Science
System; and Ground System. In addition to the integrated level-I
milestones described in the following each subsystem will have
its separate level 2 milestones. <BR>

<P>
<B>Major milestones:<BR>
</B>
<P>
<B>FY 1996 (Lander-Based)<BR>
</B>
<P>
Demonstration of a science rover capable of sampling and science
instrument pointing. This demonstration will include:
<UL>
<LI>Integration of at least three science instruments to the rover
(work with planetary scientists to integrate representative science
instruments to the rover). Tight integration of these instruments
to the rover computing/power infrastructure is desirable and will
be pursued)
<LI>On-board science-based autonomy (develop a command language
which enables science experiment related commands to be sent to
the rover instead of a sequence of low-level commands)
<LI>On-board monitoring and confirmation for each science activity
(develop vision and other sensor-based confirmation of test results,
such as confirmation of successful soil sampling, laser-based
verification of spectrometer pointing)
<LI>Navigation capability for long-range traverse via the integration
of a Sun sensor
<LI>Command sequencing and Web-based science target designation
(utilize state-of-the-art software such as Java)
<LI>Terrain map building and use of virtual reality technology
to visualize terrain and science data
<LI>Autonomous position localization from the lander via image
differencing (this plus a Sun sensor will provide rover position
and orientation without the need for previously used color cylinder.
Reduces mass and provides flight compatibility with a solar panel)
<LI>Rover localization via landmarks (extend goal confirmation
so that the rover can determine its position relative to a number
of designated rocks by the operator. This capability is an enabling
technology for long-range rovers for performing site surveys without
a need to use a lander for localization) 
</UL>

<P>
<B>FY 1997 (Rover-Based)<BR>
</B>
<P>
2 km field demonstration of the Long-Range Science Rover (LRSR)
controlled remotely from JPL. <BR>

<UL>
<LI>Scenario will consist of traversing in the indicated direction
and periodically (e.g., every 100 to 200 m) transmitting panoramic
images to the ground station. The ground station will provide
new commands to either continue in the same direction or to change
direction. If the site is of interest to scientists, site survey
commands will be issues.
<LI>Develop panoramic maps (with feature segmentation) and utilize
virtual reality to show a continues motion picture of the traversed
terrain.
<LI>Verify commands automatically for consistency with flight
rules
<LI>Stop at interesting locations (as determined by scientists)
and perform site surveys based on scientist designated targets.
Perform at least two science operations without a need for a separate
lander in these sites (via rover position estimation using landmarks)
<LI>Show ability to fracture rocks and image unweathered surfaces
<LI>Develop laser/stereo/capacitative techniques for obstacle
avoidance and science instrument pointing/emplacement. Perform
experiments to compare the performance of these techniques.
<LI>Show ability to dig and bury a seismometer near the lander
(prior to long-traverse) and confirm that the operation has been
successful. 
<LI>Investigate use of beacons to update rover position relative
to the lander (possibly use GPS to emulate a beacon system). Perform
experiments to show performance of the rover returning to the
lander from 100-300 m traverses. <BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<B>FY 1998<BR>
</B>
<P>
5 km field demonstration of LRSR autonomous traverse and performing
scientific experiments.
<UL>
<LI>Traverse 5 km, stop at five different survey sites (selected
by scientists using descent imagery and rover returned images)
and perform science experiments. 
<LI>Integrate at least two additional science instruments to the
rover
<LI>Demonstrate rover's ability to autonomously perform placing/pointing
science instruments on specific designated rocks/targets via on-board
sensor suite.
<LI>Use on-board traversability analysis for autonomous path planning
to avoid paths not safe for the rover.
<LI>Develop capability so that PIs located in their home institutions
can select science targets and specify experiment parameters utilizing
the WEB. 
<LI>Show rover's ability to return to the lander from 1-2 km traverses
using a beacon system 
</UL>

<P>
<B>FY 1999 <BR>
</B>
<P>
10 Km traverse. Rover performs directed and opportunistic science
experiments based on an onboard knowledge base. 
<UL>
<LI>Demonstrate simple sample packaging capability for return
to the lander
<LI>Show rover's ability to return samples from 3-4 km distances
to the lander 
<LI>Show rovers ability to find science targets of interest (based
on an onboard database) and perform relevant science experiments
autonomously <BR>

</UL>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
