<a name="rdac">

<H2>Ranger Dexterous Arm Control </H2>

The goal of this task is to augment the operational capabilities of the
dexterous arms in the Ranger Flight Experiment.  These new capabilities will
be developed within the framework of Configuration Control, which has been
developed at JPL and selected for implementation on the Ranger arms.
The FY'95 focus was to develop and implement collision detection and
avoidance capabilities for the Ranger arms, and to transfer the software
to the Ranger project.  The FY'96 focus is to develop, simulate and transfer
the automated base placement capability for the Ranger, and to conduct 
experiments to validate the collision detection/avoidance and base
placement capabilities.
<p>

<IMG SRC="http://robotics.jpl.nasa.gov/people/hayati/Quarterly_Reports/ranger.gif">
<!IMG SRC="ranger.gif">

<H3> A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>
<UL>

<LI> Developed optimal base placement algorithm
for automatically selecting Ranger base location that will
assure reachability of task objects and maximize the 
end-effector's manipulability index.
<P>

<LI> At the request of SSL, began implementing a software redesign
to assist integration of obstacle detection and collision avoidance
modules into the Ranger software architecture.
<P>

<LI> Prepared a paper entitled "On-Line Collision
Avoidance for the Ranger Telerobotic Flight Experiment," for
the 1996 IEEE International Conference on
Robotics and Automation.

</UL>

<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>

<LI> Deliver restructured obstacle detection and collision avoidance
software to SSL for integration into the Ranger software architecture.
<P>

<LI> Port the obstacle detection and collision avoidance software
into the JPL RSI laboratory for test and evaluation.
<P>

<LI> Code and test the graphical animation for optimal base placement of
Ranger, and deliver it to SSL.

</UL>

