<a name="ravi">

<H2> Ranger Automated Visual Inspection </H2>

Automated robotic inspection of space platforms such as Space Station is
expected to be an important element to offload time consuming inspection
activities from astronauts.  Jet Propulsion Laboratory recently developed
such a remote surface inspection (RSI) system demonstrated successfully
on the ground in a constrained lab environment. The system, however, needs 
further evaluations/enhancements to be robust for practical use in space 
applications. The objectives of this task are to 1) evaluate and enhance 
the existing JPL automated surface inspection technology to be robust 
under varying ambient sunlighting and also under varying image 
mis-registrations and 2) apply this technology to the Ranger TFX mission 
Phase 3 Visual Inspection Task to assess/validate the telerobotic 
automated inspection capability in real space operation lighting 
conditions. The inspection taskboards will be three-dimensional with 
different surface textures, and will be used for both ground-based 
pre-flight and actual Ranger flight tests. The level 1 milestone for FY'96 
is to deliver an inspection taskboard, inspection scenario, and inspection
task software to University of Maryland Ranger Program for Neutral 
Buoyance tests.
<P>

<IMG SRC="ri.gif">

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI> Completed task plan and workforce staffing.

<LI> Coordinated with the University of Maryland Ranger Program Team to 
define on-board camera/lighting requirements.  At present, we will assume 
that only on/off controllable continuous lighting will be available for 
the actual Ranger flight, which will achieve reduced evaluation/validation 
goals relative to the flight inspection test equipped with electronic 
shuttering/strobe lighting.  University of Maryland may later opt to 
add electronic shuttering/strobe lighting, which is more desirable for
the automated inspection demonstration.

<LI> Coordinated with the Ranger Team to investigate a possibility of using 
on-board image processing hardware/software. We decided not to pursue 
on-board image processing options due to the cost/risk involved.

<LI> Coordinated with the Ranger Team to clarify the currently planned 
ground operation option. The current plan we both agreed upon is 
near real-time remote-site ground operation at JPL.  The "near real-time" 
operation is different from "off-line" operation. Namely, we are not just 
collecting data in the actual Ranger flight for later analysis, but we will 
actually demonstrate a near real-time on-line image inspection (flaw 
detection) capability during the actual Ranger flight (at some lighting 
conditions only). Of course, further careful analysis for the flight data 
collected for all different lighting conditions will be performed in 
post-flight operations. We may later consider a possibility of 
near-real-time on-site ground operation at University of Maryland.

</UL>


<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL> 

<LI> Continue defining on-board and ground-site requirements.

<LI> Define inspection task scenario.

<LI> Perform minor fixes and enhancements required for the evaluation.

<LI> Continue evaluating existing automated visual inspection software.

</UL>

