<a name="lsr">

<H2>Lightweight and Survivable Rover </H2>

<P>
This task develops rover architectures and technologies that
significantly extend planetary surface science options of the Mars
Exploration Program. Specifically, we address the challenge of
developing a 5-to-7 kilogram class rover capable of  diverse terrain
traverses (VL1/2), self-navigable sorties of  multiple kilometers, and
extended operation for months in both equatorial and polar latitudes.
We introduce approaches to volume-and-mass efficient mobility, based
on innovative concepts in wheel design, miniature actuation, chassis
structure, thermal control, sampling mechanization, and
computation-efficient 3-D terrain sensing. These ongoing developments
address Mars Surveyor '01 mission constraints as currently known, and
offer scaleable technology/component solutions for the MSP missions at
large. We conduct this R&D in cooperation with the Mars Exploration
Technology Program, leveraging their developments of new high-capacity
thermal materials, low-temperature batteries, and miniature science
instrumentation. FY96 Level 1 task activities will demonstrate a new
wheeled mobility concept consistent with VL1/VL2 traverse and stowage
of the wheels proper to 1/3 their operational volume. 
<P>



<IMG SRC="lsr.gif"> 

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Developed a new mobility concept and chassis implementation
approaches for novel rover architectures based in collapsible
lenticular strut wheels. The wheels will potentially stow to 30%
deployed volume and are consistent in design with both conventional
four wheel (box) and six-wheel (rocker-bogie) chassis geometry. By way
of scaling reference to prior JPL rover designs:  based on rough cut
mass budget estimates (MFEX reference computing/sensor hardware), this
new mobility design would in rocker-bogie configuration equate to a
vehicle having  8x MFEX rover volume, 2.5x ground clearance, 4x hazard
avoidance threshold  -- from the same stowed rover volume at 70% MFEX
mass. <BR>

<LI>Defined and began hardware development of a new hybrid
point-laser/stereo pushbroom sensor. By comparison to current MFEX
flight design, this new approach potentially affords 100-200x
signal/noise improvement for terrain mapping, thereby finessing the
problem of time-and-power consuming redundant difference imaging to
assure reasonable receiver operating curve characteristics.
Concomitant with reduced power and computational requirements of  a
point versus stripe mapping of terrain, the new sensor will enable the
rover to map its near field and egress continuously at rates up to 6
cm/sec (x15 MFEX stop-and-wait performance) <BR>

<LI>Began design of a novel lightweight, volumetrically compact hybrid
Phase Change Material (PCM) /aerogel warm electronics box (WEB)
structure which will be implemented without jeff-bar pass-through<BR>

<LI>Developed a set of progressive FY96-99 science scenarios and
underlying concepts for quantification of evolving
navigation/terrainability  performance as a parametric function of
rover geometry and sensors. Work this year addresses the problem of
continuous motion traverse (~10m at up to 3cm/sec) to a dead-reckoned
and autonomously localized (by on-board sensing) science target in
VL1/VL2 simulated terrain - using the new mobility design in 4-wheel
configuration. FY97, which graduates to longer range traverse (1-2 km)
with a 6-wheel rover, characterizes sun-sensor based corrective
guidance in geo-transects of a dead-reckoned course, and will provide
a reference model configuration appropriate to known Mars Surveyor '01
science objectives<BR>

<LI>Presented the above and task concepts/plans  to a JPL-internal
1/30/96 Peer Review Board drawn from the line, programmatic (TAP/Code
X), and science exploration (SESP/MEP Code S) organizations. </UL>

<H3>B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL> 

<LI>Provide a brief overview of the task technology plan to the
MarsSWG subgroup on Robotic Science, convening at JPL 2/16/96 (C.
Weisbin), with the goals of soliciting approaches and partnership in
rover science instrumentation and cooperative demonstrations<BR>

<LI>Perform detailed design of the rover collapsible wheel mechanisms
and supporting DC motor actuation<BR>

<LI>Implement algorithms for scan-line processing of the hybrid
pushbroom sensor and validate real-time operability<BR>

<LI>Develop a detailed design for the FY96 WEB configuration,
including cabling access ports<BR>

<LI>Finalize a selection of science instrument(s) and its operational
mode in the FY96-end Level 1 demo. 

</UL>

