<a name="lrsr">

<H2> Long-Range Science Rover </H2>
<p>

This task develops technologies that enable 20 Kg class microrovers
to autonomously traverse many kilometers on the surface of Mars
and perform scientist directed experiments and return relevant
data back to Earth. Present microrover technology has several
limitations that preclude more ambitious science rich missions.
Current microrovers have very limited traverse (10s of meters),
are not capable of sample acquisition and manipulation (i.e.,
soil and rock acquisition, subsurface access, burial of instruments),
have limited science packages onboard, are designed for short
term missions (10 days), and require careful and repetitive ground
monitoring and control (limited autonomy) 
<P>
There is great interest in the science community to explore Mars
by landing near interesting geographic areas and moving to pre-selected
targets to offset landing errors. It is desirable to place instruments
against outcrops or loose rocks, possibly collect rocks for return
to Earth, and search an area for sample of interest. Also, long
traverse will provide an opportunity to make observations and
measurements along traverses and to access a wide variety of rocks
from different regions of Mars.
<P>
The development program is a multi-organizational research activity
involving several JPL technical divisions, industry, and universities.
The technical approach to achieving the above objectives is composed
of a focused research effort covering: 
<UL>
<LI>Autonomous sensing/navigation, 
<LI>Sampling/sensing using a rover attached miniature manipulator

<LI>Integration of relevant science instruments and demonstration
of realistic science missions with scientist participation. 
<LI>Long range navigation (Kilometers) and landerless operation
<LI>Telescience control station, ability to plan science tasks
from scientists' home institutions, distribute return data via
the WEB, and VR visualization of terrain and science data 
<LI>Well integrated system testing and demonstration to ensure
technologies are developed and delivered within the context of
a surface planetary flight program like a Mars sample return mission.
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<B>Major FY '96 deliverables are: <BR>
<BR>
</B>
<OL>
<LI>Improve Rocky 7 performance by increasing its autonomy for
sampling and pointing science instruments (ensure sampling is
performed in scientist designated areas, confirm that sampling
has been successful, identify science instrument pointing locations).

<LI>Improve the mechanical performance of the system by redesigning
the steering and manipulator joints. Increase rover speed for
ground based performance tests.
<LI>Reduce power requirement by lowering computer clock speed.
<LI>Integrate a sun sensor and perform rover navigation using
the Sun to compute rover heading. Perform tests and obtain performance
data.
<LI>Identify at least two additional science instruments and help
integrate them to the rover.
<LI>Develop on-board science data reduction capability. 
<LI>Develop high-level commanding capability based on science
requirements. 
<LI>Perform realistic science missions with scientist participation.
<BR>

</OL>

<P>
<H3>A. Significant Activities and Events During This Period</H3>
<P>
Level 1 milestone completed:
<P>
Rocky 7 rover integration was completed which consisted of an
advanced VME based computing environment (VxWorks operating system
and ControlShell C++ programming tool), an on-board stereo vision
system, a light weight sampling arm with a two-DOF pointing capability
and a two-DOF scoop mechanism, a near IR spectrometer (integrated
to the manipulator arm). 
<P>
The demonstration consisted of an operator developing a science
experiment scenario using lander images and specifying goal points
and experiments to be performed at those goal points. The experiments
consisted of a spectrometer pointing (in at least two goal points),
performing goal confirmation (at least in one goal location),
scooping soil in a designated area, and dumping of the sample
in another specified location. A single uplink command from the
operator control station was sent to the rover. The rover then
used its local collision avoidance capability (using on-board
stereo vision) to traverse to the specified goals. Goal points
are assumed reached when the rover estimates that it is within
20 cm from the goal point. The tests were conducted outdoors at
the JPL Mars Yard. During these tests the rover traversed more
than 200 meters. Rover communicated to the lander via a wireless
modem.
<P>
Goal Confirmation consisted of the on-board vision system searching
a location for a rock with certain dimensions. Positive confirmation
would indicate that the rover had reached its specified goal point.
Soil sampling was accomplished by deploying the manipulator arm,
opening its scoops, and then pressing on the surface to determine
ground height. After scooping some soil and stowing the arm Rocky
7 traveled to the specified location for dumping the sample. The
point spectrometer operation consisted of deploying the arm, then
deploying a special calibration target to obtain images in the
ambient light. Imaging was done after the calibration target was
retracted. A software tool then analyzed the spectrometer data
and positive identification of rock material was demonstrated.
<P>
<IMG SRC="rock7_marsyard.gif">
<P>
<B>Rocky 7 Rover at JPL Mars Yard<BR>
</B>
<P>
Rocky 7 has introduced several important improvements over Sojourner
rover. These are:
<OL>
<LI>Manipulation capability (very light arm, 700 Grams)
<LI>On-board stereo vision capability for hazard detection (reducing
hardware complexity while increasing resolution)
<LI>Reduced actuation while maintaining similar rocker-bogie mobility
characteristics (reduction of mobility actuators from 10 to 8
with possibility of further reduction to 6)
<LI>Autonomous localization of the rover using lander cameras
thus providing the ability to autonomously execute several science
experiments from a single uplink command
<LI>A modern highly capable computing and software infrastructure
to respond to future more complex rover needs using state-of-the-art
real-time software. 
</OL>

<P>
<BR>

<IMG SRC="manipulator.gif"><br>
<B>700 Gram Manipulator Arm and Scooping Mechanism</B>

<P>
<B>Other activities:<BR>
</B>
<P>
JPL participated in a NASA TV special on robotics. During this
hour long program Mars Yard was used to show a four-wheel vehicle
controlled by a local high school students as well as showing
Rocky 7 and a Sojourner model. Operators from the University of
Maryland controlled SCAMP and Ranger Vehicle remotely from JPL.
Donna Shirley and Samad Hayati Described JPL's flight and research
programs for Mars exploration. <BR>

<P>
<H3>B. Plans for next period</H3>
