<a name="nrtd">

<H2>Nanorover Technology Development</H2>

The objective of this task is to develop a very small but
scientifically capable rover system which can easily fit within the
projected mass reserves of future landed missions on Mars and other
planetary surfaces.  These reserves are currently (e.g. Mars Surveyor)
about 1kg and new smaller missions (e.g. New Millenium) may have mass
reserves as small as 100g.  By fitting within the mass reserves, and
by having a very simple interface to the lander, the nanorover can fly
as a secondary payload or as a late addition to the mission.
<p>

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>

<LI> Developed breadboard 25 gram 2-wheeled (tail dragger) mobility
chassis and tested different wheel diameters to assess mobility of
very small rovers in sand.  Concluded that wheel diameters much less
than 5 cm cause dramatic reduction in mobility for this mass regime.
Concluded that small tracked vehicles (as originally proposed) will
entrain material and have low mobility and power efficiency compared
to wheeled vehicles.  As expected, ground pressures should be much
less than 1psi for good performance.  Selected 4 wheel, all-wheel
drive, skid-steered 1-dof-articulated mobility chassis as the best
trade-off of complexity, mass, and performance.
<p>

<LI> After literature review and discussions with Planetary
Scientists, we selected for the science complement an Active Pixel
Sensor (APS) 256x256 silicon microscopic imaging detector with filter
wheel and a near-IR point spectrometer.  These are selected as
low-mass, high science return instruments which can give tremendous
mineralogical data sets and which can be incorporated at moderate cost
and without radioisotopes.  The APS, developed in the JPL Microdevices
Laboratory, offers approximately 100-fold reduction in power
requirement over CCD based imaging, which is crucial for a vehicle
with a 1/2 watt power budget.  It will be equipped with a variable
focus lens which allows imaging from about 2 cm to infinity, with
about 7 microns per pixel microscopic imaging at closest approach.  A
crucial Micro-Electro-Mechanical-Systems (MEMS) component of the
system will be nanoactuated optical elements in the spectrometer which
will maintain proper focus despite the expected 100K temperature
gradients and excursions.  The science requirements of the IR
spectrometer (better than 20 nm of resolution over a range which
includes important bands at 1.4 and 2.3 microns) sets the vehicle scale
at about 10 cm and the surface area of the top (solar panel), thereby
determining the power budget to be about 1/2 watt for more than 4 hours
per day for Mars equatorial missions.
<p>

<LI> Reviewed alternative electronics architectures and
low-temperature packaging technology, and selected the rad-hard 80C51
microcontroller on a kevlar printed circuit board for the electronics.
The kevlar circuit board has adequate structural and thermal
properties to be the frame of the rover and to form the optical bench
of the spectrometer (given the nanoactuation described above).
Additional support chips will include A/D converter and Field Programmable
Gate Array (FPGA).  The initial focus of this activity is to use
commercial parts and package them in a way consistent with operation
under Mars ambient surface conditions.

</UL>


<H3> B. Plans for the Next reporting Period </H3>

<UL>

<LI> Plan to move up demonstration of 25 gram mobility system
performing FY'96 level-2 milestone (originally scheduled for 9/96):
"Demonstrate a nanorover (tethered to off-board electronics but with a
mobility mechanism of ~10 gram mass) performing a realistic mission
scenario in the vicinity of a lander.  This mission will consist of
traverses to targets selected in lander imagery (with traverses
accurate to ~10 cm at 3 m).  The off-board electronics will control
the mobility mechanism based on lander commands and also be able to
perform microscopic imagery (<~100 microns/pixel)".  This experiment/
demonstration will validate the overall mission scenario and mobility
characteristics of the system, especially the ability to accurately
place the science instrument with respect to selected science targets.
<p>

<LI> Finalize design of optics, mechanisms, and electronics in preparation
for submission to printed circuit fabrication by end of April '96.  

</UL>

<H3> C. Schedule </H3>

