<a name="esb">

<H2> Exploration of Small Bodies </H2>
<p>

Future exploration of interplanetary small bodies, such as comets
and asteroids, requires technology development in a variety of
areas.  Landing and operation in the microgravity environment
of small bodies is an extremely challenging problem.  The Exploration
of Small Bodies task will focus on developing the enabling technologies
to accomplish <I>in-situ </I>scientific studies of these interplanetary
objects.  The primary objectives of this task are to develop the
mechanisms to perform landing, anchoring, surface/subsurface sampling
and sample manipulation for a complement of science instruments.
 Five key new technologies will be developed:
<DL>
<DT> Compact Drill Mechanism
<DD>To develop a drill capable of
depths up to a meter, with a total mass of 2 kg and minimal power
usage.  A Sample Acquisition and Transfer Mechanism (SATM) must
be integrated to the Drill within this mass limit.

<DT> SATM
<DD>To develop sampling mechanisms that will not contaminate,
mix nor heat a subsurface sample obtained from a known depth.

<DT> Drill and SATM control algorithms
<DD>These mechanisms must
be operated autonomously, compensating for the unknown material
and incorporating fault tolerant controls.  A key goal is also
to obtain scientific information regarding the substrate sampled,
such as hardness and density, by the use of the embedded control
sensors within the Drill.

<DT> Landing and Anchoring
<DD> The act of landing and staying at
a test site in a microgravity environment is grouped as a &quot;single&quot;
new technology since the methods to absorb impact, accommodate
terrain, compensate for horizontal velocity and anchor are all
interrelated.

<DT> Simulant Test Bed
<DD> The surface substrate must be simulated
to assure the above technologies are relevant.  The task of simulating
a cometary material is very challenging, and near term focus is
on that goal.  Adequate cryogenic simulants as well as ambient
analogs will be developed.<BR>
</DL>

<P>
The Exploration of Small Bodies effort is reported by dividing
it into three task areas:  Drilling and Sampling, Landing and
Anchoring, and Facility Modifications.<BR>
<BR>

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period </H3>

<U>Summary:<BR>
</U>
<UL>
<LI>Task fully staffed.  Lag in personnel availability during
first quarter planned.

<LI>Test lab moved to new facility.  Workstation acquired and
facility modifications in process.  (Move unplanned; net costs
OK since planned workstation at no cost.)

<LI>Coordination with Champollion organized.  Task corroborates
with pre-project &quot;Tiger Team&quot; for landing configurations,
then fabs and tests concepts.  Members from each team attend each
other's weekly staff meetings for efficient focus of tasks.

<LI>Bounding limit requirements for landing baselined (max
velocities, g-forces, etc).

<LI>New Technology Report for Compact Drill Mechanism submitted
to JPL patents organization.<BR>
</UL>

<P>
<U>Landing and Anchoring<BR>
</U>
<P>
A significant activity performed during this reporting period
was the coordination of this task with the Champollion pre-project
organization.  To maintain relevance to this flight program, intimate
coordination is ongoing with the recently formed Champollion &quot;Tiger
Team&quot;.  Landing and anchoring concepts in a cometary environment
are being developed in corroboration with this Tiger Team.  Champollion
resources that will enhance this task in accomplishing its goals
include weekly meetings with staff scientists, experts in navigation,
guidance and control, and the Lander System designers.  This task
will continue on to fabricate and test the one (or possibly two)
most promising landing concepts.  Current models of the topography
of comets results in an extremely challenging problem for landing,
in that the surface may have little &quot;holding strength&quot;
for anchoring up to depths of 3 meters.  The terrain may exhibit
high reliefs and scarps, or may consist of a thin crust over very
large voids.  The latest anchoring concepts that may be developed
consist of mechanisms to provide deep anchorings up to a meter
or more in depth.  An &quot;extendible piling&quot; versus &quot;harpoon
and winch&quot; configurations are currently in design trades.
<P>
The requirements for a representative comet Lander have been determined.
 Efforts in the navigation, guidance and control disciplines have
determined that the Lander must at a minimum have two axis attitude
control.  Targeting will be performed from the mother spacecraft,
and then the Lander will be navigated by &quot;point-and-shoot&quot;.
 Bounding limits of the landing phase will be  6 m/s vertical
and 2 m/s horizontal velocity vectors to a mean surface normal.
 Vertical and horizontal deceleration loads shall be limited to
14 Gs in each vector, to be compatible with a 30 G RMS limit load
negotiated by Champollion with the science payload.  For the purposes
of limiting the design space, the Lander attitude (along the velocity
vector) at the point of contact with the surface is assumed to
be bounded by plus or minus 45 degrees to surface normal.  This
value combines the velocity vector-to-surface components with
the surface topography component.<BR>

<P>
<U>Facility Modifications/Simulant Test Bed<BR>
</U>
<P>
The laboratory move was unplanned in the original Proposal.  This
move was  required because of the change of cognizance for the
task in the JPL organization.  (The original development of the
Compact Drill Mechanism was performed under the Robotic Scientist
Task.)  The lab facilities used for the initial Drill Mechanism
development remains for the Telerobotics Program, while the Exploration
of Small Bodies development testing is being conducted in a new
dedicated facility.  This facility combines the lab space requirements
of the Drill/ Sample Acquisition Mechanisms, Simulation Test Bed
and the Landing and Anchoring development.  The building contains
a high bay for landing simulation testing.  Laboratory upgrades
for this task was previously costed, but the move was unforecasted.
 The cost for the initial move was more than compensated for in
the budget by the unspent planned funds for a Sun workstation,
which was acquired at no cost to the task.
<P>
Development of the comet Simulant Test Bed will be enabled by
the relationship with the Champollion pre-project, with the weekly
access to project scientists and the assurance that the final
product will be relevant.  Simulation of a comet site is considered
a greater challenge than an asteroid site, so in the near term
all focus will be on cometary materials development.  Adequate
simulation and selection of  analogs suitable for room temperature
testing is on-going.  A materials engineering expert is currently
staffed full time to perform this sub-task.<BR>

<P>
<U>Drill and Sampling Mechanisms</U>
<P>
A New Technology Report was submitted to JPL patents organization
for the Compact Drill Mechanism.  Determination of the minimum
thrust forces that will adequately penetrate the upper bound of
the cometary model are being determined analytically, and testing
next quarter will confirm.  This upper bound is modeled as a density
of 2 g/cm3 and a compression strength of 100 MPa.  Selection of
the motors and gearheads for the &quot;next generation&quot; Drill
is currently being researched.  Reducing the power requirements
towards the 10 watt value desired by Champollion will be investigated,
but some testing and analysis suggests the minimum achievable
may be 30 watts.<BR>


<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Initiate detail design of anchoring concepts.  Initiate
fabrication and/or procurement of required mechanisms.

<LI>Perform computer kinematics analysis of baselined landing
concept.

<LI>Initiate software development of &quot;smart drill&quot;
control algorithms.

<LI>Perform mixture of the hard bounding limit of comet materials
in Simulant Test Bed.  Test material properties and compare to
comet model.

<LI>Produce analytical predictions of achievable minimum power
and thrust for effective drilling.
</UL>
 

