<a name="mldm">

<H2>Micro Lander Dexterous Manipulators </H2>

<P>
This task develops new robotic architectures and technologies for planetary
surface science, consistent with mission objectives and constraints of the NASA
Mars Exploration Program. Resulting robots - as integrated with Mars lander or
rover science platforms - will be used to dexterously view, probe, acquire, and
containerize samples for in situ analysis and potential return to earth. Task
technology thrusts include design of scalable, ultra-light arms and actively
powered effectors, the development of new composite robot components and
material forming processes, and the innovation of miniature, high-torque
density solid state motors applicable to wide ranging Mars climates. The scope
of  task R&D is ground laboratory concept demonstrations and the evaluation of
selected new components in realistic Mars environmental conditions. FY96 Level
1 task activities develop and demonstrate a new, all-composite manipulator
under dexterous task space control for representative sampling operations. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="mldm.gif"> 

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Developed a concept design for an all-composite (links and joints) two
meter manipulator having potential to reduce mass 30-40% from the FY95 baseline
3-d.o.f. arm hybrid composite-link/metal-joint architecture. The new arm design
is scalable, and will also be used in related development of  a small
rover-mounted dexterous micro-arm.
<BR>

<LI>Supporting the above, defined a new approach for fabrication and structural
forming of novel high strength composite robotic components based in 3-D air
lay-up carbon fiber and polycyanate post-impregnation. By comparison to
composite components formed in more conventional 2-D materials and resins,
resulting designs are expected to have several-fold greater tensile and
torsional strength/mass, as will be critical to highly loaded composite joint
structures. 
<BR>

<LI>Working with QMI, Inc. (TCA partner), produced the first of a new JPL
segmented-and-reversed stack rotary ultrasonic motor design that potentially
allows higher torque density, lower drive voltages and reduced cost of
fabrication. In related developments, the MIT collaboration (N. Hagood et al.)
produced a new motor eliminating much of the vibration and efficiency loss
observed in their first FY95-end prototype due to poor control of normal axis
tolerancing (which degrades critical rotor-stator interface contact
properties).
<BR>

<LI>With Dr. Eric Baumgartner (Michigan Tech NASA-ASEE visiting faculty
fellow), demonstrated a novel means of arm positioning to a designated sampling
point -- accurate to ~ 5 mm at two meter arm extent. In this machine
vision-based iterative visual guidance technique, all computations are referred
to the camera planes of two wide field stereo CCD imagers -- no prior explicit
calibration of the cameras is required nor is a detailed kinematic model of the
arm needed (thus making the approach of considerable interest in environments
where such modeling is either prohibitive or subject to unpredictable change
due to environmental influences.). This work is summarized by E. Baumgartner
and P. Schenker in a forthcoming IEEE ICRA'96 paper. 
<BR>

<LI>Per report to the September TRIWG meeting, we proposed a derived flight
design of the FY95 Code X concept arm (3-d.o.f. hybrid composite/metal serial
manipulator with DC motors) within an externally-led UCLA Mars Surveyor '98 AO
science response -- the Mars Volatiles and Climate Surveyor (PI, David A.
Paige). We were informed at end-October that the proposal was selected, and
work on flight arm development is now underway by a separate project team with
whom we maintain close working contact.  

</UL>

<H3>B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Develop a detailed mechanical design for the new all composite lander arm
<BR>

<LI>Begin experiments in 3-D composite/polycycanate component fabrication, and
define a testing approach for comparative analysis with respect to 2-D
composite/epoxy structures (environmental concerns potentially include both
thermal shock and UV exposure tolerance) 
<BR>

<LI>Begin environmental testing of available solid state motor (SSM) samples
for characterization of failure modes in temperature and vacuum atmospheric
conditions
<BR>

<LI>Continue related modeling and computer-aided design of SSM material and
structural  parameter optimization, emphasizing the stator-rotor interface
<BR>

<LI>Begin characterization of  SSMs operational properties in no-load and
loaded, open and closed loop control settings.

</UL>

