<a name="vtgg">

<H2> Vision and Touch Guided Grasping (MIT) </H2>
<p>

<H3>Introduction</H3>
This project conducts fundamental research and demonstrations in
the mutually complementary areas of real-time vision and touch
sensing, robust grasping mechanisms, and computer-based grasp
control. It enables autonomous and semi-autonomous grasping tasks
in space of human-fabricated objects (e.g. tools) and natural
objects (e.g. loose rocks) covering a wide range of object size
and geometry. The project will conduct experimental demonstration
of how to acquire and grasp stationary spherical objects and
cylindrical objects using coordinated robotic vision and control
algorithms. It will conduct experimental evaluation of how to use
touch and force feedback to improve the grasping operations. It
will analyze sensitivity of robotic grasp system performance to
object size and geometric features. Investigation of end-effector
design to support these activities will be conducted. The
research will be targeted to planned and on-going missions
utilizing earth-orbiting and planetary surface robotics such as
the remote scientist project. The task is being performed at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and supports the research
of Dr. J. Kenneth Salisbury, Prof. Jean-Jacques E. Slotine,
graduate students, and research staff.  <P>

<H3>What was done this period</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Started developing methods for stabilizing motion of
compliant objects including adaptation to unknown parameters.<P>

<LI>Started developing methods to permit stable control of
yanking of grasped  objects and simple digging actions including
adaptation to unknown parameters.

<UL> The digging issue brought to light the limitations of the
current color-keyed vision system which we are using.  We receive
only center of area and orientation information from the vision
boards.  There is little way of knowing, without some prior
knowledge of the object, where to dig.  The solution of using
touch sensing to build up a topographical map of the object and
surrounding area was explored, but it was found that the sensing
capabilities of the talon were unsufficient for this task in its
current incarnation.  We are currently exploring a new sensor
design which should eliminate this problem. 
</UL><P>

<LI>Set up laboratory mock-up of a planetary surface site
including multiple,  randomly placed rock samples.  
<UL>

Built a "mars-scape" using heavy gravel in a frame with caster wheels to roll
into the workspace.  Considering cleaner injection molding
pellets like the type used in the mock up at JPL.
</UL><P>

<LI>Developed new search algorithms which allowed for cataloging
of multiple objects in the workspace. 

<UL>
Two approaches were taken.  The one currently in use was to
program a simple search at the finite state machine level which
scans the workspace until it sees an object, servos to that
object, records all relevant data, and then continues the search
from where it left off.  Multiple occurrences of the same object
are trivially eliminated using location information.  If two
objects are reported as being within a few centimeters of
each other they are assumed to be the same object.  The second
approach which is currently being developed for future use is
explained <A HREF =
"http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/wam/doc/newsearch_page/feg_newsearch.html">here</A>.
</UL><P>

<LI>Initiated experimental evaluation and demonstration of rock
selection,  quick/slow/shake grasp, and retrieval strategies. 

<UL>
Through experimentation it has been found that various retrieval
strategies are necessary.  Among these strategies are the
following:<p>

1. Simple quick "touch sensitive" grasping.  This involves moving
the end effector to the coordinates given by the vision system
with the hand completely open, and then doing a series of steps
involving closing each finger individually until it hits
something, and then moving up a little.  This method is most
useful for objects sitting on the surface, and is the fastest and
most straight forward of the grasps.<p>

2. Slower "touch sensitive" grasping.  It was found that for
objects with non-optimal geometries for grasping, (i.e. not
having a circular cross-section), it was necessary to slow down
and incorporate a higher number of smaller increments in the
grasp.  <p>

3. For objects partially buried in gravel, adding a simple
shaking motion to the grasp increased the success rate by at
least 75%.  This involved adding a simple linear shaking motion
to the talon in the plane of the object.  The shaking allowed the
fingers to work themselves into the gravel around the object, and
was found to  be preferable to digging given the current lack of
sensory information, and the ease of implementation.<p>

4. Experimentation in digging has brought to light several
issues.  First of all, a more robust end effector was needed than
what we currently had.  Some new talon parts were designed and
fabricated to satisfy this need.  The actual finger design will
have to be modified as well to provide a wide enough surface with
which to dig.  The current fingers are thin aluminum, which has
made the digging action produce rake-type results.  We are
considering a simple "snap-on" attachment which would make the
talon more scoop-like.  Another issue is the need for extended
inverse kinematics, while this is currently more of a detail than
an issue, it would be nice to create a second kinematic mode in
which the endpoint of the last link was set to the finger tips
rather that the middle of the talon so that we could more easily
control the digging motion.  Another issue is the need for real
force control on the talon.  It has been found that without
accurate contact force information, it is very difficult to
determine the nature of the interaction with the ground, and
therefore almost impossible to create a robust system capable of
handling various environments, and most specifically variations
in soil height and density.  The last issue is the need for
better visual information.  Due to the fact that the current
vision system only outputs location, orientation, and approximate
area, determining where to dig is a matter of guess work at this
point, i.e. we try digging 10cm to the left and to the right of
the object.<p>
</UL><P>

<LI>Further analyzed and improved the consistency of the grasping
algorithm. 
<UL>
We have found that while we are able to achieve 100% success for
grasping objects within the workspace, it often takes several
attempts at a grasp before success.  In considering energy
consideration, it would be desirable to minimize the number of
attempts.  To do this we have established various measures on
which to base the graspability of the object.  These include: <p>

1. Location: the center of the workspace being preferable to the
edges, etc.<p>

2. Size: There is a certain optimal size for grasping based on
our hardware, this being objects with a 4cm radius.  Twice that
is too large, and half that is too little.  This information is
not directly available with the current vision system, only rough
estimates based on pixel count are possible at this point.<p>

3. Orientation:  The orientation of the object with respect to
the forearm of the wam when grasping is important due to the fact
that the talon only has three degrees of freedom rather than the
four it would need to grasp at any arbitrary orientation.  Having
the object perpendicular to the forearm is optimal, and parallel
is least optimal.<p> Using these three measures, and associated
uncertainty values, it is possible to create a graspablility
index which is a composite of all three values, and will
approximate the chances of a successful grasp.  We are currently
investigating different models which will be used to provide this
estimate of the possibility of a successful grasp for each
object.  Again, the main limitation here is the vision system.

</UL><P>

<LI>Explored fish-eye vision option. 
<UL>

Experimented with different fish-eye cameras. After some work by the
vision board developer, the system showed reasonable results, but as
of yet has not been implemented as we are exploring the possibilities
of other vision systems.
</UL>
</UL>

<H3>Concerns</H3>
<OL>

<LI>A more flexible vision system may have to be incorporated for
digging and first-try grasping.

<LI>Better contact/touch sensors need to be incorporated into the system.

</OL>
Both of these concerns are being budgeted for in the FY96 contract.



<p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://robotics.jpl.nasa.gov/people/hayati/Quarterly_Reports/ColorBar.GIF" 
WIDTH="638" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<p>
<pre>


</pre>
