<a name="me">

<H2> Mars Exploration (MIT, Brooks) </H2>
<p>

<OL>
<LI> Compliant manipulator
<LI> Real-time vision for outdoor navigation 
<LI> 10 gram rover
</OL>
     
1.  We are working with two versions of the arm.  The first bench 
mounted prototype has continued as our workhorse for developing 
control algorithms, and for testing new wiring schemes.  The second 
version is fully completed mechanically, but awaits new wiring and 
electronics. <P>
     
We have built a high level control system to control the first arm, 
concentrating on reaching. Some biologically inspired "movement 
primitives" have been used to allow the control of all 6 dof with 
simple algorithms. A hierarchical controller is being developed that 
will move the arm around, while at the same time protecting the joints 
from excess torque, responding naturally to collisions, and reacting 
appropriately to touch sensor information at the end effector. The 
early work has also involved some learning of the arm characteristics. 
It is envisaged that this system will provide a robust and stable base 
on which more complicated digging/hammering tasks can be built. <P>
     
In order to fully integrate the second version of the arm onboard the 
tracked vision-based rover we have been developing new, smaller, and 
more robust motor controller boards.  We have completed the new 
schematic design for these boards while completely maintaining 
software compatibility, halving their size, and increasing their 
electrical robustness. <P>
     
     
2.  We have significantly extended the programs running on the second 
generation vision system on our tracked robot. We now have three 
parallel vision operators running, and a very robust navigation 
system based on that visual input.  We have tested the system 
extensively, mainly in our indoor planetary surface testbed,
but also some outdoor testing.  We have completed an
initial analysis of the performance of the vision system. <P>
     
     
<H3>January -- March 1996</H3>
     
<OL>
<LI> We will lay out the new control boards, fabricate them and will 
start the installation of the second arm in the rover.  We will 
continue to develop control algorithms on the first arm and 
demonstrate some visually guided manipulation.
     
<LI> We will carry out more outdoor testing of the vision and 
navigation system.  We will run first test on our new third 
generation low power vision system.
     
<LI> We will begin a new task; the design and fabrication of a 10 gram 
micro-rover.  During these three months we will investigate
sources of parts for a demonstration system, investigate thermal 
and electrical constraints, and produce an initial design, with 
performance estimates.
</OL>



<p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://robotics.jpl.nasa.gov/people/hayati/Quarterly_Reports/ColorBar.GIF" 
WIDTH="638" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<p>
