<a name="rams">

<H2> MicroTelerobotics & Medical Applications </H2>

This task is a cooperative NASA-Industry effort to develop a telerobot for
breakthrough micro-and-minimally invasive surgeries. The resulting Robot
Assisted
Microsurgery (RAMS) workstation, via computer enhanced controls, will enable
new procedures beyond human manual dexterity, and allow a broader group of
practitioners to successfully deliver needed healthcare services at reduced cost.
Surgical applications include the eye, ear, nose, throat, face, hand, spine, and
brain. NASA-JPL's role is to design, fabricate, test, and document an
engineering R&D prototype -- a six degrees-of-freedom, position and force
scaling master-slave telemanipulator -- capable of relative positioning of 20
microns over a 10-to-20 cm*3 continuous volume (e.g., the eye).  The industry
partner, MicroDexterity Systems, Inc., working through independent funding,
defines medical requirements, collaborates in system engineering design,
develops and tests a pre-commercial clinical prototype, and with end market
support certifies and commercializes a final design. <P>

JPL successfully demonstrated a robot slave engineering
prototype in FY 1994, and in FY 1995, a master arm capable of simulating a
force feedback environment and manually controlling task space position of the
slave. In FY 1996, JPL will add the capability of force-reflection to the
master arm from a sensor on the slave arm, enable the handling of surgical
instruments and demonstrate a realistic microsurgical procedure using the
telerobotic system. Further growth master-slave system capabilities include
textural
feedback at the master, and <i>in situ</i> imaging at the robot slave.
Beyond its medical significance, this new MicroTelerobotic system has potential
dual-use in ground-to-orbit and thermal-vacuum applications that include
EVA/IVA telescience and telemedicine, safe bio-and-materials processing,
micro-mechanical assembly, small-instrument servicing, and terrestrial
environmental testing. <P>

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events </H3>
<UL>
<LI> <I> Program Planning and Administration: </I> Changed program plan to
include
the demonstration of a realistic microsurgical demonstration as the FY 96 Level 1
milestone for the task. FY 96 work, staffing and budget plans were submitted
and approved.<P>
The previous plan proposed:
<UL>
<LI> Completing slave clone fabrication, assembly, integration, test and
demonstration.
<LI> Completing detail slave design documentation.
<LI> Instrumenting the slave arm for force feedback to the master arm and
demonstrating direct and virtual force feedback over a nominal 10:1 dynamic
range of .5 - 5.0 oz. and integrating and evaluating tremor compensation
[LEVEL 1 milestone].
<LI> Beginning development on multi-mode <I> in-situ</I> imaging functions for
end of attached tool instrumentation.
<LI> Beginning development of supervisory control modes of the telerobot system.
</UL>
<P>
The new plan will:
<UL>
<LI> Complete slave clone fabrication, assembly, integration, test and
demonstration.
<LI> Complete slave detail design documentation.
<LI> Demonstrate an integrated master-slave telemanipulator
performing a calibrated microsurgical procedure with controlled incisions
into soft media, guarded teleoperated control and coordinated surgical instrument
handling. Capabilities to be implemented for the demonstrations include
direct and virtual force feedback over a nominal 10:1 dynamic range of .5 - 5.0 oz.
and integrated tremor compensation [Level 1].
<LI> Conduct medical lab testing of robot performance (with MAB backing).
<LI> Develop a master clone (and integrate with slave clone if slave is at JPL).
</UL>
<P>
The new plan is contingent on final approval of the current task budget.
<P>
<LI> <I>Second slave arm prototype:</I> Procured, fabricated and partially
assembled
sub-systems of the slave prototype-2. Late delivery of vended items has delayed
integration and test of the prototype. Procured items will be delivered in
mid-February leading to late February completion of the prototype integration
and test.
<P>
<LI> <I>Slave detail design documentation: </I> Detail mechanical drawings
(77 in number) have been generated. Descriptions of the software architecture,
and details on the Graphics User Interface, communication and real-time
control and
configuration software have been written. Parts and vendor lists tabulation
are in
progress as are the sections on the electronics hardware and servo-control
sub-systems.
<P>
