<a name="ravi">

<H2> Ranger Automated Visual Inspection </H2>

Automated robotic inspection of space platforms such as Space Station is
expected to be an important element to offload time consuming inspection
activities from astronauts.  Jet Propulsion Laboratory recently developed
such a remote surface inspection (RSI) system demonstrated successfully
on the ground in a constrained lab environment. The objective of this task 
is to apply this technology to the Ranger TFX mission Phase 3 Visual 
Inspection Task to assess/validate the telerobotic automated inspection 
capability in real space operation lighting conditions. To achieve this
evaluation objective, we will perform pre-flight, on-orbit actual flight, 
and post-flight experiments. The degree of success of the task depends 
upon how well the pre-flight baseline experiment and its predictions agree 
with real flight experiments, using performance metrics such as flaw size and 
flaw contrast under various sunlight and mis-registration conditions. 
Post-flight will provide lessons learned. The level 1 milestone for FY'96 
is to deliver an inspection taskboard, inspection scenario, and inspection task
software to University of Maryland Ranger Program for Neutral Buoyancy tests. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="ri.gif">

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI> Defined onboard and ground requirements for Ranger flight inspection
in coordination with the University of Maryland Ranger Program Team.
For now, we assume that only on/off controllable continuous lighting is 
available, which will achieve reduced evaluation goals (camera electronic 
shuttering with strobe lighting may be available later). For the Ranger 
flight experiment/demonstration, we will support near-real-time remote-site 
(JPL) ground image inspection (flaw detection), without onboard
image processing hardware due to the cost/risk involved.

<LI> Defined inspection task scenario. It consists of initial calibration
and actual inspection (flaw detection) phases. The initial calibration 
procedure is essential in the Ranger flight inspection task, because 
"unflawed" and "flawed" images need different camera arm locations, requiring 
accurate camera arm positioning to align the "unflawed" and "flawed" images.
The two quadrants of the taskboard will be used for "unflawed" images and 
the other two for "flawed" images, eliminating procedures for attaching and 
detaching flaws during the Ranger flight experiment. One set of the 
unflawed/flawed quadrants will be used for 2-D surface marking tests and 
the other set for 3-D surface structure tests, during the actual inspection 
phases after the initial arm calibration.

<LI> Completed task re-planning to meet with a reduced budget guideline.
The on-going "evaluation of the automated inspection software" work is now 
moved to the newly created RSI Technology Transfer Task. The planned
"enhancements of the automated inspection software" work is now deleted.

<LI> Presented the task overview/status in the Ranger Integrated Design 
Review (IDR) at University of Maryland.

</UL>


<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL> 

<LI> Design/fabricate taskboard. Two copies of the inspection taskboard will 
be made: one for pre-flight ground test and the other for Ranger Neutral
Buoyancy test. See the description above in "Defined inspection task scenario".

<LI> Develop inspection task software. NDDS will be used for data communication
between University of Maryland and JPL. Satellite up/down link will be used
for transmission of video images. JPL will control video compression
parameters to obtain higher quality image during inspection.

</UL>

<H3> C. Schedule </H3>

<IMG SRC="ri_schedule.gif">

