<a name="lmma">

<H2> Low Mass Muscle Actuators </H2>

<H3>MILESTONE: </H3>

<UL>
<LI>i-PMMA, which was reported to have a very high electrostictive 
	coefficient, will be tested to form a baseline (April 96).</LI>
<LI>Develop methods of introducing electrodes to produce 
	actuators (July 96)</LI>
<LI>Investigate alternative ESP actuators (Aug. 96)</LI>
<LI>Analyze muscle Configurations to effectively harvest ESP actuation 
	capability (Aug. 96)</LI>
<LI>A selected muscle mechanism will be produce to demonstrate a 1-DoF 
	arm with ESP actuator (Sept. 96)</LI>
</UL>

<H3>ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</H3>

<UL>
<LI>i-PMMA was processed, formed as a .2 mm thick film and was
electroded to allow electro-activation.   A strong actuation
characteristics was observed.</LI>

<LI>A series of commercially available materials were selected for
a parametric study of the properties that are responsible to
electrostriction in polymer.  This includes the tacticity, dipole
moment, and the  dielectric constant of the pendant group [The
basic mechanism of electrostriction in organic polymers is
presumed to be related to the polymer structure, i.e., a backbone
(a polymer chain) with pendant groups  (elements with a strong
dipole moment) attached to the backbone.]</LI>

<LI>Compact, low voltage electronic driver was develop to actuate
the ionic Perflurinated Solfonic Acid films.</LI>

<LI>Interdigital electrode were introduced on Kapton films to
examine the capability to design polymer muscles,  the precision
that can obtained in spacing electrodes and the quality of
adherence between the metallic  electrodes and the polymer
substrate as well as the mass producibility of the concept of
polymer muscles.</LI>

</UL>


