<a name="lsr">

<H2>Lightweight and Survivable Rover </H2>

<P>
This task develops rover architectures and technologies that significantly
extend planetary surface science options of the Mars Exploration
Program. Specifically, we address the challenge of developing
a 5-to-7 kilogram class rover capable of diverse terrain traverses
(VL1/2), self-navigable sorties of multiple kilometers, and extended
operation for months in both equatorial and polar latitudes. We
introduce approaches to volume-and-mass efficient mobility, based
on innovative concepts in wheel design, miniature actuation, chassis
structure, thermal control, sampling mechanization, and computation-efficient
3-D terrain sensing. These ongoing developments address Mars Surveyor
'01 mission constraints as currently known, and offer scaleable
technology/component solutions for the MSP missions at large.
We conduct this R&amp;D in cooperation with the Mars Exploration
Technology Program, leveraging their developments of new high-capacity
thermal materials, low-temperature batteries, and miniature science
instrumentation. FY96 Level 1 task activities will demonstrate
a new wheeled mobility concept consistent with VL1/VL2 traverse
and stowage of the wheels proper to 1/3 their operational volume.
<P>
<IMG SRC="lsr96.jpg"> <BR>

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Developed a detailed design for the first rover to be built
in this task, &quot;LSR-1&quot; as shown in the CAD graphic above.
This 100 cm long vehicle has 20 cm diameter wheels of 8 cm width,
70 cm track, and 30 cm belly-pan clearance. It will carry both
front and rear science trays; the front tray will eventually host
a light micro-sampling arm from the Micro Lander Dexterous Manipulators
task, and the rear tray will be deployable to ground level thereby
enabling release, emplacement and/or recovery functions. Each
tray is approximately 33 cm wide, 15 cm long, and 12 cm high.
As further discussed below, the LSR-1 primary chassis is an integrated
structure/thermal design affording considerable weight savings.
The overall vehicle design is scaleable, being primarily limited
at the lower end by Warm Electronics Enclosure (WEE) volume, and
at the upper end by launch vehicle mass/volume stowage constraints.
We have capped the FY96 implementation at 7 kg (with science),
per JPL Program Office request (C. Weisbin). The mobility vehicle
proper will weigh 6+ kg, and carry as its first science instrument
for the Level 1 Sept '96 demo an integrated APS imager/near-IR
spectrometer package. LSR with fully collapsible running gear will 
flexibly stow at dimensions comparable to the Mars Pathfinder Rover 
(MFEX) while deploying to approximately 1.8x linear dimensions of 
same. Hence LSR-1 will have a much improved terrainability that 
enables not only VL1, but also VL2 class missions. [We note in passing 
that a number of JPL personnel attended a recent NASA Ames hosted 
Mars Sample Return Science Workshop (cf. MarsSWG/S. Squyres) of 
March 25-27, 1996. The preliminary consensus of the three science 
communities present (climate-life-resources) suggests that areas of 
interest for rover-based sample acquisition and traverse could be 
highly variable and challenging -- ranging from lakebeds, to volcanic 
terrain and highland features]. LSR-1 is estimated, in flight configuration, 
to carry up to 2 kg of science in each of its front and rear trays. Compare
this projected LSR capability to MPF/MFEX planned operations at
11+kg gross vehicle weight, with a 1 kg science APXS payload.
<BR>

<LI>Made significant progress on all aspects of vehicle design:
1) MOBILITY: The new collapsible wheel design was finalized, with
some revisions for torque, as well as tension-compression loading
factors, and started to fabrication. We selected motors and gearheads
(with a credible path to MSP '01 flight from these lab models)
and started procurements of same. We also began preliminary concept
development for the collapsible rocker-bogie assembly (an early
FY97 integration, with the FY96 vehicle to use rigid lightweight
Al spars) and initiated contact with several proprietary vendor
sources for component materials; 2) CHASSIS/THERMAL: A novel approach
to chassis implementation has been developed wherein the WEE thermal
structure interior walls integrate a distributed load bearing
sheet-and-spar mechanical structure capable of carrying all suspended
mass (the WEE proper, overhead solar array, attached science trays
&amp; payloads, etc.). This hybrid aerogel/Phase Change Material
(PCM) WEE thermal design (glass epoxy walls) has been reduced to a 
33x33x14 cm*3 exterior dimensions layout incorporating computing,
batteries, telecommunication components, and interface to the
rocker-bogie running gear pivot. An innovative feature of this
thermal/structural chassis is complete elimination of the conventional
Jeff-bar WEE pass-through and its concomitant 30-40% heat losses;
rather, the rocker will pivot in an external 3-D composite mount;
; 3) COMPUTING: We established a WEE configuration for the MFEX
80c85 board set (&quot;EM brain&quot; as provided by MEP) that
will serve as our FY96 computing baseline. We also began a straightforward
port of existing code to a 80486 development environment, with
the intent of implementing an evolved 32-bit architecture by early
FY97 (utilizing MFEX I/O, modified logic, and processor retrofit
to a smaller form factor - cf. TRIWG LSR FY97 proposal and our
interaction with MPF/MFEX developers to establish this potentially
inexpensive, and early flight-targeted option for '01 MSP higher
performance sensing/navigation/control); 4) NAVIGATION: The primary
bottleneck to navigational speed in MPF/MFEX sensor-based obstacle
detection is the power cycling requirements of the sequentially-scanned
five laser stripers and subsequently repeated stereo CCD sensor
readout (to obtain an ambient light image for background differencing,
given the laser stripes are insufficiently bright for direct detection).
As such, MFEX travels stop-and-wait at an average .3-.4 cm/sec;
if the rover lasers could be fired/sensed in parallel, much higher
rates of egress would potentially be possible. To this end, we
are developing a spot-pushbroom sensing approach (viz. spots are
read-out over only a few, versus hundreds of CCD scan-lines as
projected lateral spot pattern &quot;pushes&quot; forward), initially
based in a five-laser/CCD direct projection configuration (FY96),
with planned growth to a lower power and more highly resolved
multi-spot/APS based implementation (FY97). Potential speed-ups
-- with high optical conversion efficiency and supporting computational
capability -- could approach 20X MFEX average speed, and enable
continuous egresses. Even with the baseline 80c85 computing implementation,
we project improvements to the 1-3 cm/sec range (though not necessarily
continuous traverses). During this period we have developed a
first cut implementation of the direct spot projection system,
algorithms, real-time 80c85 implementation, and begun testing
and optical system characterization. We have also initiated design
of a multi-spot system utilizing high-efficiency diffraction grating
projectors. This optical characterization work has advanced our
understanding relative to earlier MPF/MFEX-related R&amp;D, and
includes our generalization of the mathematical imaging model
for laser beam detectability to include bi-directional reflectance
distribution functions (BDRF) for representative particulate surfaces
(wherein we have drawn on serendipitous photometry literature
from planetary geology that arrive at better substantiated results
than the conventional Lambertian assumption of MPF). Interestingly,
the BDRF-based models predict relatively more light will be reflected
back at the camera than by assumed Lambertian means; this suggests
further reduced power requirements. However, our experimental
studies to date of focus and power transmission through the train
of laser collimating optics show far from optimal performance;
thus, we are investigating further, including use of new optical
components for improved collimation and reduced laser housing
backscatter.<BR>

<LI>Presented the LSR task concepts/plans to a JPL-internal 1/30/96
Peer Review Board drawn from the line, programmatic (TAP/Code
X), and science exploration (SESP/MEP Code S) organizations --
and -- responded to a request from SESP/MEP to assess the achievable
relative science payload as a function of LSR scale (See FY97
TRIWG LSR proposal discussions and tables therein). We also presented
related information to a February 9, 1996, meeting of the MarsSWG
subgroup on Robotic Science at JPL(M. Carr/USGS-ad hoc Chair).
Based on general outcomes of these discussions, the LSR team arrived
at the above described LSR-1 vehicle target design for a FY96
Level 1 demonstration, with the following milestone [NOTE: We
have chosen to implement a six-wheel rocker-bogie configuration
as the first LSR-1 prototype at given 6+ mobility mass target,
believing it offers better terrainability as a function of fixed
stowage (collapsed) volume versus other configurations. We also
examined some four wheel design options, which may be particularly
attractive if the direction of later developments are toward scale/mass
reduction -- which could be quite significant if more of the vehicle
electronics is run at ambient, thus minimizing or altogether eliminating
WEE sizing constraints]:

</UL>

<P>
<I><B>FY96 Level 1</B>: Develop, demonstrate, and evaluate for
local area science sorties (10 m dead-reckoning, MarsYard) in
various VL1/2 class terrain, a new volume-efficient rover mobility
design - of 20 cm wheel diameter, the collapsible wheel proper
stowable to ~30% active volume -- which can egress at average
1-to-3 cm/sec rates under visual hazard detection/guidance by
a novel spot-pushbroom hybrid laser/stereo sensor. Statistically
characterize navigational system performance relative to the MFEX
baseline [science: imaging sensor/near-IR point spectrometer (JPL)]
9/96</I> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<H3>B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period</H3>

<UL>
<LI>Finalize LSR-1 vehicle detailed design and mechanical/electrical
interfaces
<LI>Test, characterize, and finalize the LSR-1 motors and gearing;
fabricate the first wheel prototype
<LI>Fabricate and test major structural components of the WEE
and attached interfaces
<LI>Complete optical design upgrades, implementation, and characterization
of the LSR-1 spot-pushbroom sensor system; begin operational subsystem
testing using the Rocky 3 platform as a test mule (with reference
to MFEX stripe-laser data earlier derived on same)<BR>

</UL>

