<a name="lrsr">

<H2> Long-Range Science Rover  (LRSR)</H2>


This task develops technologies that enable 20 Kg class microrovers
to autonomously traverse many kilometers on the surface of Mars
and perform scientist directed experiments and return relevant
data back to Earth. Present microrover technology has several
limitations that preclude more ambitious science rich missions.
Current microrovers have very limited traverse (10s of meters),
are not capable of sample acquisition and manipulation (i.e.,
soil and rock acquisition, subsurface access, burial of instruments),
have limited science packages onboard, are designed for short
term missions (10 days), and require careful and repetitive ground
monitoring and control (limited autonomy) 
<P>
There is great interest in the science community to explore Mars
by landing near interesting geographic areas and moving to pre-selected
targets to offset landing errors. It is desirable to place instruments
against outcrops or loose rocks, possibly collect rocks for return
to Earth, and search an area for sample of interest. Also, long
traverse will provide an opportunity to make observations and
measurements along traverses and to access a wide variety of rocks
from different regions of Mars.
<P>
The development program is a multi-organizational research activity
involving several JPL technical divisions, industry, and universities.
The technical approach to achieving the above objectives is composed
of a focused research effort covering: 
<UL>
<LI>Autonomous sensing/navigation, 
<LI>Sampling/sensing using a rover attached miniature manipulator

<LI>Integration of relevant science instruments and demonstration
of realistic science missions with scientist participation. 
<LI>Long range navigation (kilometers) and landerless operation
<LI>Telescience control station, ability to plan science tasks
from scientists' home institutions, distribute return data via
the WEB, and VR visualization of terrain and science data 
<LI>Well integrated system testing and demonstration to ensure
technologies are developed and delivered within the context of
a surface planetary flight program like a Mars sample return mission.
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<B>Major FY96 deliverables are: <BR>
<BR>
</B>
<OL>
<LI>Improve Rocky 7 performance by increasing its autonomy for
sampling and pointing science instruments (ensure sampling is
performed in scientist designated areas, confirm that sampling
has been successful, identify science instrument pointing locations).

<LI>Improve the mechanical performance of the system by redesigning
the steering and manipulator joints. Increase rover speed for
ground based performance tests.
<LI>Reduce power requirement by lowering computer clock speed.
<LI>Integrate a sun sensor and perform rover navigation using
the Sun to compute rover heading. Perform tests and obtain performance
data.
<LI>Identify at least two additional science instruments and help
integrate them to the rover.
<LI>Develop on-board science data reduction capability. 
<LI>Develop high-level commanding capability based on science
requirements 
<LI>Perform realistic science missions with scientist participation.
<BR>

</OL>

<P>
<H3>A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Detailed plans for this task were developed and reported in
an internal JPL task review meeting.  This meeting was Chaired
by Chuck Weisbin and had several senior JPL managers as review
panel members.  Subsequent to the meeting, the panel issued its
finding about the task which very positive. It also had technical
and programmatic suggestions for improvements.  A response is
due May 15, 1996. The review material is available for interested
parties on hardcopy.
<LI>New joints have been built and are being integrated to Rocky
7.  These will replace the manipulator and steering joints. Same
type of joints will be used to develop the mast this year.
<LI>A WEB based interface using JAVA language has been defined
and a first version is available for testing. This tool allows
any individual with a browser that supports JAVA to design and
upload science target and waypoint information for the rover.
Currently, two images are provided to a user. One image gives
the elevation map generated from a panoramic image.  The center
of this image is the last location of the rover. Wedges represent
an area where stereo correlation information is available. Actual
images for each wedge is displayed in a second window. Waypoint
designation and target selection can be done by using the tool
bar.  Editing of the entered information is possible using standard
cut and paste and dragging operations. If you have JAVA click
here to see the &quot;public version of this interface): <A HREF="http://robotics.jpl.nasa.gov/tasks/scirover/operator/wits/index.html">Web Interface for Telescience (WITS)</A>.
This interface will be used in a mid year demonstration to drive
Rocky 7 in JPL MarsYard.
<LI>A command interpreter using the lisp language has been designed
and currently tests are in progress. This adds sequencing capability
and conditional execution of various commands to the rover.
<LI>An approach for science instrument pointing has been developed
that uses the vision system to determine whether it is safe to
deploy the arm to collect images for the science instrument (point
spectrometer in this case) as well as determining the rock surface
tangent so that the images are taken perpendicular to the rock
surface. Similar vision based techniques are being developed to
identify flat surfaces for soil sampling and check for arm collision
avoidance with rocks. In addition a vision based differencing
technique is also being developed to confirm the existence of
soil samples in the scoops. 
</OL>

<P>
<H3>B. Plans for next period</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Integrate the new arm with Rocky 7 and update control gains
<LI>Develop and test a new rover localization technique that is
compatible with flight rover configuration (alternative technique
to the color cylinder)
<LI>Test new autonomous science instrument and soil sampling techniques
<LI>Complete WEB based ground control station for lander based
operation and test the rover in MarsYard using the WEB based interface
<LI>Test the integrated system in MarsYard (repeating FY 95 Level-1
milestone with new interface, new localization technique, and
improved hardware and software) <BR>

</OL>

