<a name="aerobot">
<H2> Planetary Aerobot Testbed </H2>
<p>

The primary purpose of the Planetary Aerobot Testbed (PAT) is to develop
the telerobotic technologies necessary to fly autonomous, robotic 
aerovehicles (aerobots) in the atmospheres of Venus, Mars, Titan and the 
Outer Planets. 

An aerobot is capable of one or more of the following activities:
<UL>
<LI>Autonomous State Determination.
<LI>Periodic altitude variations where altitude, amplitude and period 
are design variables.
<LI>Control of altitude and following a designated flight path within
a planetary atmosphere using prevailing planetary winds.
<LI>Landing at a designated surface location.
</UL>

This activity focuses on the development of balloon 
aerovehicle robots for Venus and Mars. In addition to the telerobotic
technologies, PAT will demonstrate new science techniques such 
as imaging from a balloon in FY96. 
<p>

FY96. First reversible fluid balloon altitude control manual operation
demo; first Venus autonomous balloon navigation sensors prototype
flight demos; high resolution balloon imaging demonstration.
<p>

FY97. First reversible fluid balloon autonomous flight demo; first
Mars autonomous balloon navigation sensor prototype flight demos.
<p>

FY98: First reversible fluid balloon autonomous landing demos; complete
first earth balloon global planning model development.
<p>

FY99: First global balloon flight navigation demos; Complete
first Mars/Venus Global Planning Models. 
<p>

<H4> A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period. </H4>


There has been considerable progress in the Planetary Aerobot Testbed (PAT) development this last quarter.  Two of the tasks currently supported by the Telerobotics Program are the Venus Sensor and Perception (VESPER) and the Buoyancy Control Subsystem (BCS).

<H4> Buoyancy Control Subsystem (BCS) </H4>

The PAT BCS is a unique mobility system being developed to further the 
exploration of planetary atmospheres and surfaces.  An aerobot BCS will 
allow science packages to be placed in the atmosphere of places such as 
Venus or Titan, and then to be flown at different altitudes, landed at 
specific sites, or guided to different regions in the atmosphere under 
autonomous control.
<p>

The system currently being developed under the Telerobotics Program for 
operation within the Earth's atmosphere consists of a primary balloon 
with Helium lifting gas, a secondary balloon for the reversible fluid, 
and a pressure vessel/heat exchanger system designed to allow control of the 
fluid phase.  The operation subsystem will enable the verification of 
complex dynamic, thermodynamic and aerodynamic models which will eventually 
adapted to Venus and Titan.  Experience gained in the manual operation of 
the BCS in FY96 will enable the autonomous operation and control of PAT in 
FY 97.
<p>

This quarter various subsystem-level configurations have been studied and 
down-selected to two potential configurations, differing in the number of 
valves required.  The components have been initially sized.  The heat 
exchanger material is either a mylar/polyethylene or nylon/polyethylene 
composite film, heat-sealed together to form the heat exchanger 
passage-ways.   Cut-down system components, including a parachute and 
laser-initiated reefing line cutters have been identified.  Various 
light-weight latching valves have been identified and tested.
<p>

The PAT BCS will begin integration and testing mid summer 1996 for a 
September 1996 first launch.  The PAT BCS team at JPL includes Eric 
Slimko, Matt Heun and Jack Jones from Mechanical Engineering, and Andre 
Yavrouian from Thermal and Propulsion Engineering.  
<p>

<H4> Venus Sensor and Perception (VESPER) </H4>

The VESPER subsystem achieved a significant technical
milestone last quarter - the end-to-end integration and demonstration
of an inertial attitude estimator for use in the testbed gondola. This 
is obviously of some significance to the PAT project, but may also be of 
interest to the larger community as is discussed below.
<p>
First, the technical details: 
<p>
  Signals from the inertial sensors (rate gyros) were amplified, conditioned
  and provided as differential inputs by the Venus Sensor & Perception 
  (VESPER) subsystem to the Robotic Controller subsystem's Analog-To-Digital 
  (A2D) converter via an 8x1 multiplexor (MUX).  The Controller, a PC104 bus 
  based 33 MHz 486/387 Intel microprocessor system, controlled the A2D device 
  as well as the MUX selector digital i/o interface using the real-time 
  operating system VxWorks (Version 5.3), and the advanced real-time software 
  framework ControlShell (Version 5.1). The attitude quaternion was 
  graphed in real-time using the Stethoscope tool-kit while the rate-gyro
  fixture was put through various test rotations. 

<center><p><A HREF="pat_inertial_estimator.jpg"><IMG SRC="pat_inertial_estimator.jpg" 
ALT="Aerobot Attitude Estimation"></A></center>



From a project perspective, this milestone provides early validation
of PAT's choice of computing platform, hardware bus, i/o architecture, 
operating system, and software tools. Any technical uncertainty in 
the remaining integration efforts involving the Real-Time Controller 
has been greatly reduced, giving us more confidence in meeting the
objectives of this years program.
<p>

From an institutional perspective, this milestones marks the first 
validation of the PC104/Intel/VxWorks architecture for a robotics 
application at JPL. Hitherto, our experience has been with 
VME/Motorola/VxWorks (e.g. Rocky7, Hazbot, RAMS) configurations which have 
limited, expensive hardware selections for embedded applications where 
small size is important. The PC104 standard and the Intel microprocessor 
represent a small, rugged, and inexpensive computing platform with a wide 
variety of cheap peripheral components. Our other experiences have been 
with custom architectures (e.g. Rocky3, MFEX, STAR) with low-end 
microprocessors and/or simple or no operating systems. The ability to use 
the VxWorks operating system outside of the VME/Motorola architecture 
increases our confidence in providing the benefits of a high-end operating 
system to a number of new demanding applications. At the same time, this 
enables a development approach that preserves our significant investments in 
existing VxWorks software and systems expertise. For those applications 
choosing to leverage the strong re-use features built into ControlShell, 
porting of code modules between applications becomes especially easy, even 
trivial, for all non-device-driver code. 
<p>

This successful effort represents a team effort by J. (Bob) Balaram, Mark 
Long, and Robert Scheid from the Automation and Control, and 
Phil Salomon and David Zhu from the Avionics Equipment.
<p>


<H4>C. Schedule.</H4>

Key milestones.

<UL>
<LI> Perception System Hardware/Software Integration (5/96)
<LI> Buoyancy Control System Component Fabrication (6/96).
<LI> Buoyancy Control System Integration & Test (8/96)
