<a name="nrtd">

<H2>Nanorover Technology Development</H2>

The objective of this task is to develop a very small but
scientifically capable rover system which can easily fit within the
projected mass reserves of future landed missions on Mars and other
planetary surfaces.  These reserves are currently (e.g. Mars Surveyor)
about 1kg and new smaller missions (e.g. New Millenium) may have mass
reserves as small as 100g.  By fitting within the mass reserves, and
by having a very simple interface to the lander, the nanorover can fly
as a secondary payload or as a late addition to the mission.
<p>

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>
<UL>

<LI>Performed FY'96 level-2 milestone (originally scheduled for 9/96):
"Demonstrate a nanorover (tethered to off-board electronics but with a
mobility mechanism of ~10 gram mass) performing a realistic mission
scenario in the vicinity of a lander.  This mission will consist of
traverses to targets selected in lander imagery (with traverses
accurate to ~10 cm at 3 m).  The off-board electronics will control
the mobility mechanism based on lander commands and also be able to
perform microscopic imagery (<~100 microns/pixel)".  This experiment/
demonstration was performed on 1/24/96 using the breadboard 25 g
2-wheel rover developed in the first quarter, and validated the
overall mission scenario and mobility characteristics of the system,
especially the ability to accurately place the science instrument with
respect to selected science targets.  <p>

<LI> Developed breadboard 4 wheel, all-wheel drive, skid-steered
1-dof-articulated rocker-bogie mobility chassis.<p>

<LI> Designed science instrument using a camera based on an Active
Pixel Sensor (APS) 256x256 silicon microscopic imaging detector with
filter wheel and a near-IR point spectrometer based on a concave
holographic diffraction grating.

<LI> Identified a vendor capable of producing a custom
Micro-Electro-Mechanical-Systems (MEMS) component of the system, a
nanoactuator for the slit focus of the spectrometer which will
maintain proper focus despite the expected 100K temperature gradients
and excursions.  Issued Purchase Order for custom design.<p>

<LI> Designed electronics based on the rad-hard 80C51
microcontroller, Field Programmable Gate Arrays, and other flight-qualified or
qualifiable parts.<p>

</UL> 

<H3> B. Plans for the Next reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI> Integrate breadboard 4-wheel mobility chassis with off-board electronics
and rerun level-2 demonstration to refine navigation algorithm and do
performance evaluation.
<p>

<LI> Finalize design of optics, mechanisms, and electronics and submit
to fabrication in May/June '96.  <p>
</UL>

<H3> C. Schedule </H3>

<IMG SRC="nrov_sch.gif">

