<a name="esb">

<H2> Exploration of Small Bodies </H2>

<H3>A. Technology Development Summary (FY 96/97) </H3>

Develop enabling technology to perform <I>in-situ</I> scientific
exploration of comets and asteroids.  This technology will also
have some applications in planetary and satellite exploration.
Key areas of development:

<UL>
<LI> Lightweight, low power drill with low reaction force requirements
that has a one meter depth capability and cryogenic operating
temperatures.  The drill mechanism must also provide science data
regarding substrate drilled.

<LI> Sample Acquisition and Transfer Mechanism (SATM) to provide
a sample from known depth to science instruments on Lander, without
contamination or heating. 

<LI> Landing and anchoring technologies to enable single site
exploration of a microgravity body.  Low rebound impact absorption
struts and tethered anchors are the approach being developed.
A pyrotechnic device to accelerate the anchors, yet remain sealed
to prevent surface contamination, is also a key new technology
to be developed.

</UL>


<H3>B. Significant Activities this Reporting Period</H3>
 
<H4>DRILL &amp; SATM MECHANISMS</H4>

<UL>
<LI> Compact Drill Mechanism detail drawings completed &amp;
fab initiated.

<LI> Procurement placed for cryogenic DC brush motor/gearboxes
($79K).
<UL>
<LI> Fixed price partnership (cost sharing) with American Technology
Consortium.
</UL> 

<LI> Procurements placed for new technology carbide gearing
and cryo bearings.                 

<LI> SATM proof of concept model fabricated and tested.
<UL>
<LI> Successful test demonstrated acceptable design; unit fabrication
initiated.
</UL> 

<LI> Produced a requirements set for maximum allowable drill
forces, which is needed to set landing mechanisms requirements.
<UL>
<LI> Maximum thrust of 135 N in strong comet and 13N in weak comet.
</UL> 
<UL>
<LI> 
</UL> 


<LI> Software development on-going for autonomous operation
and adaptive drilling.
<UL>
<LI> Controller shall operate drill and SATM while minimizing forces,
include sequence to transfer sample, and be &quot;fault tolerant&quot;.
<LI> Drill shall have capabilities as &quot;science instrument&quot;
by calibration of force feedback characteristics of various terrestrial
analog materials. 
</UL>

</UL>
 

<H3>B. Significant Activities this Reporting Period (continued)</H3>

<H4>LANDING &amp; ANCHORING</H4>

<UL>

<LI> Low rebound damping strut material characterization testing
performed.

<UL>
<LI> Fabricated test penetrators and plunged into various densities
of Eccofoam material at -165&#176;C to generate data to design
final damping struts.
</UL> 

<LI> Lander parametric analytical model generated in ADAMS.

<UL>
<LI> Subtask to determine required physical parameters of Lander
for &quot;dynamic stability&quot;, such as relationship of footprint
and leg geometry that are needed to meet vertical and horizontal
landing velocities, obstacle heights and terrain slopes. 
</UL> 

<LI> Procurement placed for sealed pyrotechnic accelerator for
anchors.

<UL>
<LI> $50K fixed price development contract with Hi Shear, Inc. 
</UL> 

<LI> Preliminary anchor designs fabricated.

<UL>
<LI> Initial testing to be performed at Caltech using hi-velocity
air guns.

<LI> Test target design performed (size and depth of target &amp;
container depends on analog material to be tested, such as weak
comet vs strong comet).
</UL> 

<LI> Contacted industry for anchor tether development capabilities.

<UL>
<LI> Cortland Cable can fabricate tether with sufficient strength
and electrical conductors for cryogenic operation.
</UL> 

</UL>


