<a name="mldm">

<H2>Micro Lander Dexterous Manipulators </H2>

<P>
This task develops new robotic architectures and technologies for planetary surface science, consistent with mission objectives and constraints of the NASA Mars Exploration Program. Resulting robots - as integrated with Mars lander or rover science platforms - will be used to dexterously view, probe, acquire, and containerize samples for in situ analysis and potential return to earth. Task technology thrusts include design of scaleable, ultra-light arms and actively powered effectors, the development of new composite robot components and material forming processes, and the innovation of miniature, high-torque density solid state motors applicable to wide ranging Mars climates. The scope of  task R&D is ground laboratory concept demonstrations and the evaluation of selected new components in realistic Mars environmental conditions. FY96 Level 1 task activities develop and demonstrate a new, all-composite manipulator under dexterous task space control for representative sampling operations.
<P>

<IMG SRC="mldm_arm.gif"> 

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Completed preliminary mechanical design of "MarsArmII," an
all-composite three degrees of  freedom manipulator that is the FY96
Level 1 deliverable from this task. This two-meter long arm will have
2-D composite rigid tubular links, three (roll-pitch-pitch) joints
based in a novel 3-D composite implementation, and be actuated by a
set of  rotary ultrasonic motors. The MarsArmII concept further serves
as reference for a scaled-down "Micro-arm" design, an approximate 60
cm long small manipulator targeted for use as a light, dexterous
rover-borne sampling device (cf. Lightweight and Survivable Rover task
report) <BR>

<LI>Enabling the above designs, we have made significant progress on a
new resin transfer mold 3-D composite, work we are carrying out in
cooperation with B. F. Goodrich, Inc. During this period we fabricated
samples of the first such materials, which are based on an air lay-up
3-D carbon fiber pre-form and epoxy post-impregnation. Results of
initial mechanical tests are very encouraging: The material has
approximately one half the density of aluminum, equivalent breaking
strength, and one-third the modulus. We have found the 3D composite --
unlike 2-D counterparts -- amenable to conventional machining
(milling, cutting, tapping, etc.). In test cases, we successfully
tapped 1/4-20 and #2-56 machine screws. We therefore believe the new
3-D composite process will be a means of making very light, strong
parts for critical load-bearing interfaces such as robot joint
structures, rover wheel assemblies & running gear, etc. <BR>

<LI> There has been good progress on a number of fronts in our
ultrasonic solid state motor (SSM) work: 1) QMI, Inc. (TCA partner)
developed a miniature driver circuit that has prospects for
generalized application to many SSM designs, facilitating use and
reducing expense;  2) modifications were completed to our SATEC
cryo-vac test chamber enabling full range characterization of motor
torque-speed  behavior under realistic conditions (down to 120K and
10mTorr); 3) the MIT/JPL SSM modeling tools were improved by
finite-element-model extensions, versus prior Rayleigh-Ritz averaging,
that now enable accurate prediction of fundamental motor operating
parameters such as stator drive frequency (and a new 3" motor has been
designed, to be used in corroborating model predictions; 4) MIT (N.
Hagood) delivered a revised dual side stator motor design for
evaluation (showing, as noted in last report, significantly improved
rotor-stator interface control, and reduced vibration/noise); 5) four
related JPL New Technology Reports have now been approved for patent
disclosure, and two submitted to the Washington D. C. office. <BR>
  
<LI>We have developed strawman science scenarios for FY96-end
experimentation/ demonstration: 1) autonomous soil science where a
robot arm trenches soil to examine and deposit soil samples to lander
based science instrumentation; 2) small rock science where a robot arm
scans and picks up small, loose surface samples of interest, and 3)
large rock science where a robot arm and attached science tooling
interacts with larger weathered rocks/outcroppings to expose, scan and
extract fresh rock samples. From these operating scenarios we will
select key elements to test the new MarsArmII and associated dexterous
controls procedures. We have iterated with the MSP Mars '98/Mars
Volatiles and Climate Surveyor (PI, David A. Paige) task on some of
these concepts, in part motivated by their recent testing of robotic
arm digging in frozen Mars soils simulants. Based on these discussions
with the flight project, we have factored some design changes into
MarsArmII (e.g., a 33% increase in tip down-force capabilities with
negligible mass impact to overall design).   
</UL>

<H3>B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Finalize MarsArmII mechanical design; close procurement on
critical items (motors/materials/controllers); and submit key
assemblies to fabrication<BR>

<LI>Continue work in 3-D composite process design, materials
fabrication and testing, and specify RTM procedures for all critical
parts of MarsArmII and Micro-arm; also, begin selective environmental
testing of  2D composite processes (based in epoxy/polycyanate matrix
systems) <BR>

<LI>Continue SATEC chamber environmental testing of commercial solid
state motor examples, supporting: 1) the establishment of an
experimental baseline for analysis of forthcoming new JPL/QMI
segmented and reverse stack high torque designs, and 2) the
identification and understanding of motor failure modes due to low
temperature and vacuum atmospheric conditions <BR>

<LI>Continue development of SSM models for SSM material and structural 
parameter optimization, emphasizing the stator-rotor interface design,
including the fabrication of a test device for design model
validation<BR>

</UL>

<H3>C. Schedule </H3>

<P>
<IMG SRC="mldm_sch.gif"> 
