<a name="rams">

<H2> MicroTelerobotics: Robot Assisted MicroSurgery (RAMS) </H2>

This task is a cooperative NASA-Industry effort to develop a
telerobot for breakthrough micro-and-minimally invasive
surgeries. The resulting Robot Assisted Microsurgery (RAMS)
workstation, via computer enhanced controls, will enable new
procedures beyond human manual dexterity, and allow a broader
group of practitioners to successfully deliver needed healthcare
services at reduced cost. Surgical applications include the eye,
ear, nose, throat, face, hand, spine, and brain. NASA-JPL's role
is to design, fabricate, test, and document an engineering R&D
prototype -- a six degrees-of-freedom, position and force scaling
master-slave telemanipulator -- capable of relative positioning
of 20 microns over a 10-to-20 cm*3 continuous volume (e.g., the
eye).  The industry partner, MicroDexterity Systems, Inc.,
working through independent funding, defines medical
requirements, collaborates in system engineering design, develops
and tests a pre-commercial clinical prototype, and with end
market support certifies and commercializes a final design. <P>

JPL successfully demonstrated a robot slave engineering prototype
in FY 1994, and in FY 1995, a master arm capable of simulating a
force feedback environment and manually controlling task space
position of the slave. In FY 1996, JPL will enable the handling
of surgical instruments, demonstrate a realistic microsurgical
procedure using the telerobotic system and build a second
prototype to allow external medical laboratory testing of the
RAMS technology. Further growth master-slave system capabilities
include textural feedback at the master, and <i>in situ</i>
imaging at the robot slave. Beyond its medical significance, this
new MicroTelerobotic system has potential dual-use in
ground-to-orbit and thermal-vacuum applications that include
EVA/IVA telescience and telemedicine, safe bio-and-materials
processing, micro-mechanical assembly, small-instrument
servicing, and terrestrial environmental testing. <P>

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events </H3>
<UL>
<LI> <I> Medical Advisory Board Meeting </I> The second RAMS
Medical Advisory Board meeting was held at JPL on January 22,
1996. Attendees were: <P>
<UL>
<LI> Steven T. Charles, MD, MicroDexterity Systems, Inc. and The Charles
Retina Institute, vitreo-retinal surgery, six years of R&D in surgical
micro-robotics.
<LI> Patrick Kelly, MD, professor and chairman of neurosurgery at New York
University, Mayo Clinic adjunct, founder of Stereotaxic Systems.
<LI>Graham Lister, MD, professor of hand surgery, The University
of Utah School of Medicine, Division of Orthopedic Surgery and
Primary Children's Medical Center.
<LI>Faina Shtern, MD, NIH/National Cancer Institute, Chief, Diagnostic Imaging
Research, and program manager for new initiatives in Imaging Guided Therapy.
<LI>Maria Siemionow, MD, PhD, Cleveland Clinic Foundation, Director, Plastic
Surgery Research.
<LI>Daniel Winfield, Senior Research Engineer, Research Triangle Institute,
NASA Technology Applications Team.
</UL>
<P>
The board submitted its report in early February with the following findings:
<UL>
<LI> The MAB described the work at JPL as <I> superb </I> and
said that it is a significant contribution toward ultimate
development and commercialization of this technology.

<LI> MDS should perform a cost/price analysis on the product to
be marketed and provide a commercialization schedule.

<LI> JPL and MDS should continue with external medical laboratory
testing plans.

<LI> The metrics for measurement of success of this task were
suggested to be the level of induced private sector funding and
the number of RAMS based systems in testing in medical
laboratories at the conclusion of the task.

<LI> JPL and MDS should continue publicizing this work in the
technical and popular media.

</UL>
<P>
<LI> The RAMS task deliverables were re-planned due to a budget
cut from $800K to $620K. The re-planned deliverables are:

<UL> 
<LI> Demonstration of the RAMS telerobotic system performing a
vitreo-retinal microsurgical procedure with 20 micron surgical
instrument relative positioning. <B> Level 1 </B>

<LI> Fabrication of a slave robot prototype-2 and loan of the
slave prototype-1 robot to the Cleveland Clinic <B> Level 2 </B>

<LI> Delivery of the RAMS slave robot design documentation to
MDS, Inc. <B> Level 2 </B>

<LI> Fabrication of a master prototype-2 and integration with its
corresponding slave robot <B> Level 2 </B>

</UL>
<P>
<LI> <I>Second slave arm prototype:</I> Procured, fabricated and
partially assembled sub-systems of the slave prototype-2. Late
delivery of vended items has delayed integration and test of the
prototype. Procured items were delivered in late March leading to
mid-April completion of the prototype integration and test.
Implementation of a stand-alone (without network support) version
of the RAMS system is complete. Safety electronics to detect
panic and failure conditions and execute a graceful shutdown has
been implemented and tested. A GUI and joystick interface was
implemented on a PC for the prototype system to be loaned to the
Cleveland Clinic.
<P>
<LI> <I>Slave detail design documentation: </I> The Level 2
milestone of  delivery of the RAMS slave robot documentation was
completed. A 400-plus page document was delivered to MDS, Inc. in
March.
<P>
<LI> <I>Loan of slave prototype to Cleveland Clinic: </I> Completed
NASA-JPL Loan Agreement for loan of slave clone to the Cleveland Clinic
Foundation.
Also worked with Dr. Siemionow of the Cleveland Clinic Foundation to plan for
tests of the slave robot prototype to be conducted in her laboratory.
<P>
<LI> <I> Microsurgery simulation: </I> With MDS, Inc., defined
the removal of a calibrated microsphere from a simulated eyeball
as a microsurgery procedure for demonstration using the RAMS
system. Design of a simulated eyeball is in progress. Instruments
for performing the microsurgical procedure have been provided by
MDS. These will be modified and integrated into the slave robot
end effector.
<P>
<LI> The TRIWG FY 97 proposal was prepared and presented to the
March TRIWG meeting at JSC.
<P>
<LI> <I>Initiated master prototype-2 fabrication.</I>
<P>
<LI> <I>External presentations: </I> A number of presentations
and external contacts were made; the more significant ones are
listed below:
<UL>
<LI> A paper coauthored by the JPL RAMS team was presented at the
Medicine Meets Virtual Reality IV Conference held in San Diego,
January 18-20, 1996.

<LI> RAMS was featured in an advertisement by Real-time
Innovations, Inc. of their Control Shell product in the IEEE
Robotics and Automation Society Magazine.

<LI> RAMS was presented at an American Medical Association
meeting in Washington, DC as part of a poster presentation of JPL
projects in medicine.

<LI> Dr. Nicogossian, NASA Deputy  Assistant Administrator,
visited the RAMS lab on March 29 and was given a demonstration.

</UL>
<LI> 
<P>
<LI> <I>MDS Activity: </I>
<UL>
<LI> MDS has assisted JPL in defining a demonstration surgical
procedure and has provided JPL with numerous instruments and
supporting equipment for implementing a realistic simulated eye
microsurgery environment.

<LI> MDS is continuing its collaboration with Baxter to identify
surgical procedures that can benefit from this technology. Baxter
is also funding MDS to perform feasibility and clinical tests of
the RAMS technology.

<LI> MDS has signed an agreement with GE Medical Systems to
develop a RAMS-based telerobotic system for image-guided MRI
compatibility.

<LI> MDS has secured a Phase I SBIR grant from ARPA for
continuing development of a micro-telerobotic system for remote
applications.

</UL>
<P>
</UL>

