<a name="ravi">

<H2> Ranger Automated Visual Inspection </H2>

Automated robotic inspection of space platforms such as Space Station is
expected to be an important element to offload time consuming inspection
activities from astronauts.  Jet Propulsion Laboratory recently developed
such a remote surface inspection (RSI) system demonstrated successfully
on the ground in a constrained lab environment. The objective of this task 
is to apply this technology to the Ranger TFX mission Phase 3 Visual 
Inspection Task to assess/validate the telerobotic automated inspection 
capability in real space operation lighting conditions. To achieve this
evaluation objective, we will perform pre-flight, on-orbit actual flight, 
and post-flight experiments. The degree of success of the task depends 
upon how well the pre-flight baseline experiment and its predictions agree 
with real flight experiments, using performance metrics such as flaw size and 
flaw contrast under various sunlight and mis-registration conditions. 
Post-flight will provide lessons learned. The level 1 milestone for FY'96 
is to deliver an inspection taskboard, inspection scenario, and inspection task
software to University of Maryland Ranger Program for Neutral Buoyancy tests. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="ri.gif">

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI> Designed/fabricated the inspection taskboard with underwater resistant
     painting for Neutral Buoyancy tests, and delivered to University of 
     Maryland on 7/3.

<UL>
<LI> The left and right sides of the inspection taskboard are mechanically 
     identical with sub-millimeter accuracy --- left side for "unflawed" 
     and right side for "flawed" images.

<LI> The inspection taskboard has three pairs of panels: flat 2-D, concave 
     holes/convex heads, and 3-D structure sections. 

<LI> The right side of the 2-D section (bottom right panel) is silk-screened, 
     which will be used to examine the inspection quality with different sizes 
     and contrasts. 

<LI> The left and right sides of the top and middle panels (holes/heads and 
     3-D structure sections) are currently identical. Flaws, for example, 
     black, grey, or colored tape patches, will be added on the right side 
     prior to inspection tests.
</UL>

<LI> Delivered an initial version of the inspection task software to 
     University of Maryland and conducted an initial integrated test

<UL>
<LI> Integrated the NDDS communication link into the JPL RSI system, and
     JPL (Gene Chalfant) and University of Maryland (Corde Lane) successfully 
     performed an initial integrated test. 

<LI> In the test, the Ranger simulator at UMd was sending the joint angles 
     telemetry data periodically, and the Ranger arm graphics simulation 
     at JPL was being updated accordingly. At the same time, the operator
     at JPL RSI system sent inspection/robot control commands, and we verified
     that the Ranger simulator at UMd received the commands correctly.
</UL>

</UL>


<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL> 

<LI> Plans to have two more integrated tests: one for command sequence GUI and 
     the other for the calibration procedure. The inspection task scenario and 
     corresponding command sequence will be refined through these tests.

<LI> Perform inspection experiments at JPL using the inspection taskboard,
     a duplicate of the one delivered to University of Maryland

</UL>

