<a name="sview">

<H2> Calibrated Synthetic Viewing </H2>


The camera viewing problem is a major concern in ISS (International Space
Station) payload alignment/mating operations, since the end-effector camera 
is occluded by the ORU during the ORU insertion, while the overhead and ISS 
cameras provide limited views. The Calibrated Synthetic Viewing (CSV) is 
needed to enable successful ORU insertion despite the inadequate video 
coverage. By contrast, the current baseline use of the onboard AVF 
(Artificial Vision System) has limitations in terms of viewing constraints 
and availability of AVF vision targets for small payloads. 
<P>

New technical contributions include 1) enhance existing edge-based 
semi-automatic VR (virtual reality) calibration, 2) develop a new 
local fine alignment algorithm to compensate for model inaccuracy, and 
3) demonstrate a reliable, high-precision alignment for the ISS RPCM-like 
ORU insertion (1/4 inch clearance) under limited/occluded camera viewing 
conditions, with quantitative analysis/experiments of alignment accuracy 
in comparison with vision-target based technique. The level 1 milestone 
for FY'96 is to deliver the calibrated synthetic viewing (CSV) software 
developed at JPL to the JSC ARMSS (Automated Robotic Maintenance for 
Space Station) testbed for technology assessment and demonstration 
to the Space Station Program.
<P>

<IMG SRC="sv.gif"> 


<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period </H3>

<UL>

<LI> Completed an initial version of CSV, and delivered to JSC on 6/27.
     Key integration elements include:

<UL>
<LI> edge-based camera calibration and object localization using "weighted 
     average" local edge detector, weighted least squares object localization, 
     and robust matching to remove outliers

<LI> simultaneous update of camera calibration and object localization to
     reduce relative camera positioning errors

<LI> camera/model update after camera zoom change

<LI> local fine alignment --- needs further enhancements

<LI> GUI for interactive camera/model initial adjustment and model/image edge 
     selection/deselection

<LI> GUI enhancement using TELEGRIP 3.0 upgrade allowing video image and 
     2D/3D graphics rendering in a window
</UL>

<LI> JSC interface

<UL>
<LI> visited JSC on 5/21 to define the CSV interface at JSC

<LI> Lucien Junkin of JSC/Lockheed-Martin visited JPL on 5/31 to familiarize
     with CSV

<LI> JSC (Ivan Spain) provided an example TelRIP program that can communicate 
     with the JSC ARMSS robot controller, video switch, camera control, and 
     video frame grabber at JSC. Based on this program, JPL/JSC developed 
     a TelRIP gateway program that interfaces between CSV and JSC systems 

<LI> visited JSC on 6/26 and 6/27 for CSV delivery and integrated tests.
     The basic integration tests were successful --- needs further work
     for complete integration.
</UL>

<LI> Implemented a vision target based model matching technique ---  not
     integrated into CSV yet.

</UL>


<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>

<LI> Support JSC to complete the JSC interface with further enhancements.
     JSC plans to conduct evaluation experiments in mid August. JSC will 
     use similar camera views that were used by an Oceaneering team to test 
     the RPCM-ORU coarse alignment requirement with manual teleoperation.

<LI> JPL plans experiments for comparative performance evaluation of CSV, AVF,
     and manual teleoperation.

</UL>

