<a name="lmma">

<H2> Low Mass Muscle Actuators </H2>

<H3> A. Milestones </H3>

<UL>

<LI> s-PMMA, which was reported to have a very high electrostrictive 
coefficient, will be tested to form a baseline (June 96).
<P>

<LI> Develop methods of introducing electrodes to produce actuators 
(July 96)
<P>

<LI> Investigate alternative ESP actuators (Aug. 96)
<P>

<LI> Analyze muscle Configurations to effectively harvest ESP actuation 
capability (Aug. 96)
<P>

<LI> A selected muscle mechanism will be produce to demonstrate a 1-DoF 
arm with ESP actuator (Sept. 96)
<P>

</UL>


<H3> B. Accomplishments </H3>

<DL>

<DT> ELECTRODING TECHNIQUES
<DD> Methods of electroding polymer films were 
considered and it was determined that sputtering techniques should not 
be used due to film damage associated with heat.  The method that we 
found most effective is vapor deposition.  However, in order to assure 
a good adhesion of the electrode to the polymer surface it is 
necessary to apply a series of solvent and ion beam cleaning 
processes.  For low cost and easy to use applications, brushing 
conductive paste was found useful.  Further, in future mass production 
of electrodes ink-printing method will be considered and AMP Corp. 
offered their assistance.  In addition to parallel surface 
electroding, we also using interdigital electrodes as a form of 
lateral displacement actuation.
<P>

<DT> s-PMMA BASELINE
<DD> Difficulties were encountered with the effort to 
reproduce the data reported in the paper by K. Ohara et. al., entitled 
"Electrostriction of Polymethylmethacrylates" that was published in 
Colloid &amp; Polymer Science, Vol. 260, (1982) pp. 164-168.  This data 
indicated that s-PMMA responds to electroactivation with more than 12% 
strain.  The baseline was substitute with PVF2 for which significant 
amount data is available.  
<P>

<DT> ALTERNATIVE EAP ACTUATORS
<DD> A series of commercially available 
materials were selected for a parametric study of the properties that 
are responsible to electrostriction in polymer.  This includes the 
tacticity, dipole moment, and the dielectric constant of the pendant 
group.
<P>
[The basic mechanism of electrostriction in organic polymers is 
presumed to be related to the polymer structure, i.e., a backbone (a 
polymer chain) with pendant groups (elements with a strong dipole 
moment) attached to the backbone.]  
<P>
Film processing techniques were developed for these materials and the 
films were electroded to form actuators.  The actuators were driven by 
an electric field and the displacement was observed.  Currently, the 
relation between the response and the material characteristics are 
being analyzed to develop criteria for obtaining a strong striction 
from polymers.  
<P>

<DT> MUSCLE CONFIGURATION
<DD> A series of configurations were considered 
and a Neo-Hokian model was investigated.
<P>

<DT> PREPARATION FOR DEMONSTRATION OF 1 DoF MECHANISM
<DD> A actuator based 
on ionic Perflurinated Solfonic Acid films that delivers a 10% linear 
actuator was developed.  A mechanism is being investigated to design a 
1 DoF device that will be used to demonstrate this electroactive 
polymer performance.
<P>

</DL>


