<a name="lsr">

<H2>Lightweight and Survivable Rover (LSR)</H2>

<P>This task develops new rover architectures and enabling technologies
for planetary surface science, with themes of extending rover capability
and survivability while reducing rover mass and launch volume. Our initial
efforts focus on a 5-to-7 kilogram class rover capable of diverse terrain
traverses (VL1/2), self-navigable sorties of multiple kilometers, and extended
operation for months in both equatorial and polar latitudes. We demonstrate
new approaches to volume-and-mass efficient mobility, based on innovative
concepts in wheel design, miniature actuation, chassis structure, thermal
control, sampling mechanization, and computation-efficient 3-D terrain
sensing. These ongoing developments address currently known Mars Surveyor
Program (MSP) mission constraints and objectives, and produce technology
solutions important for later Sample Return missions. We conduct this R&amp;D
in cooperation with the Mars Exploration Technology (MET) Program, leveraging
new high-capacity thermal materials, low-temperature batteries, and miniature
science instrumentation. FY96 Level 1 LSR&nbsp;task activities produce
a first working proof of concept rover (<B><U>LSR-1</U></B>) having collapsible
wheels that stow to 1/3 their operational volume, an integrated low-loss
thermal/structural chassis, and a low-power-and-computation, all-terrain
obstacle detection sensor. </P>

<P><IMG SRC="lsr96.jpg" HEIGHT=367 WIDTH=561><BR>
</P>

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>We made significant progress on detailed mechanical design and fabrication
of our first LSR prototype during this reporting period. &quot;LSR-1,&quot;
per the CAD depiction above, is a 7kg vehicle (incl. a science instrument
for visible imaging and near-IR spectrophotometry), 100 cm in length, having
20 cm dia. wheels, 70 cm track, and 30 cm belly-pan clearance. A key innovation
in LSR is the development of space-worthy collapsible wheels enabling major
reduction in launch stowage volume (and in subsequent FY97 developments,
related collapsible running gear) for which we have implemented a first
mechanical proof-of-concept, shown below: </LI>

<P><IMG SRC="colwheel.jpg" HEIGHT=231 WIDTH=600></P>

<P>[<I>working bench model of LSR wheel: 25 cm dia, wheel, aluminum construction,
collapses to approx. 30% deployed volume, simulated growsers, approx. 400g</I>]
</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<P>The operational LSR-1 wheels will be of hybrid composite/metal construction,
weighing about 250g each at 20 cm dia. We have docketed a NTR for this
development under the title &quot;Volume Efficient Deployable Rigid Wheel
(VEDRW).&quot; In general, our recent development of a new high-strength
machinable 3D composite (cf. accompanying 3Q96 JPL/Micro Lander Dexterous
Manipulator task report - &quot;<I>Black Aluminum</I>&quot;) is playing
an important part in LSR design, enabling 40-50% mass reduction of various
struts, integral thermal-structural elements, load-bearing joints, etc.
At this time, we estimate the mobility subsystem mass at 3.0 kg (six wheels,
rigid Al strut rocker-bogie with composite linkage elements, actuators,
etc.). All rotating surfaces incorporate Vespel SP-3 bushings, rather than
ball bearings, thus providing a further mass savings and extending low
temperature operability. Related developments in this period include design
of the LSR-1 power train, which utilizes flight heritage Maxon DC motors
and five-stage planetary gear-heads (modified fifth stage planet carrier
and output shaft). </P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>We continued the development of a novel integrated thermal/structural
vehicle chassis for LSR-1, wherein the warm electronics enclosure (WEE)
walls integrate a distributed load bearing sheet-and-spar mechanical composite
structure. Thermal control &amp; isolation is advanced over MFEX/Sojourner
through a combination of new Phase-Change Materials (PCM) being developed
in a companion MET task (R. Manvi), and LSR task introduction of a new
thermally isolating aerogel. We reported on some recent facets of this
work in two papers (G. Hickey et al.) given at the <I>Intl. Conf. on Environmental
Systems</I>, Monterey, CA, July 10, 1996. A <B><I><U>significant event</U></I></B>
within our latest work is our first experimental findings on a new low-loss,
low-mass rover thermal isolation approach. Utilizing a sheet-and-spar WEE
model structure from LSR-1, we performed thermal conductivity tests on
opacified resorcinol-formaldehyde aerogel, and demonstrated 10-to-30% lower
losses relative to silica aerogels used in MFEX -- these results as observed
in a Mars- relevant 10 torr CO2 ambient over a -80 to 20C range. </LI>

<LI>As described in prior LSR task reports, this year's work develops a
new laser spot-pushbroom sensor enabling reliable obstacle detection/avoidance
at relatively high rates of traverse, low computation, and low power. We
made good progress this period on design and proof-of-concept of the sensor
system, which was conceived for FY96/LSR-1 baseline operations as a five-laser/five-spot
projector, whose projected beams are selectively scanned and triangulated
within CCD cameras. Our evolution from conventional light-striping, as
used in MFEX/Sojourner, to highly focused, low-loss spot-projection has
required careful modeling and optimization of the laser collimating optics.
This work and experimentation was also useful to MFEX sensor development
(cf. Email of 5/29/96 J. Matijevic to D. Lavery). Further, we have been
able to extend the single-spot-per-laser projection concept to a new sensor
design in which up to 15 bright spots per laser are projected into the
50-100 cm rover near field through use of laser-mounted diffraction grating
optics. Using such a preliminary implementation, we have demonstrated obstacle
detection to 1 cm accuracy at 50 cm in full sunlight by <I>direct imaging
and spot/background discrimination</I>. Thus, we avoid time-consuming overhead
and power utilization of an additional difference imaging step (cf. MFEX
design). </LI>
</UL>

<H3>B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Complete fabrication &amp; assembly of all LSR-1 mobility components
(wheels, actuators and running gear) </LI>

<LI>Complete tooling &amp; fabrication of the thermal-structural LSR-1
chassis (incl. processing/machining of supporting interior composite struts
and exterior chassis/science interfaces); continue experimental characterization
of related thermal materials and the integrated thermal structure </LI>

<LI>Complete software and electronic integration of spot-pushbroom sensor,
communications (rover modem link) and MFEX Engineering Model board set
for LSR FY96 Level 1 operations </LI>

<LI>Integrate the preceding mobility, thermal/chassis, sensor-based subsystems
into LSR-1 prototype and test/checkout operability </LI>

<LI>Conduct MarsYard experiments with LSR-1, documenting highlights for
FY96-end Level 1 milestone. </LI>
</UL>

<H3>C. Schedule </H3>

<P><IMG SRC="lsrschd.gif" HEIGHT=248 WIDTH=550></P>

