<!+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++>

<a name="lrsr">

<H2> Long-Range Science Rover  (LRSR)</H2>


<P>
This task develops technologies that enable 20 Kg class microrovers
to autonomously traverse many kilometers on the surface of Mars
and perform scientist directed experiments and return relevant
data back to Earth. Present microrover technology has several
limitations that preclude more ambitious science rich missions.
Current microrovers have very limited traverse (10s of meters),
are not capable of sample acquisition and manipulation (i.e.,
soil and rock acquisition, subsurface access, burial of instruments),
have limited science packages onboard, are designed for short
term missions (10 days), and require careful and repetitive ground
monitoring and control (limited autonomy) 
<P>
There is great interest in the science community to explore Mars
by landing near interesting geographic areas and moving to pre-selected
targets to offset landing errors. It is desirable to place instruments
against outcrops or loose rocks, possibly collect rocks for return
to Earth, and search an area for sample of interest. Also, long
traverse will provide an opportunity to make observations and
measurements along traverses and to access a wide variety of rocks
from different regions of Mars.
<P>
The development program is a multi-organizational research activity
involving several JPL technical divisions, industry, and universities.
The technical approach to achieving the above objectives is composed
of a focused research effort covering: 
<UL>
<LI>Autonomous sensing/navigation, 
<LI>Sampling/sensing using a rover attached miniature manipulator

<LI>Integration of relevant science instruments and demonstration
of realistic science missions with scientist participation. 
<LI>Long range navigation (kilometers) and landerless operation
<LI>Telescience control station, ability to plan science tasks
from scientists' home institutions, distribute return data via
the WEB, and VR visualization of terrain and science data 
<LI>Well integrated system testing and demonstration to ensure
technologies are developed and delivered within the context of
a surface planetary flight program like a Mars sample return mission.
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<B>Major FY96 deliverables are: <BR>
<BR>
</B>
<OL>
<LI>Improve Rocky 7 performance by increasing its autonomy for
sampling and pointing science instruments (ensure sampling is
performed in scientist designated areas, confirm that sampling
has been successful, identify science instrument pointing locations).

<LI>Improve the mechanical performance of the system by redesigning
the steering and manipulator joints. Increase rover speed for
ground based performance tests.
<LI>Reduce power requirement by lowering computer clock speed.
<LI>Integrate a sun sensor and perform rover navigation using
the Sun to compute rover heading. Perform tests and obtain performance
data.
<LI>Identify at least two additional science instruments and help
integrate them to the rover.
<LI>Develop on-board science data reduction capability. 
<LI>Develop high-level commanding capability based on science
requirements 
<LI>Perform realistic science missions with scientist participation.
<BR>

</OL>

<H3>A. Significant Activities and Events During this Period</H3>
<UL>
<LI>A science team has been formed to participate in LRSR's field
testing in December 96 and May of 97. The science team is led
by Professor 
<A HREF="http://epsc.wustl.edu/people/arvidson.html">Ray Arvidson </A>of
Washington University and Ron Greeley of University of Arizona.
Plans and schedules have been developed to conduct these field
tests. A joint web page has been developed to inform other planetary
scientists about these filed experiments (<A HREF="http://wundow.wustl.edu/~king/rover_new.html">Mojave Field Experiments for Rocky 7 Prototype Mars Rover</A>)
and disseminate the results after each experiment. 
<LI>A joint team of JPL and Washington University personnel traveled
to the Mojave desert and selected the Pisgah lava field on Lake
Lavic for December field experiments. These experiments are currently
planned for December 17 and 18, 1996. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI> <IMG SRC="crater-lake_lavic.gif">
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>A new arm was developed and integrated to the vehicle. This
arm uses newly designed joints that have less friction and therefore
provides smooth motions. The arm has successfully been used to
dig soil, point a spectrometer, and dump acquired soil. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI> <IMG SRC="new_arm_digging_small.gif">
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>A mast system to enable long range traverse has been designed,
fabricated and currently is being tested to provide capability
for landerless operations. This mast has three degrees of freedom,
weighs 600 gm and when deployed stands 1.42 meter above ground.
 This mast will be used both for navigation and science instrument
pointing and placement. Currently, the mast carries a pair of
CCD cameras for stereo imaging. The cameras also have color filters
that provide for synthesized color imaging and spectrometry. The
stereo imaging system weighs 150 gm.  In addition, a close-up
imaging instrument has been developed using a CCD camera which
can be placed against rocks for 50 um/pixel resolution imaging.
This imager uses a number of LED's to take images under different
lights, and therefore can be used for spectral analysis. The camera
is mounted in a self-aligning housing that will automatically
place the camera head on a rock when the surface normal is not
known, precisely. Three micro switches provide onboard confirmation
that the camera head has contacted a surface. This close-up imager
weighs 200 grams.  The mast has been designed to carry a 500 gm
science instrument.
<LI> One candidate is a Mossbuaer instrument being developed by
Goestar Klingelhoffer from Germany. Another candidate is a spectrometer
called LCTF (Liquid Crystal Tunable Filter) that is being developed
by JPL.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><IMG SRC="mast&instruments_identified.gif">
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>A number of improvements in the dig-dump and spectrometer
pointing operations have been implemented to improve the overall
robustness of the system. Before deploying the arm, Rocky 7 searches
the area in front of the rover for possible collision of its manipulator
with rocks. It searches and finds spots that are safe for manipulation.
It then autonomously moves the rover such that the arm deployment
occurs in a collision free region. For
dig and dump operations, the vision system checks the before and
after images of the manipulator scoops to determine whether or
not the dig or dump operations were successful. For digging operations,
the vision system confirms that the area is &quot;soil&quot; like
by looking at the texture of the spot. These capabilities are
currently being tested in the end-to-end system in Mars Yard.
</UL>

<H3>B. Activities for Next Reporting Period</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Develop a kinematics model for the mast and control the mast
in a stand-alone setting
<LI>Test the mast stereo imager and the mast mounted close-up
imager
<LI>Develop navigation algorithms for long range traverse using
the sun sensor
<LI>Perform mobility tests with USC
</UL>

<H3>C. Schedule </H3>

<P>
<IMG SRC="lrsrschd.gif" BORDER="2"><BR>

<P>
<LI> Concerns/Issues:

The operation of the mast and associated science instruments will first be demonstrated in a stand-alone configuration for the year-end demo.  The mast will be integrated on to Rocky 7 in time for December field tests.<BR>
