<a name="aerobot">
<H2> Planetary Aerobot Testbed </H2>

There has been considerable progress in the Planetary Aerobot Testbed
(PAT) development this last quarter.  Two of the tasks currently
supported by the Telerobotics Program are the Venus Sensor and
Perception (VESPER) and the Buoyancy Control Subsytsem
(BCS).

<h3>Buoyancy Control Subsytsem (BCS)</h3>

The PAT BCS is a unique mobility system being developed to further the
exploration of planetary atmospheres and surfaces.  An aerobot BCS
will allow science packages to be placed in the atmosphere of places
such as Venus or Titan, and them to be flown at different altitudes,
landed at specific sites, or guided to different regions in the
atmosphere under autonomous control.<P>

The system currently being developed under the Telerobotics Program
for operation within the Earths atmosphere, shown in figure 1,
consists of a primary balloon with Helium lifting gas, a secondary
balloon for the reversible fluid, and a pressure vessel/heat exchanger
system designed to allow control of the fluid phase.  The operation
subsystem will enable the verification of complex dynamic,
thermodynamic and aerodynamic models which will eventually adapted to
Venus and Titan.  Experience gained in the manual operation of the BCS
in FY96 will enable the autonomous operation and control of PAT in FY
97.<P>
 
<center><img width=600 height=660 src="pat_sch.gif"><P><i>
Fig. 1.  Preliminary configuration of PAT '96.</i></center><P>

The third quarter of 1996 has provided some very interesting
developments for the Buoyancy Control System (BCS) of the Planetary
Aerobot Testbed (PAT).  First, the system-level design was
reconsidered and a method for operating these types of balloons with a
one valve instead of three was discovered.  This allows us to make
smaller, lighter reversible fluid balloon systems applicable to the
target missions of Earth, Venus, and Titan.<P>

Second, progress has been made on the hardware front.  The heat
exchanger, arguably the largest and most complicated component of the
system, was built using mass production electronic parts packaging
equipment, providing inexpensive, accurate techniques for
construction.  This technique allows us to scale the PAT heat
exchanger to virtually any desired size with very few engineering
changes, opening up the possibility for flying future PATs of
different sizes without increasing costs.  Additionally, other
components such as the balloon, gas bag, and cutdown system components
(parachutes and line cutters) have been located and in some cases
received.  The last significant piece of hardware, the fluid reservoir
with valve train, is currently in fabrication for system test.<P>

A difficulty arose in the characterization and modeling of the
reversible fluid originally intended to fly aboard PAT.  This fluid,
dubbed Mix II (65% R142b and 35% R124), has recently been found to
have a higher solar absorbtivity than originally expected.  Too much
solar absorption will keep the fluid from condensing and will cause
PAT not to reverse direction.  In addition, because this fluid boils
at a lower temperature than fluids flown in the past, PAT would
operate closer to the tropopause, where the radiant black body
temperature characteristics of the atmosphere are less well understood
and cause difficulties in the proper modeling of the delicate
thermodynamics of the vehicle.  In light of these two issues, we are
searching for better reversible fluids to fly the mission.  Our
leading candidate, a combination of R114 and R143, promises to give us
a similar Buoyancy Control Margin to PAT without the above problems. 
Fortunately, this change has little impact on the hardware described
above.<P>

The next quarter should bring together the culmination of the
activities.  A full-scale BCS system will be erected in the newly
established Aerobot Laboratory for initial characterization. 
Additionally, plans are in the works to fly the system within the
Earth's atmosphere on PAT.<P>

<h3>Venus Sensor and Perception (VESPER)</h3>

The first objective of the VESPER system is to develop autonomous
perception concepts for balloon aerobot system (with focus on Venus
operations) to enable: on-board localization of balloon with respect
to a planet, estimation of balloon motion (horizontal/vertical) and
determination of balloon gondola attitude.   This capability supports
science instrument line-of-sight determination and sequence
triggering, global navigation and path-planning, and descent/landing
operations.  In other words, Where are we ? Where are we going ? What
are we looking at? <P>

Other objectives are to develop a ``ground-truth'' system for
performance evaluation as well as emulation of other sensors, develop
an open and extensible hardware, software and test infrastructure i.e.
a testbed to support the demonstration of sensors, algorithms and
mission concepts for aerobot studies applicable to Mars, Venus, Earth,
etc., and to serve as a point design to provide the foundation of a
design database for potential mission opportunities - Mars 2001, Venus
2005. <P>

Specific FY96 objectives of VESPER include establishment of a set of
general aerobot perception/navigation concepts using inertial,
imaging, celestial, and radiometric sensors, the design and
implementation of a sensor/perception system for demonstration of a
core subset of perception concepts on PAT including:<P>

<ul>

<li>Inertial propagation of balloon state - attitude and attitude rate.
<li>Science camera triggering and line-of-sight referencing.
<li>Frame-to-frame image based ground velocity track estimation.
<li>Pressure-based balloon altitude estimation. 

</ul>

Additional objectives include implementation (but not necessarily fly)
additional perception/navigation concepts such as 6-dof inertial
propagation of balloon state - attitude, attitude rate, translational
position/velocity and simple imaging-based sun/horizon sensor.  Other
specific objectives are selection and implementation of long-lead
sensor hardware elements e.g. radar/lidar altimeter, sun-sensor for
Venus, radiometric sensor, implementation of a ground-truth system for
attitude and use GPS data (implemented by communication/RF task) for
position and implementation of ambient atmospheric sensors -
pressure/temperature for support of FAA transponder and flight
performance/modeling. <P>

In the last quarter the VESPER subsystem saw continued progress
towards the demonstrationflight in the fall. All hardware and
electronics development is completewith the integration of the
inertial sensors into a compact lightweight package.  Algorithm and
software development activities focus on improvements and tuning of
the image processing algorithms for frame-to-frame motion estimation
and the Kalman filter algorithms for the inertial attitude and motion
estimation. Calibrations of the various sensors is in progress.
Preparations are also underway to process and interpret aerial image
data returned from an Active Pixel Sensor (APS) camera to be flown in
the fourth quarter on a small test balloon (ALICE). A study is also
underway to select a suitable altimeter technology and sensor (either
Q-switched laser or pulsed radar) for use on the balloon.
<P>

<B>Contact</B>: 
<A HREF="mailto:Kerry.Nock@jpl.nasa.gov">
Kerry Nock/JPL</A> (email: Kerry.Nock@jpl.nasa.gov)

