<a name="nrtd">

<H2>Nanorover Technology Development</H2>

The objective of this task is to develop a very small but
scientifically capable rover system which can easily fit within the
projected mass reserves of future landed missions on Mars and other
planetary surfaces.  These reserves are currently (e.g. Mars Surveyor)
about 1kg and new smaller missions (e.g. New Millenium) may have mass
reserves as small as 100g.  By fitting within the mass reserves, and
by having a very simple interface to the lander, the nanorover can fly
as a secondary payload or as a late addition to the mission.
<p>

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>
<UL>

<LI> Integrated breadboard 4-wheel mobility chassis with off-board
electronics and reran level-2 demonstration of waypoint navigation
using waypoint designation in monocular lander imagery.  Measured
performance of system and found average trajectory errors of 11.3 cm
over a zig-zag course from 1 to 5 meters from the lander camera.
<P>

<LI> Finalized optics and mechanisms designs and submitted to
fabrication.  Initial fabrication of some mechanical parts.  Custom
concave holographic grating for infrared spectrometer ordered and
received from American Holographic of Fitchburg, MA.  Major purchased
parts ordered and received.
<P>

<LI> Continued electronics design and preliminary circuit board layout.

</UL>

<H3> B. Plans for the Next reporting Period </H3>

<UL>

<LI> Layout and fabricate printed circuit boards.  Complete fabrication
of all mechanical components.
<P>

<LI> Integrate and assemble all optics, mechanisms, and electronics.  Test
assembled system.  Install preliminary software load.  <p>

</UL>


<H3> C. Schedule </H3>

