<a name="mldm">

<H2>Micro Lander Dexterous Manipulators </H2>

<P>This task develops new robotic architectures and technologies for planetary
surface science, consistent with mission objectives and constraints of
the NASA Mars Exploration Program. Resulting robots - as integrated with
Mars lander or rover science platforms - will be used to dexterously view,
probe, acquire, and containerize samples for in situ analysis and potential
return to earth. Task technology thrusts include design of scaleable, ultra-light
arms and actively powered effectors, the development of new composite robot
components and material forming processes, and the innovation of miniature,
high-torque density solid state motors applicable to wide ranging Mars
climates. The scope of task R&amp;D is ground laboratory concept demonstrations
and the evaluation of selected new components in realistic Mars environmental
conditions. FY96 Level 1 task activities develop and demonstrate a new,
all-composite manipulator under dexterous task space control for representative
sampling operations. </P>

<P><IMG SRC="mldmarm.gif" HEIGHT=234 WIDTH=493></P>

<P><BR>
</P>

<H3>A. Activities in This Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>We completed the detailed mechanical design of &quot;MarsArmII,&quot;
an <I>all-composite</I> three degrees of freedom (T/S/E) manipulator that
is our FY96 Level 1 deliverable from this task (Sep'96). MarsArmII is constructed
of high-strength 2-D composite tubular links, three (roll-pitch-pitch)
modular joints based in novel 3-D composite implementation (see below),
and is driven by a set of rotary solid state ultrasonic motors (USM) acting
through harmonic drives. The arm proper, integrated with all instrumentation
and actuation, is approximately two meters at full extent, 4 kg in mass,
and will support a full extent load of approx. 15 lb. while achieving 5
in/sec tip velocities. MarsArmII will carry a new all-composite Multi-Function
Science End Effector (MFSEE ) incorporating a trenching tool, worm-driven
opposed jaws (for sample acquisition/handling), micro-viewing science camera
and a simple active abrasion device for exposure of fresh rock surfaces.
We have processed the enabling composite billets/tubes, and most parts
are now in fabrication. We note that MarsArmII further serves as reference
for a scaled-down &quot;Micro-arm&quot; design, an approx. 60 cm long small
manipulator targeted for use as a light, dexterous rover-borne sampling
and deployment device (cf. Lightweight and Survivable Rover task).</LI>

<LI>Our work on the new 3D composite process continued successfully, measured
in one respect by recent resin transfer mold production of numerous billets
as large as 10x10x2.5 cu-in, from which we are able to <I>directly, repeatably
machine</I> arm joint, joint-tube interface, end-effector parts and other
critical load-bearing assemblies by conventional metal shop practice. Preliminary
mechanical tests yielded average 80 ksi thread shear strengths at 4-40
screw size, and dependable results for 2-56 machine screws. We have filed
for technology disclosure under the name &quot;Black Aluminum.&quot; </LI>

<LI>We made progress in several areas of ultrasonic motor design and analysis:
1) one important advance was experimental development (within a SATEC chamber
instrumented for local motor cooling/torque-gauging) and completion of
first environmental tests under space-relevant conditions. Using commercially
available Shinsei (Litton-Westrex/Japan) 1 in-lb devices, we obtained stable
motor torque-speed characteristics from room temperature down to -50C onset
of thermally induced mechanical seizure in 2.2x10^2 Torr vacuum. We observed
no evidence of vacuum corona or welding, these being primary low-temperature
concerns for this type of motor. Given the motor is maximally rated for
&gt;-10C operations in 1 ATM ambient, these initial results are encouraging;
2) Significant progress was made in developing finite element models (FEM)
of USM's to incorporate complete configuration of the stator (teeth size,
diameter and thickness, etc., these interface parameters being empirically
observed as critical variables in motor torque output/efficiency). This
work is joint with MIT (N. Hagood), who provides further support in design-synthesis,
novel techniques of experimental analysis (interferometric tools for dynamic
characterization of the motor actuation phenomenology - e.g. visualization
of wave transduction at the critical stator-rotor interface and related
pathologies due to mechanical design tolerancing, areally/temporally uniform
control of interface pressure/friction, etc.), and prototyping of new large
diameter (3&quot; dia.) /high-torque devices for JPL evaluation at lower
temperatures; 3) Using the new finite element algorithm, we designed a
series of USM's (1.75&quot; dia.) utilizing parametrically different materials,
teeth size and thickness, so as to validate our new design tools. Resulting
USM's demonstrated significantly higher torque than any of our prior comparable
heuristic designs (or those based on more approximating MIT Rayleigh-Ritz
vs. JPL&nbsp;FEM models). In parallel with our JPL efforts, TCA partner
QMI is now making a 3&quot; diameter motor based on the JPL reverse-stack-and-segment
design to produce a high torque USM. QMI, with JPL requirements input,
also made progress in design of generic USM drivers/amplifiers that were
successfully used to operate both commercial Shinsei and MIT prototype
R&amp;D&nbsp;lab devices. </LI>
</UL>

<H3>B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI>Complete MarsArmII fabrication, assembly, electromechanical integratation,
and instrumentation. Test MarsArmII under USM servo controls and once they
prove operational, demonstrate/evaluate the arm in application to representative
dexterous sampling tasks under sensor-referenced Cartesian controls (e.g.,
see &quot;autonomous soil science&quot; and &quot;autonomous rock science&quot;
scenarios discussed in 2q96 report). </LI>

<LI>Continue characterization of the 3-D composite process and mechanical
properties of resulting bulk quantity materials used in MarsArmII design.
</LI>

<LI>Continue SATEC chamber environmental testing in low-temperature/vacuum
regimes, including new JPL designs. </LI>
</UL>

