<a name="vtgg">

<H2> Vision and Touch Guided Grasping (MIT, Theobald) </H2>

This project conducts basic research in the area of vision and touch
guided grasping of objects.  This project encompasses the areas of
touch sensing, material property sensing, stable autonomous grasping
of objects (including buried, constrained, or moving objects), and
enhanced remote user interaction.  Our platform for testing and
development is the
<A HREF="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/wam/">WAM system</A>
with two active vision cameras.  In addition, in order to facilitate
technology transfer, we have also recently constructed the
<A HREF="http://www.ai.mit.edu/people/theo/rocky/">Rocky7 Test
System</A> which consists of a kinematically similar yet simpler
"mock-up" of the Rocky7 rover.

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events for This Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI> Ultrasound material property sensor (UMPS)
<UL>
<LI> Successfully able to identify several fluids: water, ethanol,
methanol, isopropal alcohol.
<LI> Done preliminary rock identification studies; have experimented
with two different granite rock types and have been able to
discriminate the two.
</UL>
<LI> Object Acquisition with the WAM system
<UL>
<LI> A sequence of progressively more aggressive grasping/digging
techniques has been found to be very reliable in acquiring objects
buried within heavy gravel.  This sequence includes simple
grasping, shaking while grasping, and using the fingers to dig along
the major axis of the object while grasping.
<LI> Interacting with objects which are constrained in their motion
(such as hinged doors) has begun to be studied.  Using spatial
filtering of the path of the hand, the WAM can successfully find the
path of least resistance in order to open an arbitrarily oriented
door.
<LI> Gathering of information about multiple objects in the workspace
has been implemented.  For each object a frame grab of the camera
views, its location, approximate size, orientation, and aspect ratio
are collected.  In addition, a graspability ranking is associated with
each object based upon various criteria.  This information is then
displayed to a remote operator through a graphical user interface for
selection of objects to be retrieved.
</UL>
<LI> Rocky7 Test System (Rocky7-TS) Mock-up
<UL>
<LI>The fabrication of the Rocky7-TS has been completed.
<LI>Programming of low level controllers and vision system has begun.
<LI>Work has been done on developing/choosing a control architecture,
high level behavioral control, and command scripting language.
</UL>
</UL>

<H3> B. Plans for Next Reporting Period </H3>

<UL>
<LI> Ultrasound material property sensor (UMPS)
<UL>
<LI> Build new experimental test apparatus for rocks and soils to be
placed in for identification.
<LI> Characterize various rocks: granites, sandstones, shales, etc.
</UL>
<LI> Object Acquisition with the WAM system
<UL>
<LI> Cleanup and restructuring of the active vision system control and
trajectory handling code is currently being done to facilitate further
expansion and development of the system.
<LI> Additional testing will be done in interacting with objects which
have constrained motions.
<LI> Enhancements to the user interface will be added (including
simulated haptic interaction with objects).
</UL>
<LI> Rocky7 Test System (Rocky7-TS) Mock-up
<UL>
<LI> Continue to work on developing the low level control systems,
high level architecture, and vision processing.
<LI> Implement preliminary sample acquisition with this system.
</UL>
</UL>
<P>

