<!+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++>

<a name="memit">

<H2> Mars Exploration (MIT, Brooks) </H2>

<H3> A. Activities in This Reporting Period: 
Apr to Jun 1996</H3>
     
We have been working in two areas in support of autonomous Mars 
exploration: <P>
     
<OL>
<LI>Ruggedized autonomous visual navigation for a Mars rover.
<LI>A compliant arm for the rover to carry out geological inspection tasks. 
<LI>Nano-rovers in the 10 to 30 gram range.
</OL>
     
 <P>
     
1. We completed work on the obstacle avoidance navigation system for our 
Mars micro-rover.  We carried out extensive tests of the system in our 
Lunar-sandbox at MIT, at the indoor JPL Mars-yard, and at the outdoor 
JPL Mars-yard.  The system ran in all three locations without changing 
any code or any constants.  We collected data from the test runs and
are now analyzing that data and writing up the results in a journal 
paper.  <P>
     
     
     
2. We have made operational the new four degree of freedom arm for the 
micro-rover.  Specifically we: <P>
     
<UL>
<LI> (a) designed and fabricated a scoop/gripper as an end-effector 
for the arm
<LI> (b) fabricated and debugged a new generation of servo boards 
with roughly twice the density of the first generation
<LI> (c) got the new arm running spring control code 
</UL>
     
     
3. We started a new task, building conceptual prototype nano-rovers. 
We built a 10gram mobility system, and a fully functional 30gram 
nano-rover.  The 30gram system has two motors, onboard processor,
an active power management system, a two way digital radio link,
a 160x160 pixel camera, and a solar recharging system.  We have tested 
the nano-rover in bench top conditions. <P>
     
     
<H3> B. Plans for the Next Reporting Period:
Jul to Sept 96</H3>
     
 <P>
     
<OL>
<LI> We will complete the data analysis and journal paper.  We will start 
work on a new vision task, sample selection, which will eventually be 
integrated with the navigation task.
     
<LI> We will put high level equilibrium point control on top of the newly 
working spring control.  We will commence mounting of the electronics
for the arm onboard the micro-rover.
     
<LI> We will make it so that images collected on the 30gram rover can be 
downlinked over the radio system.  We will investigate onboard image 
processing to try to identify candidate micro-fossils.  We will 
investigate new methods of locomotion for nano-rovers, including 
jumping.
</OL>


<P>
<B>Contact</B>: 
<A HREF="http://www.ai.mit.edu/people/brooks/brooks.html">
Rodney Brooks/MIT</A> (email: 
<A HREF="mailto:brooks@ai.mit.edu">brooks@ai.mit.edu</A>)

<p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="http://robotics.jpl.nasa.gov/people/hayati/Quarterly_Reports/ColorBar.GIF" 
WIDTH="638" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<p>
<pre>


