<!+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++>

<a name="rams">

<H2> MicroTelerobotics: Robot Assisted MicroSurgery (RAMS) </H2>

This task is a cooperative NASA-Industry effort to develop a telerobot for
breakthrough micro-and-minimally invasive surgeries. The resulting Robot
Assisted
Microsurgery (RAMS) workstation, via computer enhanced controls, will enable
new procedures beyond human manual dexterity, and allow a broader group of
practitioners to successfully deliver needed healthcare services at
reduced cost.
Surgical applications include the eye, ear, nose, throat, face, hand,
spine, and
brain. NASA-JPL's role is to design, fabricate, test, and document an
engineering R&D prototype -- a six degrees-of-freedom, position and force
scaling master-slave telemanipulator -- capable of relative positioning of 20
microns over a 10-to-20 cm*3 continuous volume (e.g., the eye).  The industry
partner, MicroDexterity Systems, Inc., working through independent funding,
defines medical requirements, collaborates in system engineering design,
develops and tests a pre-commercial clinical prototype, and with end market
support certifies and commercializes a final design. <P>

JPL successfully demonstrated a robot slave engineering
prototype in FY 1994, and in FY 1995, a master arm capable of simulating a
force feedback environment and manually controlling task space position of the
slave. In FY 1996, JPL will enable the handling of a surgical
instrument, demonstrate a realistic microsurgical procedure using the
telerobotic system and build a second prototype to allow external medical
laboratory testing of the RAMS technology. Further growth master-slave system
capabilities include textural
feedback at the master, and <i>in situ</i> imaging at the robot slave.
Beyond its medical significance, this new MicroTelerobotic system has potential
dual-use in ground-to-orbit and thermal-vacuum applications that include
EVA/IVA telescience and telemedicine, safe bio-and-materials processing,
micro-mechanical assembly, small-instrument servicing, and terrestrial
environmental testing. <P>

<H3> A. Significant Activities and Events </H3>
<UL>
<P>
<LI> <I>Loan of slave prototype to Cleveland Clinic: </I> Delivered and
	  installed the first prototype RAMS slave robot at the Microsurgery
	  laboratory of Dr. M. Siemionow of the Cleveland Clinic
	  Foundation. The delivered system includes a laptop and
	  joystick user interface in a stand-alone configuration requiring no
	  network interface. In addition, a cable-controlled forceps tip
	  was mounted on the robot end effector. It is controlled from
	  handles mounted on the joystick input device. Researchers at
	  the Cleveland Clinic were instructed on use of the RAMS
	  prototype system. Tests of the robot are being conducted to
	  determine its performance in a clinical setting.
<P>
<LI> <I>Second slave arm prototype:</I> Completed the fabrication,
	  assembly, integration and test of the second slave
	  prototype. The second slave prototype arm is now the robot
	  used on the RAMS system at JPL; the first prototype was
	  integrated into the system delivered to the Cleveland Clinic.
	  Design improvements in the second prototype allow more robust
	  and smoother motion in a lighter package.
<P>
<LI> <I>Microsurgery simulation: </I> Completed the design and
	  fabrication of a simulated eyeball for use in demonstration of
	  simulated microsurgery procedures. The simulated eyeball
	  realistically replicates the visual and mechanical features of
	  a real human eyeball including a retina and fluid inflation of
	  the eyeball. The simulated eyeball is free to move in its socket
	  and has the force interaction characteristics of a real
	  eyeball. Upgrades to the RAMS system for the microsurgery
	  simulation, including slave end effector instrument handling design,
	  software and hardware for indexed motion and pivoting
	  algorithms for constrained motion control, were initiated.

<P>
<LI> <I>Second master arm prototype:</I> Completed all mechanical
	  fabrication of the prototype-2 master arm. Anodizing, assembly and
	  wiring of encoders and motors are underway.
<P>
<LI> <I>External presentations: </I> Over the last quarter, the RAMS
	  system was shown to a number of visiting groups and was
	  also demonstrated as part of the JPL Open House
	  on June 8 and 9 where thousands of visitors including
	  JPL Director Ed Stone and Deputy Director Larry Dumas were
	  shown precise positioning with scaled manual control of the
	  slave robot tip tracing letters on a $20 bill.
<P>
<LI> <I>MDS Activity: </I>
<UL>
<LI> Underwent significant re-organization during this reporting
	      period. Kamran Siminou left MDS and Hal Wolbrink will be
	      joining MDS as Chief Engineer and Chief Operating Officer.

<LI> Developed a new strategic plan for commercialization of the
	      microtelerobotics technology. Ideas and components from
	      JPL, Sandia, vendors and new concepts from Steve Charles
	      and others will be incorporated in the next generation
	      system.

<LI> Continuing negotiation with Sofomor-Denek, Fischer Imaging, GE
	      Medical Systems, St Jude's hospital and Baxter Healthcare.

<LI> Begun development effort funded by ARPA Phase I SBIR award.
</UL>
<P>
</UL>

<H3> B. Plans for next reporting period </H3>
<UL>
<LI> Continue technical support of experiments at the Cleveland Clinic.
<LI> Complete development of surgical instrument for slave robot and
	  interface to the robot.
<LI> Complete development software and electronics hardware for indexed motion
	  control and shared pivoting motion control of the slave robot tip.
<LI> Test and demonstrate the RAMS system performing the simulated
	  microsurgery procedure.
<LI> Complete the assembly and test of the prototype-2 master arm.
</UL>
<H3> C. Schedule </H3> 
<IMG SRC="rams_sch.gif">

<H3> D. Concerns and Issues </H3>
<UL>
<LI> None.
</UL>

