<Title> 
Rover Based Stereo Vision
</Title>

<H1> 
Rover Stereo Vision <BR>
</H1>
<hr>
<hr>

<h3>
CALIBRATION<p>
</h3>


<IMG SRC="images/calib_left.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/calib_right.gif">

<h4>
This is an image pair from the 16 pairs that were used to 
calibrate the cameras. The fixtures are located in different
areas of the workspace of the rover, and a camera model is 
developed that captures all of the image formation geometry including
the radial distortion resulting from the short focal length lenses.
<p>

<hr>
<h3>
IMAGE WARPING<p>
</h3>

<IMG SRC="images/roverdistorted_left.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/roverdistorted_right.gif">

<h4>
<p>
Here, two of the images show a rock field with a prominent obstacle
in front of the rover. After the images are warped to remove the 
radial distortion, the resulting rectified images are suitable for
further processing for obstacle detection. 
<p>

<IMG SRC="images/roverwarped_left.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/roverwarped_right.gif">
<p>

<hr>

<h3>
ELEVATION MAP<p>
</h3>

<IMG SRC="images/gaussian_left.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/gaussian_right.gif"><br>
<IMG SRC="images/correlation.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/elevmap.gif">
<h4>
Pyramid image processing results in left and right band-pass 
filtered, low-resolution images (top left and top right). Integer
disparities are computed using a correlation window (lower left).
Subpixel disparities are computed for high-confidence disparity values 
and processed using the camera model to get an elevation map (lower right,
bright areas indicate high spots, dark areas indicate low areas or 
low-confidence regions)
<p>


<hr>
<h3>
OBSTACLE DETECTION<p>
</h3>

<IMG SRC="images/obstacledetect.gif">

<h4>
The elevation map is processed for abrupt changes in height that would
indicate regions that the rover would not be able to traverse (
outlined region). Also checked are high-centering hazards (not shown).
<p>


<hr><hr>
<p>

This work is a derivative of research conducted for the 
<a href="/tasks/ugv_stereo/homepage.html">
DoD's Unmanned Ground Vehicle Program</a>.
</DOC>
