<Title> 
Rover Visual Dig Verification
</Title>

<H1> 
Rover Visual Dig Verification<BR>
</H1>
<hr>
<hr>

<h3>
NAVIGATION CAMERAS' VIEW<p>
</h3>


<IMG SRC="images/imagepair_empty.gif">

<h4>
This is an image pair from the navigation cameras on the arm side of 
ther rover.  For these images, the scoops were empty.  The rover is
sitting on the lab floor.
<p>

<hr>
<h3>
IMAGE DIFFERENCING<p>
</h3>

<IMG SRC="images/imager_empty.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/imager_full.gif"><br>
<h4>
<p>
To detect success during digging and dumping operations, a visual 
verification is one of several checks employed.  For this operation,
the openned scoops are imaged before and after the manipulation 
operation.  Only the right images are needed, and are cropped for
the region of the scoop only.  These images show a close-up of this
region and its surroundings.  To detect the presense or absence of
soil  from the scoops after the operation, we check how many pixels
exceed an empirically determined and preset threshold in the difference of the
images.  For illustration, pixels which exceed the threshhold are 
false-colored red below.
<p>

<IMG SRC="images/imager_diff.gif">
<p>

<hr>

<p>




</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B21-104</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA044-000798-B003-318</DOCOLDNO>
