<TITLE> Lavic Lake Test Science Imaging</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#8f8fff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00ff00" VLINK="#0000ff">

<h1>Science Imaging</h1>

To improve upon imagery obtained from the rover-eye view, the mast
may be used to look down on science targets. This is usually a 
precursor to placement of the science instrument.

<hr>
<h3>Typical Positions</h3>
<a  href="images/r7sciImgDown.jpg">
<img src="images/r7sciImgDown_medium.jpg"></a>
<a  href="images/r7CUIonRock.jpg">
<img src="images/r7CUIonRock_medium.jpg"></a><p>

Note that in the left image, the stereo cameras a facing down, while
in the second image they are up.  Due to the stowage geometry,
the mast must rotate the masthead through 180 degrees between these
configurations.<p>

<hr>
