<Title> 
Rover Based Spectrometer Pointing
</Title>

<H1> 
Rover Based Spectrometer Pointing<BR>
</H1>

<a href="rover-spec-1.gif"><IMG SRC="rover-spec-1_medium.gif"></a>
<a href="rover-spec-2.gif"><IMG SRC="rover-spec-2_medium.gif"></a>
<p>


We have integrated into Rocky 7 a commercially available point reflectance
spectrometer (Ocean Optics Model S1000,
<a href="http://www.oceanoptics.com/">
Ocean Optics Inc.</a>, 1104 Pinehurst Rd, Dunedin, FL 34698). This instrument was
selected because it was readily available, relatively low cost, and is
small enough to be integrated in the current rover platform.  <P> 

The spectrometer is configured for a wavelength of 360-850nm -
primarily the visual range (400-700nm) and very-near IR. (Other ranges
are available but wavelength is limited because a silicon CCD detector
is used.)  For in-depth scientific investigation spectral information
out to the near-IR (2.5um) and thermal-IR (10um) are desirable.
However, the Ocean Optic spectrometer provides a good (and cost
effective) starting point which can be enhanced in the future.<P>

The spectrometer operates by gathering reflected light via a
collimating lens at the end of a fiber optic cable.  The reflected
light is then passed through a diffraction grating and spread out over
the 1024 linear CCD array.  For the 360-850nm this results in ~0.5nm
spectral bands.  This data is then converted to analog signals which
are read by the host computer.  <P>

The spectrometer itself is located inside the chassis of the Rocky 7
microrover. A fiber optic cable is brought out along the two degree of
freedom sampling arm.  The end of the sampling arm, consisting of a
pair of scoops, has been specially configured for the spectrometer.
The lens at the fiber optic cable is mounted on the edge of the
sampling mechanism which is specially designed only to open and expose
the spectrometer to reflected light at one special scoop position, as
seen in the photos.  A calibration target has also been integrated
into the end of the sampling arm so that a reference reading can be
taken in the same lighting conditions as the sample.<P>

<hr><p>

Some additional photos:
<ul>
<li>The Ocean Optics <a href="ocean-optics-spec.gif">spectrometer</a>.
<li>The spectrometer
    <a href="rocky-7-spec-layout.gif">location in Rocky 7</a>.
<li>The <a href="manipulator-spec-layout.gif">lightpath</a>
    through the manipulator.</a>
<li> <a href="match-database.gif">Spectra</a>
     obtained with Rocky 7 mounted Ocean Optics point spectrometer.
</ul>
