<TITLE>Mark Long'S Bio and Personal Bibliography</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Mark Long, 10-Apr-1996 -->

<H2>Mark K. Long<H2><H4>Still Under Construction<H4><p>

<HR><HR>

Mark K. Long received the B.S. degree in mechanical engineering from
Lehigh University, Bethlehem, PA, in 1987, the M.S. degree in
Mechanical Engineering from Stanford University, Stanford, CA, in
1988.  He is currently Ph.D. Candidate in mechanical engineering at
the California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA. <p>

He is currently a Member of the Technical Staff at NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.  He has published conference and journal papers in the
areas of kinematics, position control, and force control of redundant
manipulators as well as control of supervised telerobotic task
execution with time delay.  His research interests include kinematics,
dynamics, and control of electromechanical systems and real-time
robot control algorithms and architectures.<p>

At Caltech he is working with Prof. J. Burdick in the area of Computer
Aided Design of Micro-Electro-Mechanical Systems.  <p>

Prior to coming to JPL in 1988 he built a chemical feed control system for
the treatment of acid lakes for Sweetwater Technologies, completed  
finite element thermal analysis on laser transmitors as a summer intern 
at AT&T Bell labs, and completed various software jobs for Gancom, inc. <p>

He is an avid sailor having cruised throughout the west coast of the
U.S. as well as an Ocean passage to the South Pacific.
He has competed in numerous sailboat racing campaigns throughout
California on yachts from 13 to 80 feet in length.<p>


<H5>Last updated 26 September 94.</H5>

<HR><HR>

