<TITLE>Prototype Safety System for Robots Near Flight Hardware</TITLE>

<H1>
Prototype Safety System <BR> 
for Robots Near Flight Hardware
<H2> 
<p>

<H4>
<A HREF = "images/sensors.gif"><iMG SRC = "images/sensors_medium.gif"></A>
<A HREF = "images/materials.gif"><iMG SRC = "images/materials_medium.gif">
</A>
<P>
<H2>
Task Manager: <A HREF="/people/volpe/homepage.html">Richard Volpe</A>
<p>
Task dates: 10/92 - 10/93
<p>
<H4>
<DL>
<DT>Description</DT>
<DD> Select a representative sample of proximity sensors available from
commercial companies or research labs.  Also select a representative
sample of space craft surface materials.  Perform initial proximity
measurement characterization of all sensors.  Demonstrate robot
collision avoidance capability, though simple real-time experiments
with a single sensor.
</DD><P>

<DT>NASA Needs / Significance </DT>
<DD>The use of robots in near flight hardware requires collision avoidance
capability to prevent inadvertant damage to either system.
Non-contact sensing of the proximity of the flight hardware surface
position will enable the moving robot move so as to avoid contact.
</DD><P>

<DT>Status / Accomplishments </DT>
<UL>
<LI>A full spectrum of proximity sensors have been selected and tested:
    <UL>
    <LI> Intensity of reflection (infrared)
    <LI> Triangulation (infrared, visible laser)
    <LI> Time of flight (visible laser, microwave)
    <LI> Capacitive  
    <LI> Inductive
    </UL>
<LI> A full spectrum of spacecraft surface materials have been been obtained.
    <UL>
    <LI> Aluminums (bare, painted, anodized)
    <LI> Kaptons, Mylars, Teflons
    <LI> Beta Cloths
    <LI> Shuttle tiles
    <LI> etc.
    </UL>
<LI> Simple real-time controlled, robot collision avoidance has been
  demonstrated.
</UL>
</DD>
</DL>



<H4>
Resultant Publications: <P>

<I>
R. Volpe and R. Ivlev.  "A Survey and Experimental Evaluation of
Proximity Sensors for Space Robotics".  In The IEEE International
Conference on Robotics and Automation, San Diego, CA, May 1994.
<A HREF="/people/volpe/papers/pssra.ps.gz">postscript</A> (8 pages, 250K)
<P>

R. Volpe and R. Ivlev. "Year End Task Report of The Prototype Safety
System for Robots Near Flight Hardware".  Internal Engineering
Memorandum 3474-93-006, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Pasadena, CA,
October 1993.
<A HREF="/people/volpe/papers/pss_eoy.ps.gz">postscript</A> (34 pages, 511K)

</I>
<P>

