<TITLE> STAR: Satellite Test Assistant Robot
</TITLE>

<H1> STAR: Satellite Test Assistant Robot</h1>
<H2> 
A Robotic Inspection System for Thermal/Vacuum Environments<h2>
<p>
<A HREF="images/STAR_pic1.gif"><IMG SRC="images/STAR_pic1_medium.gif"></A>
<p>

<H4>
Current Task Members:
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="/people/mcaffee/homepage.html">
     Doug McAffee [task manager]</A>
<LI> <A HREF="/people/long/homepage.html">Mark Long</A>
</UL>


<H2>Technical Objectives:</H2>

The objective of this work element is to use telerobotic technology to
assist engineers as they ground test satellites or spacecraft in the
large Space Simulation Chambers at JPL. Inside these test chambers
spacecraft are exposed to extremely cold temperatures, high vacuum,
and simulated sunlight thereby approximating a space-like
environment. This project calls for the development and demonstration
of a mobile, multi-axis, multi-camera, telerobotic inspection system
that will be deployed inside the thermal/vacuum test chambers and
provide test operators with live high-resolution mono and stereoscopic
video and real-time infrared thermal imaging of the spacecraft article
under test. This will augment and improve current test procedures. The
STAR IR camera may also be employed to calibrate solar flux
intensities across the entire chamber volume. The anticipated cost
savings and technical enhancements provided by these capabilities will
be assessed.


<h2>Approach:</H2>

STAR is a three year development effort that began in 1992. During the
first year an initial three-axis configuration of STAR was built and
demonstrated in ambient conditions. It consisted of a 25-foot vertical
axis, a pan/tilt unit, and a general purpose instrument platform
equipped with three high-resolution CCD cameras, one having a zoom
lens. Mono and stereoscopic viewing of a spacecraft mock-up was
demonstrated on a rudimentary operator control station (OCS).

The STAR design was validated in 1993 by successfully undergoing more
than 50 hours of rigorous thermal/vacuum testing in the 10-Foot
Chamber in a joint test conducted with hardware being developed for
JPL's Cassini Spacecraft. The vertical axis had been modified and an
IR Camera had been added to the instrument payload, providing vivid
thermal images of the Cassini hardware and introducing a non-contact
measurement capability inside the chamber.

In 1994 a 25 ft. diameter azimuthal axis gantry system will be
designed to permit full lateral motion around the inside diameter of
JPL's 25-Foot Space Simulation Chamber. STAR's Operator Control
Station (OCS) will also be upgraded and enhanced to provide a
user-friendly graphical interface, position data logging and automated
test sequences.

The funding for this task is currently planned through end of FY'94. 

<h4>Planned Milestones:</h4>
<UL>
<LI>Sept 92 - Demonstrate 3-Axis Configuration and Stereo Viewing </LI>
<LI>Sept 93 - Develop OSC, Conduct Thermal/Vacuum Test, Demonstrate 
 IR Capabilities</LI>
<LI>Sept 94 - Develop 25 ft. Dia Azimuthal Gantry Design, Conduct 
Second Thermal/Vacuum Demonstration Test and Refined OCS</LI>
</UL>

Accomplishments:
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="accomplishments/system/star-system.html">
     STAR: Satellite Test Assistant Robot System</A>
<LI> <A HREF="accomplishments/infrared/star-infrared.html">
     STAR: Infrared Thermal Imaging System</A>
</UL>

Point of Contact: Douglas McAffee (818) 354-1740

