<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>A Complaint About Many HTML Documents</TITLE>

</HEAD>

</BODY>

The following text is a copy of a form letter that I have been sending to
more and more authors of Web pages. Read it and you will see why I think
there is a problem.

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<LISTING>

I am writing to notify you of a misuse of HTML in your Web page which makes
that page virtually unreadable to some people, myself included. The error
relates to your use of a directive like

	<<CODE>body bgcolor=#ffffff</CODE>>
or
	<<CODE>body background=/bright-image.jpg</CODE>>

to override the default background color of the document. The problem with
these directives is that they assume that all users have light backgrounds with
dark letters on top. If, like me, they normally have a dark background with
light letters, then those foreground letters will likely be hard to see over
your chosen background color.

What to do? Must you give up designating a background color that you think
looks good? No. You need merely do more than just define the background that
you want. You must define all of the foreground colors as well. Look at this
example taken from the Alta Vista home page (http://www.altavista.digital.com/)
for a way to do it right:

	<<CODE>body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ee"
		vlink="551a8b" alink="ff0000"</CODE>>

Here the following colors are defined:

	bgcolor	- background
	text	- normal text
	link	- link which has never been visited
	vlink	- link which has been visited
	alink	- link which is active (in the process of being visited)

If you will go to the effort to define all of these items instead of merely the
background, many more people will be able to read your Web page.

On the other hand, I would encourage you to consider refraining from doing any
overriding of user colors (background or foreground) unless you have a very
good reason. Those of us who have chosen to go to the effort to define our own
background and foreground colors for net browsing, have done so for very good
reasons. My own reason is that I find the bright backgrounds very hard on my
eyes. I cannot look at them for long periods of time without experiencing
increasing levels of discomfort and fatigue. So I am generally annoyed when the
author of a page has chosen to override my choices. In a very few cases there
are good reasons for this. These I don't mind. But in the vast majority of
cases the Web-page author is simply imposing his sense of aesthetics on me for
no good reason. Please exercise restraint in this matter.

Thank you.

</LISTING>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

If you would like to read some more on this subject, here is
<A HREF="http://www.qucis.queensu.ca/home/benoit/courses/critique.html">
some theory to back it up</A>.

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B21-135</DOCNO>
