<Title> Exploration of Small Bodies </Title>

<IMG SRC="./images/full-2.gif">

<H1>EXPLORATION OF SMALL BODIES</H1>

<HR>

Of the 15 Discovery proposals submitted by JPL in 1994, six were 
destined for small bodies, and three included plans to obtain samples from 
the surfaces of those bodies. Landing and operation in the low 
gravity environments of small bodies is an extremely challenging problem
and requires technology development in a variety of areas to ensure these 
missions are a success. The Exploration 
of Small Bodies task is therefore focusing on developing the technologies 
enabling in-situ scientific studies of these interplanetary objects.  This
multi-year task will explore three key technology areas: <P>
<UL>
<LI> Surface and Subsurface Sampling - The gathering of surface and 
subsurface samples for scientific exploration will be an important
part of any mission.  Low mass/power mechanims for sample acquisition will 
be explored as well as concurrent development of sensors and control 
methods enabling autonomous operation in materials of unknown 
compositions.  <P>
<LI> Sample Manipulation - Once a sample is acquired, it must be delivered
to on-board science instruments for in-situ analysis.  Systems for sample
handling and sample preparation for a microgravity enviroment will therefore 
be developed.<P>
<LI> Landing and Anchoring - The low-gravity environment of small bodies
allows for free-fall and unpowered landing but requires ways of absorbing
impact engery as well as attaching the lander to the surface to react
sampling forces.  Passive energy absorbtion systems such as crushable 
materials will be explored as well as anchoring systems such as rocket
deployed spikes.<P>
</UL>

In FY '95 work began (under the Remote Scientist task) to develop 
and test sampling systems specific to comets to meet the technology 
needs of the JPL/CNES Champollion comet lander (ESA Rosetta mission).
The comet sampling system is required to gather several cm3 of material 
from up to a 
meter beneath a comet's surface and deliver that sample to multiple 
on-board instruments within an extremely challenging mass/power budget.
A prototype system is being developed which incorporates multiple sensors 
not only allowing
autonomous operation but also gathering data on material
properties as sampling is done.  A cryogenic test chamber is also being
assembled enabling testing of a prototype sampling system in cryogenic comet
facsimile materials of various densities.<P>

<HR>
<H2><A href="./fy95-report/report.html">FY '95 Summary Report</A></H2>
<HR>

Contacts: <BR>
Don Sevilla - Donald.R.Sevilla@jpl.nasa.gov<BR>
<A href="../homepage.html">Rick Welch</A> - Richard.V.Welch@jpl.nasa.gov<P>
<HR>

Last updated: 5/12/95<P>

