<TITLE>KSC LOCAL-REMOTE TELEROBOTIC INSPECTION</TITLE>

<H1>KSC Local-Remote Telerobotic Inspection</H1>

<H2> A telerobotic inspection of a PAM-D booster rocket was
implemented using JPL as the primary operator local site control
station and NASA, Kennedy Space Center as the remote site where the
robot inspection was executed</H1>

<a href="images/ksc-inspection.gif">
<IMG SRC="images/ksc-inspection_medium.gif"></a>

<H3>The local-remote telerobotic inspection of a PAM-D booster rocket
mounted in a Shuttle payload cradle was the first major demonstration
of precise autonomous control of a robot under substantial time delay.
With JPL acting as the Earth based local site, and KSC acting as the
on-orbit Space Station inspection site, the total communication time
delay was on the order of 2-3 seconds.  This demonstration was
considered the first major step towards developing the robot control
architecture that would enable safe, reliable servicing of Space
Station from the ground; therefore, saving a significant amount of
on-orbit EVA astronaut hours.
<p>

The payload cradle represented a realistic obstacle environment for
the robotic inspection system.  Three inspection sites were selected
to test the robot control and imaging system.  A 12ft ASEA IRB90 robot
arm stationed on a 30ft track was outfitted with a custom end-effector
composed of a set of Hitachi KP-140 stereo cameras mounted on a
horizontal fixture.  A uVax computer platform was used to grab,
compress images from the cameras, and forward robot motion commands to
the robot controller.  The KSC uVax was connected to the JPL uVax via
a commercial serial link.  The Symbolics operator workstation at JPL
was linked to the JPL uVax via a DECNET point-to-point
connection. Using a CAD model of the booster and Shuttle cradle, the
operator at JPL selected inspection sites for the robot end- effector
to reach by highlighting the position with a cursor.  An AI based path
planner was then executed to identify the optimal trajectory and robot
arm configuration to avoid hitting any part of the cradle or other
booster related components.  Once an appropriate trajectory was
determined, the robot end point and joint control parameters were
forwarded to the KSC robot 3000 miles away for execution.  Because of
the time delay, the AI path planner and simulator were essential to
insuring safe negotiation of obstacles.  Once the the robot reached
the correct site, images of the inspection site were sent back to the
JPL workstation.  Using a graphic overlay of the correct conponent
configuration over the stereo image, the operator was able to inspect
for damage or missing/disconnected components.  The joint KSC/JPL
robot teams were successful in executing the series of inspection
tasks without one collision incident.
<p>

<blockquote> 
Sklar, M., et.al., "An Advanced Telerobotic System for
Shuttle Payload Changeout Room Processing Applications," McDonnell
Douglas Space Systems, NASA KSC, and JPL, January 1989.
</blockquote> 

Contact: Wayne Zimmerman, JPL, (818) 354-0234
zimmermana@telerobotics.jpl.nasa.gov</H4>
        



</DOC>
